[Event "King & Pawn vs King: Rule of the SQUARE"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName "Rule of the SQUARE"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/g8IZnQE2"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/6k1/1P6/6K1/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The SQUARE is a geometrical hint to determine whether a king can stop a passed pawn or not.

We draw a square with corners including the square where the pawn is (b4) and the promotion square (b8). We complete the square towards the side the king is (in this case to the right).

RULE: the king must be INSIDE the square to stop the pawn.

Therefore in this position:
- if white moves, white wins
- if black moves, it's a draw

Push the pawn! } { [%csl Gb4,Gb8,Gf4,Gf8,Rg5][%cal Gb4b8,Bb4f8,Gb8f8,Gf8b8,Gb8b4,Gf4b4,Gb4f4,Gf8f4,Gf4f8] }
1. b5 { The square gets smaller each step the pawn is pushed, so the king can never enter } { [%csl Ge5,Gb5,Gb8,Ge8,Rg5][%cal Gc8e8,Gc8b8,Gb7b8,Gb7b5,Ge7e8,Ge7e5,Gd5e5,Gd5b5] } 1... Kf5 { Keep pushing to promote! } { [%csl Ge5,Gb5,Gb8,Ge8,Rf5][%cal Ge7e8,Ge7e5,Gd5e5,Gd5b5,Gb7b8,Gb7b5,Gc8e8,Gc8b8] } 2. b6 { [%csl Gd6,Gb6,Gb8,Gd8,Rf5][%cal Gc8d8,Gc8b8,Gb7b8,Gb7b6,Gc6d6,Gc6b6,Gd7d8,Gd7d6] } 2... Ke6 { [%csl Gd6,Gb6,Re6,Gd8,Gb8][%cal Gb7b8,Gb7b6,Gc6d6,Gc6b6,Gd7d8,Gd7d6,Gc8d8,Gc8b8] } 3. b7 { [%csl Gb7,Gc7,Gc8,Gb8,Re6][%cal Gb7b8,Gb8b7,Gb7c7,Gc7b7,Gc7c8,Gc8c7,Gc8b8,Gb8c8] } 3... Kd7 { [%csl Rd7,Gc7,Gb7,Gb8,Gc8][%cal Gc7c8,Gc8c7,Gc7b7,Gb7c7,Gb7b8,Gb8b7,Gb8c8,Gc8b8] } 4. b8=Q { [%csl Gb8,Rd7] } (4. b8=R { Sure that also wins, but I mean ... 🙃 }) *


