[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]

{ This is the only exceptional case with the rule of the square. When the pawn is on the starting position (2nd rank), given that the pawn can move 2 squares instead of 1, the square is one step smaller.

For example, in this position, it's black's to move but they lose anyway: } { [%csl Ga3,Ga8,Gf8,Gf3,Rg8,Rg2,Ra2][%cal Gb3a3,Ga4a3,Ga4a8,Gb8a8,Gb8f8,Gb3f3,Gf4f3,Gf4f8,Rg7g8,Rg7g2,Rf2g2,Rf2a2] }
1... Kg5 { [%csl Gf3,Ga3,Ga8,Gf8,Rg5][%cal Gb3a3,Ga4a3,Ga4a8,Gb8a8,Gb8f8,Gf7f8,Gf7f3,Gb3f3] } 2. a4 { [%csl Ga4,Ga8,Ge8,Ge4,Rg5][%cal Gd4e4,Gd4a4,Ga5a4,Ga5a8,Gb8a8,Gb8e8,Ge7e8,Ge7e4] } (2. a3?? { this of course would be a terrible mistake } { [%csl Ra3,Ra8,Rf3,Rf8,Gg5][%cal Rb3a3,Ra4a3,Ra4a8,Rb3f3,Rf4f3,Rf4f8,Re8f8,Re8a8] } 2... Kf5 { entering the square. Draw } { [%csl Gf5,Ra3,Ra8,Rf8,Rf3][%cal Re3f3,Re3a3,Ra4a3,Ra4a8,Rb8a8,Rb8f8,Rf7f8,Rf7f3] }) 2... Kf6 { [%csl Rf6,Ga4,Ga8,Ge8,Ge4][%cal Gd4e4,Gd4a4,Ga5a4,Ga5a8,Gb8a8,Gb8e8,Ge7e8,Ge7e4] } 3. a5 { [%csl Rf6,Ga5,Ga8,Gd8,Gd5][%cal Gc5d5,Gc5a5,Ga6a5,Ga6a8,Gb8a8,Gb8d8,Gd7d8,Gd7d5] } 3... Ke6 { [%csl Re6,Gd5,Gd8,Ga8,Ga5][%cal Gd6d5,Gd6d8,Gc8d8,Gc8a8,Ga7a8,Ga7a5,Gb5a5,Gb5d5] } 4. a6 { [%csl Ga6,Ga8,Gc8,Gc6,Re6][%cal Gb6c6,Gb6a6,Ga7a6,Ga7a8,Gb8a8,Gb8c8,Gc7c8,Gc7c6] } 4... Kd6 { [%csl Rd6,Gc6,Ga6,Ga8,Gc8][%cal Gc7c8,Gc7c6,Ga7a6,Ga7a8,Gb8a8,Gb8c8,Gb6c6,Gb6a6] } 5. a7 { [%csl Ga7,Ga8,Gb8,Gb7,Rd6][%cal Ga7b7,Gb7a7,Ga8a7,Ga7a8,Ga8b8,Gb8a8,Gb8b7,Gb7b8] } 5... Kc7 { [%csl Rc7,Ga7,Gb7,Gb8,Ga8][%cal Gb8b7,Gb7b8,Ga8a7,Ga7a8,Ga8b8,Gb8a8,Ga7b7,Gb7a7] } 6. a8=Q { [%csl Ga8,Rc7] } *


[Event "King & Pawn vs King: OPPOSITION"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName "OPPOSITION"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/8WyNhQ6n"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "4k3/8/8/4PK2/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The OPPOSITION is a basic technique for most endgames involving kings.
White wins here using it! } { [%cal Gf5e6] }
1. Ke6! { This is called OPPOSITION: kings in front of each other so they're fighting for the same 3 squares (in blue).
The king that is forced to move (black king) is said to LOSE THE OPPOSITION, allowing the other king to access one of those 3 squares.
We say that the move Ke6 WINS THE OPPOSITION. } { [%csl Ge6,Re8,Bd7,Be7,Bf7] } 1... Kf8 { Gives access to the d7 square. } { [%csl Gd7] } (1... Kd8 { Gives access to the f7 square. } { [%csl Gf7] } 2. Kf7 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5e6,Ge6e7,Ge7e8] }) 2. Kd7 { And now the pawn can be pushed all the way, as all the squares are protected by the king. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Ge5e6,Ge6e7,Ge7e8] } *


[Event "King & Pawn vs King: >>>> Distant opposition"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName ">>>> Distant opposition"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/FXFKFxEN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/1kp5/8/8/8/K7 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ White to move and draw.

To win the opposition we would need to play Kb3, but we can't.

However, we can use the so-called DISTANT OPPOSITION. Can you guess where to move the king? } { [%csl Bb3] }
1. Kb1! { Bravo!
The kings are competing for the blue squares from a distance.
If the black king enters one of the yellow squares, white has a square for his king to win the opposition.
So here too, black LOST THE OPPOSITION (the distant one). } { [%csl Gb1,Rb5,Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Ya4,Yb4,Yc4,Yc2,Yb2,Ya2] } (1. Kb2?? { This would lose the opposition and the game: } { [%csl Rb2,Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Gb4][%cal Gb5b4] } 1... Kb4! { and we will lose } { [%csl Gb4,Rb2,Ba3,Bb3,Bc3] }) (1. Ka2?? { This would lose the opposition and the game: } { [%csl Ra2,Ga4,Ba3,Bb3][%cal Gb5a4] } 1... Ka4! { and we will inevitably lose } { [%csl Ba3,Bb3,Ra2,Ga4] }) 1... Kb4 { How do you draw now? } 2. Kb2! { [%csl Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Rb4,Gb2] } 2... Kc4 3. Kc2 { Well done! } { [%csl Gc2,Rc4,Bb3,Bc3,Bd3] } *


[Event "King & Pawn vs King: >>>> Reserve moves and opposition"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName ">>>> Reserve moves and opposition"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/SX7415dj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5k2/8/8/8/8/8/4PK2/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Let's see this example where kings are far from each other to illustrate a new concept: RESERVE MOVES.

All the blue moves win, but let's do the green one, as we need to get used to walking our king in front of the pawn.

Note any pawn push only leads to a draw. } { [%cal Gf2e3,Bf2f3,Bf2g2,Bf2g3] }
1. Ke3 (1. Kf3 { Yes, it also wins, but let's do Ke3 instead please :-) }) (1. Kg3 { Yes, it also wins, but let's do Ke3 instead please :-) }) (1. Kg2 { Yes, it also wins, but let's do Ke3 instead please :-) }) (1. Kg1?? { This is a draw now! } { [%cal Gf8e7] }) (1. Kf1?? { This is a draw now! } { [%cal Gf8e7] }) (1. Ke1?? { This is a draw now! } { [%cal Gf8e7] }) (1. e3?? { This is a draw now! } { [%cal Gf8e7] }) (1. e4?? { This is a draw now! } { [%cal Gf8e7] }) 1... Ke7 { Black wins the distant opposition, but that's fine, you'll see :-)
Again other moves win, but let's push the king to e4, the most natural move. } { [%csl Ge7,Re3,Bd5,Be5,Bf5][%cal Ge3e4] } 2. Ke4 (2. Kd2?? { This is a draw now! } { [%cal Ge7e6] }) (2. Kf2?? { This is a draw now! }) (2. Kd4 { Yes, it also wins, but let's go Ke4 instead :-) }) (2. Kf4 { Yes, it also wins, but let's go Ke4 instead :-) }) (2. Kf3 { Yes, it also wins, but let's go Ke4 instead :-) }) (2. Kd3 { Yes, it also wins, but let's go Ke4 instead :-) }) 2... Ke6 { It wins the opposition for black, but now white has a RESERVE MOVE with the pawn. } { [%csl Bd5,Be5,Bf5,Ge6,Re4][%cal Ge2e3] } 3. e3 { Yes!
Regaining the opposition. White wins.
This important concept (RESERVE MOVES) suggests we generally should move the king up before the pawn, to keep reserve moves at our disposal. } { [%csl Ge4,Re6,Bd5,Be5,Bf5] } (3. Kd4 { Yes, it also wins, but let's go e3 instead :-) }) (3. Kf4 { Yes, it also wins, but let's go e3 instead :-) }) (3. Kd3?? { Noooo, you definitely lost the opposition. This is a draw. } { [%csl Rd3,Bc4,Bd4,Be4][%cal Ge6d5] }) (3. Kf3?? { Noooo, you definitely lost the opposition. This is a draw. } { [%csl Be4,Bf4,Bg4,Rf3][%cal Ge6f5] }) (3. Ke3?? { Noooo, you definitely lost the opposition. This is a draw. } { [%csl Re3,Bd4,Be4,Bf4][%cal Ge6e5] }) 3... Kd6 { Ok, before we move on let's practice what we learned. How would you continue? } 4. Kf5 { Nicely done! } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Ge5e6] } (4. Kd3?? { Draw } { [%cal Gd6e5] }) (4. Kf3?? { Draw }) (4. Kd4 { It wins too, but it's not the most straightforward. Try again. }) (4. Kf4 { It wins too, but it's not the most straightforward. Try again. }) 4... Ke7 5. Ke5! { Yes! It was the only way, we use the OPPOSITION of course. } { [%csl Ge5,Re7,Bd6,Be6,Bf6] } (5. e4?? { Nooooo } { [%csl Rf5,Be6,Bf6,Bg6][%cal Ge7f7] } 5... Kf7! { [%csl Gf7,Rf5,Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } 6. Ke5 Ke7 { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6,Ge7,Re5] }) (5. Ke4?? { Nooooo } { [%csl Re4,Bd5,Be5,Bf5][%cal Ge7e6] }) (5. Kf4?? { Nooooo } { [%csl Be5,Bf5,Bg5,Rf4][%cal Ge7f6] }) (5. Kg4?? { Nooooo } { [%cal Ge7e6] }) (5. Kg5?? { Nooooo } { [%cal Ge7e6] }) (5. Kg6?? { Nooooo } { [%cal Ge7e6] }) 5... Kd7 6. Kf6 { Good job!
The pawn has a way up secured. We just need to be careful not to push it too much too soon. } { [%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Ge5e6,Ge6e7] } (6. e4?? { Ooops! It's a draw now. } { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6,Re5][%cal Gd7e7] }) (6. Kd4?? { Ooops! It's a draw now. } { [%csl Bc5,Bd5,Be5,Rd4][%cal Gd7d6] }) (6. Ke4?? { Ooops! It's a draw now. } { [%csl Re4,Bd5,Be5,Bf5][%cal Gd7e6] }) (6. Kf4 { Luckily this odd move also wins, but please find a more straightforward one :-) }) (6. Kd5 { This also wins, but it takes longer. Please find a more straightforward way :-) }) (6. Kf5 { This also wins, but it takes a bit longer. Please find a more straightforward way :-) }) 6... Kd8 7. e4 (7. Kg7?? { Awesome! You found the only move in the position that doesn't win 🙃 }) (7. Ke6 { Correct, but push the pawn instead. }) (7. Kf7 { Correct, but push the pawn instead. }) (7. Ke5 { Just push the pawn instead please :-) }) (7. Kf5 { Just push the pawn instead please :-) }) (7. Kg5 { Just push the pawn instead please :-) }) (7. Kg6 { Just push the pawn instead please :-) }) 7... Ke8 { What now? } 8. Ke6 { Bravo!
We use the OPPOSITION again to secure the victory. } { [%csl Ge6,Re8,Bd7,Be7,Bf7] } (8. e5! { Now you're either being clever or you just made a mistake...
This move also wins, but you actually LOST THE OPPOSITION.
The reason it wins has nothing to do with the opposition and you only win because you got the pawn to the 5th rank. We will study this later, but now we're practicing the opposition so please find the other winning move :-) } { [%csl Be7,Bf7,Bg7,Rf6][%cal Ge8f8] } 8... Kf8 9. e6 Ke8 10. e7 { [%csl Re8][%cal Re8d7] } 10... Kd7 11. Kf7 { [%cal Ge7e8] }) (8. Ke5?? { Really? 🤦 } { [%csl Re5,Bd6,Be6,Bf6][%cal Ge8e7] }) (8. Kg7?? { Really? 🤦 } { [%cal Ge8e7] }) (8. Kg6?? { Really? 🤦 } { [%cal Ge8e7] }) (8. Kf5?? { Really? 🤦 } { [%csl Gf5,Be6,Bf6,Bg6][%cal Ge8f7] }) (8. Kg5?? { Really? 🤦 } { [%cal Ge8e7] }) 8... Kf8 9. Kd7 { Awesome! } { [%cal Ge4e5,Ge5e6,Ge6e7,Ge7e8] } (9. Ke5?? { I can't believe you right now 🤦 } { [%csl Re5,Bd6,Be6,Bf6][%cal Gf8e7] }) (9. Kf5?? { I can't believe you right now 🤦 } { [%csl Rf5,Be6,Bf6,Bg6][%cal Gf8f7] }) (9. Kf6 { It does win (obviously?) but we're walking in circles here (Ke8, Ke6, Kf8).
Find a more straightforward way to make progress. }) (9. Kd6 { It does win, but it takes longer.
Find a more straightforward way to make progress. }) (9. Kd5 { It does win, but it takes longer.
Find a more straightforward way to make progress. }) (9. e5! { Now you're either being clever or you just made a mistake...
This move also wins, but you actually LOST THE OPPOSITION.
The reason it wins has nothing to do with the opposition and you only win because you got the pawn to the 5th rank. We will study this later, but now we're practicing the opposition so please find the other winning move :-) } { [%csl Re6,Bf7,Be7,Bd7][%cal Gf8e8] }) 9... Kf7 10. e5 { Great job. Let's stop this exercise here, because the next 3 moves are obvious :-) } { [%cal Ge5e6,Ge6e7,Ge7e8] } (10. Kd8?? { Whaaaaat? 🤦 } { [%cal Gf7e6] }) (10. Kc8?? { Whaaaaat? 🤦 }) (10. Kc7?? { Whaaaaat? 🤦 }) (10. Kc6?? { Whaaaaat? 🤦 }) (10. Kd6 { Winning too, but walking in circles. There's a more direct move :-) }) *


[Event "King & Pawn vs King: KEY SQUARES"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName "KEY SQUARES"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/OHGd4GB1"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "6k1/8/8/8/4PK2/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We call KEY SQUARES those squares a piece of the strong side has to reach to be able to win. In many endgames, KEY SQUARES can be determined so we can easily know the winning method.

For example, in this position, if the white's king reaches one of the blue squares, white will win.
That gives us the winning method: Ke5 and Kd6. } { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6] }
1. Ke5 { Correct!
On our way to d6, which can't be stopped. } { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6][%cal Ge5d6] } 1... Kf7 { [%csl Bf6,Be6,Bd6] } 2. Kd6 { Note that knowing the KEY SQUARES simplifies our calculations a lot, so that's how we will study many endgames (you study what the KEY SQUARES are rather than studying all the options move by move). } { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Gd6][%cal Ge4e5,Ge5e6] } *


