[Event "King & Pawn vs King: Always in front of the pawn"]
[Date "2022.06.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName "Always in front of the pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/E2xUo1Ie"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/3k4/4p3/4K3/8/8/8 w - - 3 2"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.06.11"]
[UTCTime "03:11:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We know this is a draw because the opponent's king is not in front of their pawn.

The easiest way to draw is this: whenever possible, we'll have our king in either of the 2 squares in front of the pawn.

Make your move :-) } { [%csl Be4,Be3] }
2. Ke3 (2. Kd3 { It also draws, but this doesn't always work (it wouldn't work in the backrank) and the easiest that ALWAYS works is to keep the king in front of the pawn instead. Please do that :-) }) (2. Kf3 { It also draws, but this doesn't always work (it wouldn't work in the backrank) and the easiest that ALWAYS works is to keep the king in front of the pawn instead. Please do that :-) }) (2. Kf5?? { Lol, what are you doing? 🙈 }) 2... Kd5 { Uh oh, we can't keep the king in those 2 squares in front of the pawn.
We need to do something else, what do we do? 🤔 } { [%csl Re4,Ge3] } 3. Kd3 { Correct! We use the OPPOSITION to prevent the other king from passing.
So that's all you need to know for this technique:
1) Keep the king in those 2 squares in front of the pawn when possible
2) When not possible, use the OPPOSITION to keep the other king away } { [%csl Gd3,Rd5,Bc4,Bd4,Be4] } (3. Kd2?? { [%cal Gd5d4] }) (3. Ke2?? { [%cal Gd5e4] }) (3. Kf2?? { [%cal Gd5d4] }) (3. Kf3?? { [%cal Gd5d4] }) 3... e4+ { Tricky players will just move back and forth with their king to confuse you, but let's see the most direct line when they push the pawn.
Where do you put the king now? } 4. Ke3 { Correct!
Both e3 and e2 are great squares, but I like e3 the most, not giving the opponent absolutely any hope of progress :-) } { [%csl Ge2,Ge3] } (4. Ke2 { Yes!
This is perfectly fine, but I just picked e3 instead, because I feel it's just more annoying. } { [%csl Ge2,Ge3] }) (4. Kd2 { Well, you're lucky this is still a draw, but it's the wrong technique and if you do it in the backrank you would lose.
So please, let's stick to the plan: king in front of the pawn :-) } { [%csl Rd2] }) (4. Kc3 { Well, you're lucky this is still a draw, but it's the wrong technique and if you do it in the backrank you would lose.
So please, let's stick to the plan: king in front of the pawn :-) }) (4. Kc2 { Well, you're lucky this is still a draw, but it's the wrong technique and if you do it in the backrank you would lose.
So please, let's stick to the plan: king in front of the pawn :-) }) 4... Ke5 5. Ke2 { Of course! } (5. Kf2 { It also draws, but this doesn't always work (it wouldn't work in the backrank) and the easiest that ALWAYS works is to keep the king in front of the pawn instead. Please do that :-) }) (5. Kd2 { It also draws, but this doesn't always work (it wouldn't work in the backrank) and the easiest that ALWAYS works is to keep the king in front of the pawn instead. Please do that :-) }) 5... Kf4 { Can't keep the king in those 2 squares again... what do we use? } { [%csl Re3,Ge2] } 6. Kf2 { OPPOSITION! 💪 } (6. Kf1?? { Noooo, you lose now! } { [%cal Gf4f3] }) (6. Ke1?? { Noooo, you lose now! } { [%cal Gf4e3] }) (6. Kd1?? { Noooo, you lose now! } { [%cal Gf4f3] }) (6. Kd2?? { Noooo, you lose now! } { [%cal Gf4f3] }) 6... e3+ 7. Ke2 (7. Ke1) (7. Kg2?? { Lol, what are you doing? 🙈 } { [%cal Gf4e4] }) (7. Kf1?? { [%cal Gf4f3] }) (7. Kg1?? { Lol, what are you doing? 🙈 } { [%cal Gf4g3] }) 7... Ke4 8. Ke1 (8. Kd1?? { [%cal Ge4d3] }) (8. Kf1?? { [%cal Ge4f3] }) 8... Kd3 9. Kd1 (9. Kf1?? { [%cal Gd3d2] }) 9... e2+ 10. Ke1 (10. Kc1?? { Lol, what are you doing? 🙈 } { [%cal Ge2e1] }) 10... Ke3 { Stalemate! } *


