{ Remember what are the KEY SQUARES.
We must keep White's king away from them. }
1... Kf7! { Of course, we use the DISTANT OPPOSITION. } { [%csl Bd5,Bc5,Bb5][%cal Gg8f7,Gf7e6,Rf4f7,Rf4f1] } (1... Kf8!? { Funnily this also draws, but it's not the most "correct" way :-) } 2. Kf2 (2. Ke2 Ke8 { [%csl Ge2,Re8] } 3. Kd3 Kd7 { [%csl Bb5,Bc5,Bd5] }) (2. Ke1 Ke7) 2... Ke7 3. Ke3 { [%csl Gc3,Ge3][%cal Ge3c3,Gc3e3] } 3... Kd7 { [%csl Rc3][%cal Ge3d3,Gd3c3] } 4. Kd3 { [%csl Rc3] } (4. Kd4 Kd6) 4... Kc7 { Using White's pawn to regain the opposition. } { [%csl Rc3,Bb5,Bc5,Bd5][%cal Gc7c3] } 5. Kc4 Kc6 { [%csl Gc6,Rc4,Bb5,Bc5,Bd5] }) (1... Kg7?? { Noooo } { [%cal Gf1e2] }) (1... Kh8?? { What are you doing?? 🙈 }) (1... Kh7?? { What are you doing?? 🙈 }) 2. Ke2 { [%csl Bd5,Bc5,Bb5] } 2... Ke6 { [%csl Bd5,Bc5,Bb5][%cal Re4e6,Re4e2] } (2... Ke7 { Also works, but let's stick to the method :-) } { [%cal Gf7e6] }) (2... Ke8 { Fun move! This SUPER-DISTANT OPPOSITION also works here, but it's easier on e6. } { [%csl Bd5,Bc5,Bb5] }) 3. Kd3 { [%csl Bd5,Bc5,Bb5] } 3... Kd5 { Well done!
That king is going nowhere near those KEY SQUARES. } { [%csl Gd3,Bb5,Bc5,Bd5][%cal Rd4d5,Rd4d3] } *


[Event "King & Pawn vs King: White to play and draw"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "King & Pawn vs King"]
[ChapterName "White to play and draw"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9/OsmqINms"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/4p3/3k4/5P2/8/8/2K5 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "11:40:20"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Uh oh, We're losing that pawn for sure!

And the pawn is right on one of the KEY SQUARES of the remaining pawn.
So basically when Kxf4 happens, Black will be winning.

Is there anything at all we can do? 🤔 } { [%csl Ge6,Bd4,Be4,Bf4][%cal Rd5f4] }
1. f5!! { Awesome!!
Forcing White to capture with the pawn, thus moving the key squares one rank down the board! } { [%csl Bd4,Be4,Bf4] } (1. Kd2?? { [%csl Bd4,Be4,Bf4] } 1... Ke4 { [%csl Bd4,Be4,Bf4] } 2. Ke2 { [%csl Bd4,Be4,Bf4] } 2... Kxf4 { [%csl Be4,Bd4,Gf4] } 3. Kf2 Ke4 4. Ke2 { [%cal Ge6e5] } 4... e5 { Black wins } { [%csl Bd3,Be3,Bf3,Ge4,Re2] }) (1. Kd1?? { [%csl Bd4,Be4,Bf4] } 1... Ke4 { [%csl Bf4,Be4,Bd4] } 2. Ke2 { [%csl Bd4,Be4,Bf4] } (2. f5 Kxf5) 2... Kxf4 { [%csl Gf4,Be4,Bd4] } 3. Kf2 Ke4 4. Ke2 { [%cal Ge6e5] } 4... e5 { Black wins } { [%csl Bd3,Be3,Bf3,Ge4,Re2] }) 1... exf5 { Now we're in time to use the OPPOSITION to keep Black's king away from the key squares :-) } { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3][%cal Bd4e3,Be4f3,Bf4g3] } (1... e5 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5f8,Rd5e6] } 2. f6 { [%cal Gf6f8,Gf6d6,Gd6d8,Gd8f8] } (2. Kd2) 2... Ke6 3. Kd2 Kxf6 4. Ke3 { [%cal Ge3e4] } 4... Kf5 5. Kf3) 2. Kd1 { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3,Gd1,Rd5] } 2... Ke5 { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3] } 3. Ke1 { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3,Ge1,Re5][%cal Re5e4,Re5f4,Re5d4,Ge1d2,Ge1e2,Ge1f2] } 3... Kd4 { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3] } 4. Kf2 $10 { There was nothing wrong with keeping the opposition with Kd2, but this is easier.
Draw. } { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3] } (4. Kd2 { Yes!
Keeping the OPPOSITION is a simple way to keep the king away from the KEY SQUARES.
But in this case, I felt that Kf2 seems a bit more natural. } { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3][%cal Ge1f2] }) *


