{ Welcome to this study on endgames from scratch.

This study will introduce the most important concepts, but more in-depth studies will be linked for you to be able to study more thoroughly those parts you want.

When we talk about "studying endgames" there are 3 things we might be referring to:

- Theoretical endgames
- Practical endgames
- Compositions }
 *


[Event "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪: Sample theoretical"]
[Date "2019.02.27"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "Sample theoretical"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/PGsjcXV5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "6k1/8/6K1/6P1/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.02.27"]
[UTCTime "10:28:06"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ White to play and win }
1. Kh6 (1. Kh5 { Nooooo!
This is a draw now :-( }) (1. Kf5 { Nooooo!
This is a draw now :-( }) (1. Kf6 { White is still winning, but now after Kh7 white has to play Kf7 and then after Kh8 it's forced to play Kg6 returning to the initial position. So this is not the way to win. }) 1... Kh8 2. g6 (2. Kh5 { Nooooo!
This is a draw now :-( }) (2. Kg6 { Ok, still winning, but why do you repeat the initial position? You're going in circles! }) 2... Kg8 3. g7 { Yes! Black is forced out of g8. } { [%csl Rg8,Rh7,Rh8,Rf8,Bf7][%cal Gg7f8,Gg7h8,Gh6h7] } (3. Kh5 { Nooooo!
This is a draw now :-( }) (3. Kg5 { Nooooo!
This is a draw now :-( }) 3... Kf7 4. Kh7 { Bravo! No way to stop promotion now, you win! :-) } *


