[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "Sample practical"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/eBXJ24W0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/5p1k/5P1p/3N2p1/2p5/P2b3P/5P1K/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.02.27"]
[UTCTime "10:39:10"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Black to play (Mamedov - Liren, 2017)

We should understand black is better for several reasons:

- bishop vs knight with pawns on both sides
- closest pawn to promotion
- faster king (black to move)
- better pawn structure }
1... Kg6 { Yes! Always play king up in the endgame. } { [%cal Gc4c3,Gc3c2,Gc2c1] } (1... Be4 { Good move, but Liren made the "human" move instead. }) (1... Bf5 { Good move, but Liren made the "human" move instead. }) (1... Bc2 { Good move, but Liren made the "human" move instead. }) 2. f3 { f3 is terrible, but white needed to do it to stop Be4
How do we continue now? } { [%csl Ra4][%cal Gd3c2,Gd3f5] } 2... Kf5 { Of course!
As Gregory Kaidanov would say, "black is up a king". } { [%csl Rh2,Gf5] } (2... Bc2 { Not bad, but Liren made the most obvious move instead. }) (2... h5) (2... Bf5 { Not bad, but Liren made the most obvious move instead. } { [%cal Gf5c8,Gc8b7] }) 3. a4 { White is trying his best: after preventing our bishop to control the a8 square, he starts pushing the passed pawn.
How do we use our best piece to control that pawn? } 3... Ke5! { Correct!
It does not only enter the pawn square but also wins a tempo by attacking the knight.
Note it's better than Ke6 because the king is centralized here. } (3... Ke6 { Good try, but the king is not as centralized as on e5, and now white has some drawing chances after Nc3. }) 4. Nc3 { If the knight moved anywhere else, the pawn was free to be pushed.
How do we annoy this knight now? } 4... Kd4 { Yes!
Note that black is using the king and white had no time to do it.
That typically means white is going to lose. } (4... Bf5! { Wow!
You're like an engine. This was more accurate according to the engine, but Liren's move was the human one instead ;-) }) (4... Kxf6 { This might be still good for black, but it's inconsistent with the previous plan (as well as with the practical rules of endgames).
The pawn on f6 is not important at all, don't waste time taking it. }) (4... Kd6 { Not a bad move, but very "inhuman". }) 5. a5! { White's only chance to hold is to generate enough counterplay with this pawn.
How do we stop it? } 5... Bf5! { Correct!
Our king is already attacking and the bishop was doing nothing, so good idea to use the bishop to stop the pawn. } (5... Kc5 { That stops the pawn, but our king was attacking and now it's not.
So we better use the bishop instead since it was doing nothing. }) (5... Kxc3 { Noooo!
The 'a' pawn cannot be stopped and white will get a queen.
With best play, this is a draw. }) 6. a6 Bd7 (6... Bc8 { Correct, but Liren played the other move. He might have been scared of Nb5+. }) 7. a7 Bc6 8. Nb5+? { This was a mistake, but the position was really tough for white already. } 8... Kc5! { Yes!
Hitting the knight so white has no time to come with the king. } 9. Nc3 Kb4! { Correct!
We go through the other side, so the knight does not have Nd5+. } 10. Na2+ Kb3 11. Nc1+ Kc2 12. Ne2 Kd3! { Yes! Preventing Nd4, the knight will be miserable } 13. Nc1+ { We already improved our king.
Time to stop attacking the knight and just dominate the position. } 13... Ke3 { Nice!
All of white's pieces are miserable. } { [%csl Rf3,Rf2,Ra8,Ra7,Rc1,Rb3,Rd3,Re2,Rh2,Rh3][%cal Ge3f2,Ge3f3,Gc6a8,Gc4b3,Gc4d3,Ge3e2] } (13... Kd2 { Good, but not Liren's choice }) (13... Kc2 { Good, but not Liren's choice }) 14. Kg3 Bxf3 (14... c3 { It also wins, but Liren did the obvious instead. }) (14... h5 { It also wins, but Liren did the obvious instead. }) 15. h4 g4! { There were other ways to win, but this is the simplest: our g4 pawn is now passed and defended, and it defends the bishop so the king can move. } (15... c3 { It also wins, but Liren did the obvious instead. }) (15... gxh4+ { It also wins, but Liren did the obvious instead. }) 16. h5 { Since white is not resigning, how do we win now?
(every move wins, let's see if you find what Liren did) } 16... Kd2 (16... c3 { that's another way, just not what Liren did }) (16... Kd4 { that's another way, just not what Liren did }) 17. Na2 c3 { Great!
Mamedov resigned here. } *


