[FEN "8/8/8/7k/8/7K/P7/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.04"]
[UTCTime "21:35:24"]

{ This is the only exceptional case with the rule of the square. When the pawn is on the starting position (2nd rank), given that the pawn can move 2 squares instead of 1, the square is one step smaller.

For example, in this position, it's black's to move but they lose anyway: } { [%csl Ga3,Ga8,Gf8,Gf3,Rg8,Rg2,Ra2][%cal Gb3a3,Ga4a3,Ga4a8,Gb8a8,Gb8f8,Gb3f3,Gf4f3,Gf4f8,Rg7g8,Rg7g2,Rf2g2,Rf2a2] }
1... Kg5 { [%csl Gf3,Ga3,Ga8,Gf8,Rg5][%cal Gb3a3,Ga4a3,Ga4a8,Gb8a8,Gb8f8,Gf7f8,Gf7f3,Gb3f3] } 2. a4 { [%csl Ga4,Ga8,Ge8,Ge4,Rg5][%cal Gd4e4,Gd4a4,Ga5a4,Ga5a8,Gb8a8,Gb8e8,Ge7e8,Ge7e4] } (2. a3?? { this of course would be a terrible mistake } { [%csl Ra3,Ra8,Rf3,Rf8,Gg5][%cal Rb3a3,Ra4a3,Ra4a8,Rb3f3,Rf4f3,Rf4f8,Re8f8,Re8a8] } 2... Kf5 { entering the square. Draw } { [%csl Gf5,Ra3,Ra8,Rf8,Rf3][%cal Re3f3,Re3a3,Ra4a3,Ra4a8,Rb8a8,Rb8f8,Rf7f8,Rf7f3] } 3. a4 { [%csl Ra4,Re4,Re8,Ra8,Gf5][%cal Rc8e8,Rc8a8,Ra6a8,Ra6a4,Rc4a4,Rc4e4,Re6e4,Re6e8] } 3... Ke5 { [%csl Ge5,Ra4,Re4,Re8,Ra8][%cal Ra6a8,Ra6a4,Rc4a4,Rc4e4,Re6e4,Re6e8,Rc8e8,Rc8a8] } 4. a5 { [%csl Ra5,Rd5,Rd8,Ra8,Ge5][%cal Ra7a8,Ra7a5,Rc5a5,Rc5d5,Rd6d5,Rd6d8,Rc8d8,Rc8a8] } 4... Kd6 { [%csl Gd6,Rd5,Rd8,Ra8,Ra5][%cal Rd6d5,Rd6d8,Ra6a8,Ra6a5,Rb5a5,Rb5d5,Rb8a8,Rb8d8] } 5. a6 { [%csl Ra6,Ra8,Rc8,Rc6,Gd6][%cal Rb6c6,Rb6a6,Ra7a6,Ra7a8,Rc7c8,Rc7c6,Rb8c8,Rb8a8] } 5... Kc7 { [%csl Gc7,Ra8,Ra6,Rc6,Rc8][%cal Rb6a6,Rb6c6,Rc7c8,Rc7c6,Rb8c8,Rb8a8,Ra7a8,Ra7a6] } 6. a7 { [%csl Rb7,Rb8,Ra8,Ra7,Gc7][%cal Rb7a7,Ra7b7,Rb7b8,Rb8b7,Ra8a7,Ra7a8,Ra8b8,Rb8a8] } 6... Kb7 { [%csl Ra7,Ra8,Rb8,Gb7][%cal Rb8b7,Rb7b8,Ra8b8,Rb8a8,Ra8a7,Ra7a8,Ra7b7,Rb7a7] } 7. a8=Q+ { [%csl Ra8,Gb7] } 7... Kxa8 { [%csl Ga8] }) 2... Kf6 { [%csl Rf6,Ga4,Ga8,Ge8,Ge4][%cal Gd4e4,Gd4a4,Ga5a4,Ga5a8,Gb8a8,Gb8e8,Ge7e8,Ge7e4] } 3. a5 { [%csl Rf6,Ga5,Ga8,Gd8,Gd5][%cal Gc5d5,Gc5a5,Ga6a5,Ga6a8,Gb8a8,Gb8d8,Gd7d8,Gd7d5] } 3... Ke6 { [%csl Re6,Gd5,Gd8,Ga8,Ga5][%cal Gd6d5,Gd6d8,Gc8d8,Gc8a8,Ga7a8,Ga7a5,Gb5a5,Gb5d5] } 4. a6 { [%csl Ga6,Ga8,Gc8,Gc6,Re6][%cal Gb6c6,Gb6a6,Ga7a6,Ga7a8,Gb8a8,Gb8c8,Gc7c8,Gc7c6] } 4... Kd6 { [%csl Rd6,Gc6,Ga6,Ga8,Gc8][%cal Gc7c8,Gc7c6,Ga7a6,Ga7a8,Gb8a8,Gb8c8,Gb6c6,Gb6a6] } 5. a7 { [%csl Ga7,Ga8,Gb8,Gb7,Rd6][%cal Ga7b7,Gb7a7,Ga8a7,Ga7a8,Ga8b8,Gb8a8,Gb8b7,Gb7b8] } 5... Kc7 { [%csl Rc7,Ga7,Gb7,Gb8,Ga8][%cal Gb8b7,Gb7b8,Ga8a7,Ga7a8,Ga8b8,Gb8a8,Ga7b7,Gb7a7] } 6. a8=Q { [%csl Ga8,Rc7] } *


[Event "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪: Opposition"]
[Date "2021.06.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "Opposition"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/2tnrhEZg"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/4k3/8/8/4PK2/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.06.21"]
[UTCTime "19:58:13"]

{ The opposition is a basic technique for most endgames involving kings. The side "winning the opposition" usually gets access to certain squares.

White wins here using it: }
1. Ke5! { .
This is called opposition: kings in front of each other so they're fighting for the same 3 squares (in blue).
We say that the king that is forced to move (black king) LOSES THE OPPOSITION, allowing the other king to access one of those 3 squares.
We say that the move Ke5 WINS THE OPPOSITION.
. } { [%csl Ge5,Re7,Bd6,Be6,Bf6] } 1... Kd7 { Gives access to the f6 square. } { [%csl Rd7,Bd6,Be6,Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] } (1... Kf7 { Gives access to the d6 square. } 2. Kd6) 2. Kf6 { And the pawn will promote helped by its own king. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] } 2... Ke8 3. e5 Kf8 4. e6 Ke8 5. e7 { [%cal Re8d7] } 5... Kd7 6. Kf7 { [%csl Ge8][%cal Ge7e8] } *


[Event "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪: Opposition: distant"]
[Date "2019.03.11"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "Opposition: distant"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/WcKaCe1G"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/1kp5/8/8/8/K7 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.11"]
[UTCTime "13:00:01"]

{ White to move and draw.

To win the opposition we would need to play Kb3, but we can't. We use the DISTANT OPPOSITION instead: 4 squares distance instead of 2 between the kings. } { [%csl Rb3] }
1. Kb1! { .
The kings are competing for the blue squares from the distance.
If the black king enters one of the yellow squares, white has a square for his king to win the opposition.
So even though the kings are not in direct opposition, black LOST THE OPPOSITION (the distant one).
. } { [%csl Gb1,Rb5,Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Ya4,Yb4,Yc4,Yc2,Yb2,Ya2] } (1. Kb2?? { This would lose the opposition and the game: } { [%csl Rb2,Gb4] } 1... Kb4! { [%csl Gb4,Rb2,Ba3,Bb3,Bc3] } 2. Kc2 Kc4 { [%csl Bb3,Bc3,Bd3,Gc4,Rc2] } 3. Kb2 { [%csl Gd3] } 3... Kd3 { etc } { [%cal Gc5c4,Gc4c3,Gc3c2] }) 1... Kb4 (1... Kc4 2. Kc2! { [%csl Bb3,Bc3,Bd3,Gc2,Rc4] }) 2. Kb2! { [%csl Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Rb4,Gb2] } 2... Kc4 3. Kc2 { draw } { [%csl Gc2,Rc4,Bb3,Bc3,Bd3] } *


[Event "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪: Opposition: reserve moves"]
[Date "2019.03.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "Opposition: reserve moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/LZ0WOvwH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5k2/8/8/8/8/8/4PK2/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.04"]
[UTCTime "21:42:03"]

{ Let's see this example where kings are far from each other. White will not care about losing the opposition because of the RESERVE MOVE they'll have thanks to the pawn: }
1. Ke3 Ke7 { Black wins the distant opposition! } { [%csl Ge7,Re3] } 2. Ke4 Ke6 { It wins the opposition for black, but now white has a RESERVE MOVE with the pawn. } { [%csl Ge4,Re6][%cal Ge2e3] } 3. e3 { Regaining the opposition. White wins.
This important concept (RESERVE MOVES) suggest we generally should move the king up before the pawn, to keep reserve moves at our disposal.
Let's show how the game could continue, to be sure we know how to use the opposition technique to promote: } { [%csl Ge4,Re6,Bd5,Be5,Bf5] } 3... Kd6 { [%csl Gf5] } 4. Kf5 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Ge5e6] } 4... Ke7 5. Ke5! { [%csl Ge5,Re7,Bd6,Be6,Bf6] } (5. e4?? { That would lose the opposition. It's a draw: } 5... Kf7! { [%csl Gf7,Rf5,Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } 6. Ke5 Ke7 { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6,Ge7,Re5] }) 5... Kd7 { [%csl Gf6] } 6. Kf6 { [%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Ge5e6,Ge6e7] } 6... Kd8 7. e4 Ke8 { [%cal Gf6e6,Ge4e5] } 8. Ke6 { [%csl Ge6,Re8,Bd7,Be7,Bf7] } (8. e5 { It also wins, but not because of the use of opposition. } 8... Kf8 9. e6 Ke8 10. e7 { [%csl Re8][%cal Re8d7] } 10... Kd7 11. Kf7 { [%cal Ge7e8] }) 8... Kf8 { [%csl Gd7] } 9. Kd7 { [%cal Ge4e5,Ge5e6,Ge6e7,Ge7e8] } 9... Kf7 10. e5 { [%cal Ge5e6,Ge6e7,Ge7e8] } *


