[FEN "7b/8/k1P5/6N1/8/1K5P/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.12.10"]
[UTCTime "21:41:35"]

1. c7 { A very forcing move, since it's threatening to promote the pawn. } 1... Kb7 2. Nf7! { And the knight dominates all the squares the bishop can go to, except for a1 and b2. But the king can dominate those 2 squares: } { [%csl Rh8,Re5,Rc3,Rb2,Ba1,Bd4,Bf6,Bg7][%cal Gf7h8,Gf7e5,Gb3c3,Gb3b2] } 2... Ba1 (2... Bf6 3. Nd6+ { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rb7c7,Gc7c8,Bd6e8,Ye8f6,Ye8c7] }) (2... Bg7 3. Nd6+ { [%csl Gc8,Rc7][%cal Gc7c8,Rb7c7,Bd6e8,Ye8c7,Ye8g7] }) (2... Bd4 3. Nd6+ { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gc7c8,Rb7c7,Bd6b5,Yb5c7,Yb5d4] }) 3. Ka2! { The squares c3, d4, f6 and g7 (in blue) are dominated by the knight thanks to the forks on b5 or e8, given that the check on d6 will force Kxc7.
For example: } { [%csl Rb2,Ra1,Rh8,Re5,Bg7,Bf6,Bd4,Bc3][%cal Ga2b2,Ga2a1,Gf7e5,Gf7h8,Bf7d6,Bd6e8,Bd6b5] } 3... Bd4 4. Nd6+ Kxc7 { Forced, otherwise the pawn would promote. } 5. Nb5+ { And White will win. } { [%csl Rd4,Rc7][%cal Gb5d4,Gb5c7] } *


