[UTCTime "21:30:50"]

{ We call KEY SQUARES those squares a piece of the strong side has to reach to be able to win. In some endgames KEY SQUARES can be determined, and they will help us remember the winning method in them.

We'll follow the convention of using BLUE to show KEY SQUARES.

In this position, if White's king reaches one of the blue squares, white will win. That gives us the winning method: Ke5 and Kd6.

. } { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6] }
1. Ke5 { [%csl Gd6,Be6,Bf6][%cal Ge5d6] } 1... Kf7 { [%csl Bf6,Be6,Gd6][%cal Rf7f6,Rf7e6,Ge5d6] } 2. Kd6 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge4e5,Ge5e6] } 2... Ke8 3. Ke6! { We finally use the OPPOSITION (chapter 9) to convert the win. } { [%csl Ge6,Re8] } 3... Kd8 { [%csl Gf7] } 4. Kf7 { And the pawn will promote. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge4e5,Ge5e6,Ge7e8,Ge6e7] } *


