[UTCTime "20:58:21"]

{ King and pawn vs king is the most simple endgame and you MUST know it by heart.
In general, you want to have the king in front of your pawn to win, and also you usually want to have the opposition.

We're going to see the 3 most important positions here, but there are subtleties in other positions that you should be aware of.
Therefore, I recommend you to check out the following complete study on this ending:
-[[ https://lichess.org/study/EsB7U2A9 ]]-

===================================

This position is ALWAYS winning, no matter whose turn it is.
You should know it by heart: a pawn on the 5th rank with the king in front is winning (note the key squares of the pawn indicated in blue):

. } { [%csl Bd6,Be6,Bf6] }
1. Kd6 { .
(note that if it was black to move it would have been even easier since black would lose the opposition immediately allowing the promotion)
... } 1... Kd8 2. e6 Ke8 3. e7 { [%cal Re8f7] } 3... Kf7 4. Kd7 { [%csl Ge8][%cal Ge7e8] } *


[Event "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪: K+P vs K - pawn before 5th"]
[Date "2019.03.04"]
