{ In general, a knight can stop a pawn when it can be put in front of it.
Sometimes, however, the opponent's king is close enough to bother the knight (like in this position).

In such cases, lateral control is key.

... }
1. Ne2+! (1. Nd3+?? { would lose }) 1... Kd2 (1... Kd1 { is useless because we just transfer the knight to the other side of the pawn: } { [%csl Ga2][%cal Ge2c3,Gc3a2] } 2. Nc3+ { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gc3a2] }) 2. Nd4! { .
The fork on b3 stops the promotion.
Immediate draw because if white promotes we fork on b3 and any other move allows Nxc2
... } { [%csl Rc1,Rd2][%cal Gd4b3] } 2... Kc3 3. Nxc2 { .
This is the most representative case, but there are many subtleties in knight vs pawn, especially with rook pawns.
Check out the following complete study on this topic:
-[[ https://lichess.org/study/MANoA8zi ]]- } *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: Counting"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
