[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/SLKXPsBs"]
[FEN "4R3/8/7K/8/1kp5/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "19:57:49"]

{ As with any ending involving rooks, there are a number of subtleties that make this the most difficult of PIECE vs pawn endings.

We're going to see a basic example, but there are many different ideas, resources and techniques. To see them all, please check out the following study:
-[[ https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii ]]-

==================================================

Now let's see this simple position where counting is enough to determine the outcome of it:

1) How many moves does Black need to be ready to promote (king on b2, pawn on c2)
2) How many moves does White need to be ready to stop it (king on d2, rook on c8)

Black needs 4 tempi and White 5.
But it's White to move, so White is in time to stop the promotion (therefore White wins).

If it was Black to move it would be a draw, since White has no time to stop the promotion and will need to sacrifice the rook for the pawn.

Let's see how White wins:

... } { [%cal Rb4b3,Rb3b2,Rc4c3,Rc3c2,Ge8c8,Gh6g5,Gg5f4,Gf4e3,Ge3d2,Rc2c1] }
1. Kg5! c3 2. Kf4 c2 3. Rc8 Kb3 4. Ke3 Kb2 5. Kd2 { [%csl Gc1][%cal Gd2c1] } *


[Event "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board): Rook's pawn"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx"]
[Date "2019.05.20"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "B vs N (with a pawn)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/Wq3qdg51"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/B6n/7p/6k1/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.20"]
[UTCTime "19:50:28"]

{ Bishop vs knight endings are frequent and very tactical. It's hard to set general rules for them and they must be approached position by position, and always aware that tactical resources might appear.

If only, a general rule can be stated: the bishop is usually better than the knight.

For a complete study on the topic, check out this link:
-[[ https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx ]]--

Here we're only going to see a well-known trick in this position where the side with the bishop is very close to losing.

Rook's pawns create more problems for the defense. This case arises quite often and contains an unexpected drawing resource we must know.

Black threatens to put king on g1 and knight on g2.

... } { [%cal Gg2g1,Gh4g2] }
1. Bd7! { The pawn must be on the 7th rank for the drawing resource to work!
... } (1. Bc6+?? Kg1 2. Bd5 Ng2+ { [%cal Gh3h2,Gh2h1] }) 1... h2 2. Bc6+ Kg1 { .
How do we stop now Ng2 followed by promotion?
... } { [%cal Gh4g2] } (2... Nf3+ 3. Ke2) 3. Bh1!! { .
Amazing but saving resource!
... } 3... Kxh1 (3... Ng2+ 4. Ke2 Nf4+ 5. Ke1 $10) (3... Nf5 4. Bf3) 4. Kf2! { important: go to same colour as the knight } { [%csl Gf2,Gh4] } (4. Kf1?? Nf5 5. Kf2 Ng3 { [%csl Rf1] }) 4... Nf3 5. Kf1 Nd2+ 6. Kf2 Ne4+ 7. Kf1 $10 { .
Important trick/resource to remember.
But of course, it only works when the king is close enough. } *


