[FEN "4k3/R7/8/3KP3/8/6r1/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.08.30"]
[UTCTime "20:40:52"]

{ There are many different techniques in R+P vs R, both defensive and attacking. One of the important ones to know is the defensive technique of Philidor, which occurs when the defensive side can "cut" the opponent's king from the 3rd rank: } { [%cal Gg3g6] }
1... Rg6! { Now White is forced to push the pawn at some point to make any progress. } { [%cal Gg6a6,Gg6h6] } 2. e6 Rg1! { The king can't hide in front of the pawn now and we will be able to check forever. } 3. Kd6 Rd1+ 4. Ke5 Re1+ 5. Kf6 Rf1+ $10 { To learn other important techniques in this endgame, please check out the study:
-[[ https://lichess.org/study/D14POEwo ]]- } *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: The winning procedure"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/gS1lV8oa"]
[Date "2022.08.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Endgames: from zero to hero 💪"]
[ChapterName "Q vs P"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tU7iyXX4/nKHgWGkZ"]
[FEN "6K1/8/3Q4/8/8/8/5kp1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2022.08.30"]
[UTCTime "20:52:13"]

{ This endgame has also a few cases worth knowing. Bishop pawn and rook pawn give drawing chances.

In general, this is the winning procedure, that most players know: }
1. Qf4+ Ke2 2. Qg3! { Our goal is to force the king in front of the pawn, and we do that with checks or moves like this Qg3 that forces the king to f1: } 2... Kf1 3. Qf3+ { The king must go in front of the pawn now and that gives us a tempo to move our own king. } 3... Kg1 4. Kg7 Kh2 { And now we repeat the same procedure until our king is close enough to deliver checkmate or win the pawn: } 5. Qf2 { It's not the only way, but I like keeping the queen in this H-shape square set, which makes the technique easier to remember. } { [%csl Bf2,Bf3,Bf4,Bg3,Bh3,Bh2,Bh4] } 5... Kh1 6. Qh4+ Kg1 7. Kg6 Kf1 8. Qf4+ Ke2 9. Qg3 Kf1 10. Qf3+ Kg1 11. Kg5 Kh2 { Now the king is close enough to start thinking about checkmates! } 12. Kh4! g1=N (12... g1=Q 13. Qh3#) 13. Qf2+ Kh1 14. Kg3 Ne2+ 15. Qxe2 { To learn more about Q vs P endgames and all the cases and subtleties, please check this study:
-[[ https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp ]]- } *


