[UTCTime "23:09:44"]

{ This famous composition demonstrates how a king can make multiple threats and how it can take more than one path to a given location, using the same number of moves.

White to play and draw. } { [%csl Ra6,Gh8,Gc6,Rh5][%cal Gc6c8,Gc8a8,Gc6a6,Ga6a8,Gh8h5,Rh5h1,Rh5d5,Rd5d1,Rd1h1,Bh8g7,Bg7f6,Bf6g5,Bf6e6] }
1. Kg7! { .
It seems the king can never catch the h pawn and can never help the c6 pawn to promote, but ... it can threaten to do both!
As Nimzowitsch would say:
"the threat is stronger than the execution"
. } 1... Kb6 (1... h4 { this does not help black either: } 2. Kf6 { [%cal Rf6g5,Rg5h4] } 2... h3 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gf6e6,Gf6e7] } (2... Kb6 { [%csl Gc6,Ge5,Bd6][%cal Rh4h1,Rh4e4,Re4e1,Re1h1,Rb6c6,Be5f4,Be5e4,Be5d6] } 3. Ke5! { [%cal Ge5d6,Re4h4,Re4e1,Re1h1,Rh1h4] } (3. Ke6?? Kxc6 { [%cal Gh4h3,Gh3h2,Gh2h1] }) 3... Kxc6 { [%cal Ge5e4,Ge5f4] } (3... h3 4. Kd6 { [%cal Gc6c7,Gc7c8] } 4... h2 5. c7 Kb7 6. Kd7) 4. Ke4 { [%csl Ge4,Rh4,Rh1,Re1][%cal Rf1e1,Rf1h1,Rh2h1,Rh2h4,Rg4h4,Rg4e4,Re3e4,Re3e1] }) 3. Ke6 h2 4. c7 { [%cal Gc7c8] } 4... Kb7 5. Kd7 { draw }) 2. Kf6 h4 (2... Kxc6 { [%csl Rd5,Rd1,Rh1,Rh5][%cal Gf6g5,Gf6f5,Gf6e5,Rf5d5,Rd4d5,Rd4d1,Rg1d1,Rg1h1,Rh2h1,Rh2h5,Rf5h5] } 3. Ke5) 3. Ke5! { [%csl Rh4,Re4,Re1,Rh1][%cal Ge5d6,Ge5f4,Rh3h1,Rh3h4,Rf4h4,Rf4e4,Re3e4,Re3e1,Rf1e1,Rf1h1] } 3... h3 (3... Kxc6 { [%cal Ge5e4,Ge5f4] } 4. Ke4 { [%csl Ge4,Re1,Rh1,Rh4][%cal Rg4h4,Rg4e4,Re3e4,Re3e1,Rf1e1,Rf1h1,Rh2h1,Rh2h4] }) 4. Kd6 { [%cal Gc6c7,Gc7c8] } 4... h2 5. c7 Kb7 6. Kd7 { [%cal Gc7c8] } 6... h1=Q 7. c8=Q+ { draw } *


