[Event "Frankenstein–Dracula Variation: Annotated moves"]
[Date "2018.12.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C27"]
[Opening "Vienna Game: Stanley Variation, Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[StudyName "Frankenstein–Dracula Variation"]
[ChapterName "Annotated moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tepI7b6Q/pKl6DYVw"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.26"]
[UTCTime "18:13:23"]

{ Annotated from Wikipedia:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vienna_Game,_Frankenstein%E2%80%93Dracula_Variation }
1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 { [%csl Rf7] } (4. Nxe4 d5 { considered to give Black no problems }) (4. Bxf7+ Kxf7 5. Nxe4 { considered good for Black as long as he avoids 5 ... Nc6 } 5... d5 (5... Nc6 6. Qf3+ Kg8 7. Ng5!)) 4... Nd6 { only move } (4... Ng5 5. d4 Ne6 6. dxe5 { some advantage for white } (6. d5 { also possible, prevents g6 } 6... Nd4 { led to very complicated play in Kis–Csato, Hungarian Team Championship 1993 } (6... g6 7. dxe6! { Böök–Heidenheimo 1925 }))) 5. Bb3 (5. Qxe5+ Qe7 6. Qxe7+ Bxe7 7. Be2 { Ulf Andersson recommended this, claiming that White has some advantage }) 5... Nc6 (5... Be7 { (returning the pawn) is a quieter alternative, for example: } 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nxe5 O-O 8. O-O Nxe5 9. Qxe5 Bf6 10. Qf4 Ne8 11. d4 c6 12. d5 { however, White has a better game (Larsen; Nielsen–Muir, corr. 1971) }) 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 (7... f6 { David Bronstein won one game with this, but... come on... f6... } 8. Nxc7+ Qxc7 9. Qxf6 b6 10. Qxh8 Bb7 11. Qxh7 O-O-O { Bronstein found no followers to this line (obviously) }) (7... Nf5 8. g4 (8. Qd5 { also strong } 8... Nh6 9. d4 d6 10. Bxh6 Be6 11. Qf3 Bxh6 12. d5 { advantage white, Hughes–Fogarty, Pittsburgh 2013 }) 8... a6 9. gxf5 axb5 10. fxg6 Qe7 11. gxf7+ Kd8 12. Ne2 { preventing Nd4 } 12... e4 13. Qg3 { advantage white }) 8. Qd5 Qe7 (8... Qf6 { has also been tried and White has to be careful. For instance, after: } 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 (11. d4 { this is however the way to play as white } 11... Nxd4 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. Nf3 Bb7 14. Qxd4! { (that would be a terrible move with the Black queen on e7) and Black's attack is now less sharp after: } 14... exd4 15. Bg5 Qxg5 16. Nxg5) 11... Bb7 12. h4 { as in the main line, black has the strong: } 12... Ne7! { that they cannot play with the queen on e7 (White has now a very poor game) }) 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 Bb7 12. h4 f4 (12... Nb4 13. Bg5 { [%cal Gb4d5] } (13. Qxb7 Nxb7 14. Bg5)) 13. Qf3 Nd4 (13... Bh6 14. Bd2) 14. Qg4 Bh6 { [%cal Ga8b6] } (14... Bg7) (14... Bxa8) *


