{ When we cannot use Philidor against a central or bishop's pawn, we have this technique. The main idea is to keep the rook behind the pawn:

... }
1... Rf1! { [%cal Gf1e1] } (1... Rg5?? 2. Kd6 (2. Ke6 Rg6+ $10) 2... Rg1 { [%cal Gd6e6] } (2... Rg6+ 3. e6 $18) 3. Rh8+ Kf7 4. e6+ $18) (1... Rf4!? { It also works (and so do Rf3 or Rf2) but in general we want to have the rook as far as possible from the opponent's king. }) 2. Kd6 { The most challenging move, as it gives black many alternatives, but only one draws. } (2. Ke6 { could be annoying, but less practical since Black's answer is forced: } { [%cal Ge8f8,Re8d8] } 2... Kf8! (2... Kd8? 3. Rh8+ Kc7 4. Ke7 Rf2 5. e6 Rf1 6. Ke8 Rf2 7. e7 Rf1 8. Rf8 { [%cal Gf8f7,Ge8f7] }) 3. Ra7 Re1! { Transposing to the main line } { [%cal Gf1e1] }) 2... Re1! { .
It's the only move, and it's difficult to find if you don't know K&H. The rook needs to stand behind the pawn to prevent its advance.
... } 3. Ke6 (3. Rh8+ Kf7 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6,Ge1e6] } 4. Rh7+ Ke8 5. Ke6 Kf8 { transposing to the main line }) 3... Kf8! 4. Rf7+ (4. Rh8+ Kg7 5. Ra8 Re2! { K&H main concept: White can't play Ke7 when the pawn is attacked } 6. Kd6 Kf7 $10 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6,Ge2e6] }) 4... Ke8 (4... Kg8 5. Rf5 { It should be a draw too, but it's dangerous to have the king cut. }) 5. Ra7 Kf8 6. Ra8+ Kg7 { .
And here if Black's rook was on any other file, White would win with Ke7. White needs to keep the pawn defended and there's no way to make progress.
... } 7. Kd6 Kf7! { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6,Ge1e6] } 8. Ra7+ Ke8 { .
No way to make progress, we keep applying the same technique or Philidor if given the chance. } *


