{ Let's follow the same line again: }
1... Rf1 2. Kd6 Rd1+?? { .
As you know, the rook had to go to e1, but this is a "logical" mistake to make:
... } 3. Ke6 Kf8 { .
How is this winning?
How is this different from the position after 2. Ke6, Kf8?
Well, in that position the rook was on f1, preventing the following maneuver:
... } 4. Rf7+! Ke8 (4... Kg8 5. Rd7! Re1 6. Kf6 { And the pawn advances, although the ending is still difficult to convert: } 6... Rf1+ 7. Ke7 Ra1! { Best defence, since now e6 would be a draw. } 8. Rd2! (8. e6?? Kg7! $10 { See chapters 15-18 to understand how this is a draw. }) 8... Ra7+ 9. Kf6 $18 { [%cal Ge5e6] }) 5. Ra7! { Important tempo to secure the advance of the pawn. } 5... Kf8 6. Ra8+ Kg7 7. Ke7 { Black is lost because the rook occupied the important a-file. We'll see how that's important to win in chapters 15-22. } { [%cal Ge5e6] } *


