[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/D14POEwo/GeWlxLwA"]
[FEN "4k3/7R/8/3KPr2/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.02.05"]
[UTCTime "14:34:36"]

{ We'll see now another common mistake that doesn't lose but makes black's life difficult. You never know when you'll get to that position from a middlegame, so it's important to know it even if you're certain you wouldn't commit the "mistake".

We start as usual:

... }
1... Rf1 2. Kd6 Re1! 3. Ke6 Kd8? { .
For an engine (or for an endgame database), this move is as good as Kf8. But we broke the principle of going to the short side with the king. The endgame is still a draw, but some additional difficulties will be presented, given the wrong placement of the king:
... } 4. Rh8+ (4. Ra7 { a rook waiting move is best answered with a rook waiting move: } 4... Re2!) 4... Kc7 { .
For now K&H is working: White cannot play Ke7 because of our rook attacking the pawn. But White can try several things to exploit our king's position:
... } 5. Kf6 { .
1st attempt, easy to refute:
... } 5... Kd7! { This is purely the K&H technique. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd7e6,Ge1e6] } 6. Rh7+ Ke8 7. Ke6 { .
And of course, now we could (and should) play Kf8, but let's go with Kd8 again to see another attempt by White:
... } 7... Kd8? (7... Kf8) 8. Rh8+ Kc7 9. Re8 { .
This is the most challenging attempt. The threat is Kf7 and advancing the pawn.
The game is still a draw but Black needs to be precise.
... } { [%cal Ge6f7] } 9... Rh1!! { The only move!
We can defend with checks from the short side. That shouldn't usually work but it does in this case thanks to White's rook's placement. } (9... Re2?? { Waiting would lose, but the analysis is complex: } 10. Kf7! Rh2 { too late } (10... Rf2+ 11. Ke7 Rh2 12. Rf8! { and e6 will lead to Lucena } { [%cal Ge5e6] }) (10... Kd7 11. e6+ Kd6 12. Rd8+ { [%cal Ge6e7,Ge7e8] }) 11. Rg8! (11. e6?? Rh7+ 12. Kg6 Rh1 13. e7 Kd7 $10) 11... Rh7+ 12. Rg7 Rh8 13. Ke7! { White needs a lot of patience before being able to push the pawn! } (13. e6?? Kd6 14. e7 Kd7 $10) 13... Kc6 14. e6 Kc7 15. Kf6+ Kd8 (15... Kc6 16. Rd7 { will lead to Lucena }) (15... Kd6 16. Rd7+ Kc6 17. Rd1 Rh6+ 18. Kf7 Rh7+ 19. Kg6 Rh2 20. e7 Re2 21. Kf7 Rf2+ 22. Ke8 { Lucena }) 16. Kf7 Kc7 17. Rg1 Rh7+ 18. Kg6 Rh8 19. Rd1 { Lucena }) (9... Rf1 10. Ke7 { [%cal Ge5e6] }) 10. Kf7 (10. Rf8 Re1! $10 { Back to K&H }) 10... Rh7+ 11. Kg6 (11. Kf6 Rh6+ 12. Kg7 Kd7! $10) 11... Kd7! 12. Ra8 Rh1 $10 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gh1e1,Gd7e6] } *


