[ChapterName "Defending #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/D14POEwo/ZBIgJpzX"]
[FEN "r7/3RK1k1/4P3/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.02.05"]
[UTCTime "14:34:36"]

{ This position is a draw. But only thanks to the rook being in the a-file.

As a general rule, once the pawn has reached the 5th, 6th or 7th ranks and the defending king cannot be in front of it, the only efficient defensive method is occupying the long side with the rook. Therefore the defending rook must be on the a-file.

Since there are some winning ideas (that we'll see) related to the back rank, the ideal spot for the defensive rook is the a8 square.

We'll see in this and the next two chapters some attempts for White to try and win this position, and how to defend as Black.

Let's start with Rd8.

... } { [%csl Ga8] }
1. Rd8 { .
A logical move, forcing Black's rook away from the ideal spot.
White's main threat is to go Ke8 and e7.
... } 1... Ra7+! { Tactically preventing Ke8, since it would be an immediate draw. } (1... Ra6 { This also draws since it also prevents Ke8.
Maybe Ra7+ is a bit more practical since the draw might not be as obvious as in this case. }) (1... Ra1?? { Allowing Ke8 in good conditions is fatal, since White achieves a Lucena endgame: } 2. Ke8 Kf6 3. e7 $18) 2. Rd7 (2. Ke8? { The position was drawn anyway, but White loses any chance now, since the draw is immediate: } 2... Kf6 { [%csl Re6] } 3. Rd7 Ra8+ 4. Rd8 Ra7 $10) (2. Kd6 Ra6+ 3. Ke5 Ra5+ 4. Rd5 Ra8 $10) 2... Ra8! { And we go back to the initial position. } *


