1. Kd6+ { .
This might be the first idea many players would have, but it's the easiest to refute, since the defending king goes in front of the pawn and some other defensive techniques start to be available: } 1... Kf8! (1... Kf6 2. Rf7+ Kg6 3. Rf1 { It's still a draw thanks to the rook on the long side (see chapter 5), but in general it's dangerous to have our king cut away from the pawn's file and any mistake would be fatal. }) 2. Rh7 { [%cal Gh7h8] } (2. Rf7+ Ke8 (2... Kg8 3. Rf1 { A draw thanks to the long-side defence (chapter 5), but dangerous to have our king cut away from the pawn's file. }) 3. Rh7 { [%cal Gh7h8] } 3... Ra6+ (3... Rd8+ 4. Ke5 Rd1 $10 { also Phillidor }) 4. Ke5 Ra1 $10 { Phillidor! }) 2... Rd8+ 3. Ke5 Rd1 $10 { Phillidor } *


[Event "Techniques in Rook + Pawn vs Rook: Defending #3"]
