[UTCTime "14:34:36"]

{ We've said many times how this position is lost for Black because the rook is not on the a-file.

Let's see how to win.

... }
1. Kd6+! { .
It's the only move to win, but more important than the move itself is the maneuver we're trying to do: we want to get to the initial position being Black's turn to force the king to g6, and only then we'll be able to initiate a winning rook maneuver.
... } (1. Ra1 Rb7+ 2. Kd6 Rb6+ 3. Kd7 Rb7+ 4. Kc6 Rb2 5. Re1 Kf8 6. Kd7 Rd2+ 7. Kc6 Ra2) 1... Kf6 (1... Kf8 2. Kd7 Kg7 3. Ke7 { it's the same }) 2. Kd7! Kg7 (2... Rb1 3. e7 Rd1+ 4. Ke8 { [%cal Ge8f8] } 4... Kg7 5. Ra8 $18 { [%cal Ga8d8] }) 3. Ke7! { Zugzwang. } 3... Kg6 { .
Now that the king is on g6 instead of g7, we start the next phase: bring the rook behind the pawn and threaten to promote.
... } 4. Ra1! { Note that allowing lateral checks wouldn't work if Black's rook was on the a-file. } 4... Rb7+ 5. Kd6 (5. Kd8 { would be an engine's choice since it takes less moves, but Kd6 is more forcing }) 5... Rb6+ 6. Kd7 Rb7+ 7. Kc6 Rb8 (7... Rb2 8. Re1 { [%cal Rg7f8] }) 8. Kc7 Rb2 9. Re1! { .
Securing the promotion. Note that this wouldn't work with the king on g7.
... } 9... Rc2+ 10. Kd7 Rd2+ 11. Ke8 Ra2 12. e7 $18 *


