[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "12:36:22"]

{ This is a very important ending since rook and pawn endgames are the most common in practice. It would typically arise from a rook vs rook ending where one rook has to be sacrificed to stop a passed pawn.

As with any ending involving rooks, there are a number of subtleties that make this the most difficult of PIECE vs pawn endings. }
 *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: Counting"]
[Date "2019.04.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Counting"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/ND5gYrjh"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "4R3/8/7K/8/1kp5/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "12:39:29"]

{ When no other circumstance applies, the most basic technique is to count tempi.

This position is one example of that: Black's king will not cut our king and our rook cannot be threatened. Therefore we can simply count:

1) How many moves does Black need to be ready to promote (king on b2, pawn on c2)
2) How many moves does White need to be ready to stop it (king on d2, rook on c8)

In this case, Black needs 4 tempi and White 5. But it's White to move, so White is in time to stop the promotion (therefore White wins).

If it was Black to move it would be a draw, since White has no time to stop the promotion and will need to sacrifice the rook for the pawn.

Let's see how White wins:

... } { [%cal Rb4b3,Rb3b2,Rc4c3,Rc3c2,Ge8c8,Gh6g5,Gg5f4,Gf4e3,Ge3d2,Rc2c1] }
1. Kg5! c3 2. Kf4 c2 3. Rc8 Kb3 4. Ke3 Kb2 5. Kd2 { [%csl Gc1][%cal Gd2c1] } *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: What if we start moving the rook?"]
[Date "2019.04.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "What if we start moving the rook?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/4ZNwpUBj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "4R3/8/7K/8/1kp5/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "12:44:37"]

{ Ok, we know this wins for White. And we need to do the 5 moves in green arrows.

But why did we start with the king? Is there a problem if we start with the rook?

... } { [%cal Ge8c8,Gh6g5,Gg5f4,Gf4e3,Ge3d2] }
1. Rc8?? Kc3!! { .
This is the problem!
This brilliant move allows Black to draw by opposing to White's king march:
... } 2. Kg5 Kd3 { .
And now it's clear we're not in time to stop the pawn. If we count again:
1) Black needs 3 tempi to be ready to promote.
2) White needs a lifetime to get the king to b2. } { [%cal Rd3d2,Rc4c3,Rc3c2,Rc2c1] } *


