[UTCTime "12:51:02"]

{ Euwe determined that White draws if the king is on one of the red squares and wins in any other case.

As long as we can count we don't really need to know all of that.

In this position, the count still works, because despite the kings being in the same file, Black's king is not in time to annoy White's king.

... } { [%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Rd8,Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8,Rh7,Rg7,Rg6,Rh6][%cal Gf7e6,Ge6d5,Gd5d4,Gd4d3,Gd3d2,Rf4f3,Re4e3,Rf3f2,Re3e2,Re2e1] }
1. Ke6 e3 (1... Ke3 2. Ke5 Kf3 3. Ra3+ e3 4. Kd4) 2. Kd5 e2 3. Kd4 Kf3 4. Kd3 Kf2 5. Kd2 *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: When the king is too far from helping the pawn"]
[Date "2019.04.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "When the king is too far from helping the pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/FhFoI1d3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "7K/6R1/1k6/p7/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "12:54:07"]

{ When the king is too far from helping the pawn promote, we have a winning resource: cutting that king.

In this case, despite White's king being also too far away, cutting the king wins:

... }
1. Rg5! { .
Now the king will never help the pawn promote.
... } { [%csl Rb6][%cal Gg5a5,Gg5h5] } 1... a4 2. Kg7 { .
If Black does nothing, White will just keep walking the king until taking the pawn.
But if Black pushes the pawn, the pawn is taken:
... } { [%cal Gg7h6,Gh6h5,Gh5g4,Gg4f3,Gf3e3,Ge3d3,Gd3c3] } 2... a3 3. Rg3! { .
The king is too far to defend the pawn.
... } { [%csl Rb6] } 3... a2 4. Ra3 *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: Strong king behind the pawn"]
[Date "2019.04.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Strong king behind the pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/cM9TjlUX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "7R/8/2K5/8/1pk5/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "12:58:17"]

{ This position is a draw, but there are a couple of subtleties we need to know.

White's king can't reach a2 in time, so the winning idea is not stopping the pawn as usual, but instead trying to checkmate.

Black's king, on the other hand, cannot avoid being pushed towards the edge of the board to keep the pawn alive and stop White's king from going to a2. To avoid the checkmate Black will need to use underpromotion:

... }
1. Rh4+ (1. Kb6 b3 2. Ka5 b2 3. Rb8 Kc3 4. Ka4 Kc2 5. Ka3) 1... Kc3 { obviously the only move } 2. Kc5 { (there's no time to go round the pawn with Kb5) } 2... b3 { .
The position is like the starting one but one rank down.
With the same procedure, Black's king will be pushed towards the edge of the board:
... } 3. Rh3+ Kc2 4. Kc4 b2 5. Rh2+ Kc1 6. Kc3 { .
Black can promote, but anything that's not a knight will be answered with Rh1 checkmate.
... } 6... b1=N+! 7. Kd3 { .
And we all should know how to make a draw from here :-)
Also note that this wouldn't save the game with a rook pawn (see chapter 13) } *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: Outflanking"]
[Date "2019.04.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Outflanking"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/3hkzSHUt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/3K3R/8/2pk4/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "13:04:23"]

{ This position is winning for White.
The difference: the pawn has not reached the 5th rank yet.

In this case, we know pushing the king towards the edge will not work (underpromotion to knight will save the day).

But there's a method that does win: outflanking.

... }
1. Rh5+ Kd4 2. Kc6! { .
This does not work when the pawn is more advanced, but here White is just in time.
... } 2... c4 3. Kb5 c3 4. Kb4 c2 { [%cal Gh5h1,Gh5c5] } 5. Rc5 Kd3 6. Kb3 *


[Event "Rook vs pawn: Shoulder-charging"]
[Date "2019.04.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Shoulder-charging"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/WcEgflEr"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/7K/3pk3/8/8/3R4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "13:10:01"]

{ In this position, Black has hopes for 2 reasons:

1) The rook is in front of the pawn, so Black will eventually win a tempo
2) Black's king is in the proper side of the pawn to annoy White's king

However the position is a win for White, by using the technique of SHOULDER-CHARGING:

... }
1. Kg4! { .
Not the only winning move (Kh4 also wins).
The key idea is to get an opposition with the kings on e3 and g3.
Now Re1+ is a threat.
... } (1. Kh4 { [%csl Re3][%cal Gh4g3] }) 1... Ke3 2. Kg3! { .
Again Re1+ is a threat and cannot be stopped, since Black's king needs to keep the pawn defended.
... } 2... d3 3. Re1+ Kd2 4. Kf2 { White wins } { [%cal Gf2e3] } *


