[StudyName "Rook vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Time-gaining check"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/9BorSoii/fMUoutAI"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "R7/8/8/8/2K3p1/8/5k2/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.29"]
[UTCTime "13:14:34"]

{ These endgames are usually a race between the kings.
We only move the rook when it's strictly necessary.

This position is such a scenario.

Black's king is an ideal position to support the pawn and White's king is still far from helping.

If we allow g3 it will be an immediate draw. Therefore the only move that wins is:

... } { [%csl Rf2][%cal Gg4g3,Gg3g2,Gg2g1] }
1. Rf8+! Ke2 { (blocking the pawn's path would only help White's king to get in time) } 2. Rg8! { .
And thanks to the previous check, we get to put the rook behind the pawn without allowing g3 in response. White won a crucial tempo.
... } 2... Kf3 3. Kd3! { Shoulder-charging
... } 3... g3 4. Rf8+ Kg2 5. Ke2 { White wins } *


