{ The queen is obviously the strongest piece to stop a pawn.

Most players think they master this endgame because they know the basic ideas. However, we'll show some important details and subtleties that can cost you half a point if you ignore them.

Fortunately, you'll probably remember these subtleties easily, as they're really striking. }
 *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: The winning procedure"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "The winning procedure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/gS1lV8oa"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "6K1/8/3Q4/8/8/8/5kp1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "18:21:37"]

{ Let's show the winning procedure, that most players know.

We check the king until we force it in front of the pawn, so we can get our king one step closer.
We repeat the same procedure until our king is close enough to deliver checkmate or win the pawn:

... }
1. Qf4+ Ke2 2. Qg3! Kf1 3. Qf3+ { .
The king must go in front of the pawn now.
... } 3... Kg1 4. Kg7 Kh2 5. Qf2 Kh1 6. Qh4+ Kg1 7. Kg6 Kf1 8. Qf4+ Ke2 9. Qg3 Kf1 10. Qf3+ Kg1 11. Kg5 Kh2 { .
Now the king is close enough to start thinking in checkmates!
... } 12. Kh4! g1=N 13. Qf2+ Kh1 14. Kg3 Ne2+ 15. Qxe2 *


