[Event "Queen vs pawn: Rook pawn: stalemate theme"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Rook pawn: stalemate theme"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/4EKb6ML5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/5K1P/8/8/3q4/8/8/2k5 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "18:31:37"]

{ The rook and the bishop pawns give the defending side some stalemate resources.

Let's see this one:

... }
1. Kg8 Qd8+ 2. Kg7 Qg5+ 3. Kf7 Qh6 4. Kg8 Qg6+ 5. Kh8! { .
If we remember the winning procedure, when the king is in front of the pawn we use that tempo to bring our king closer.
In this position that would be stalemate.
There's no way to bring the king closer and therefore there's no way to win. } *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: Rook's pawn: strong king near"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Rook's pawn: strong king near"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/5uSJBxfR"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/6KP/3q4/4k3/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "18:34:09"]

{ Instead of remembering winning and drawing zones in the board (would you remember them?) I prefer De la Villa's method of key squares.

The key squares are one knight-jump away from the promotion square. In this case, f7 and g6.

The strong side can win if the king is 2 steps away from a key square.

In this example, that's the case. Also, the winning method will show us why the rule is like that, since the king needs to reach one of those squares to win:

... } { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] }
1... Qe7+ (1... Qd7+ { [%csl Gf7,Gg6] } 2. Kg6 { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 2... Qe6+ { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 3. Kg7 { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 3... Qe7+ { .
Now the king cannot go back to g6, because of Qf8, so it has to go back and allow our own king to reach that g6 square:
... } { [%csl Gf7,Gg6] } 4. Kg8 { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 4... Kf6! { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 5. h8=Q+ { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } 5... Kg6 { .
Important position to remember. The only way to stop checkmate in 1 is by giving up the queen. } { [%csl Gg6] }) 2. Kg8 { [%csl Gg6,Gf7] } (2. Kg6 Qf8 { [%cal Gf8h8] }) 2... Kf6 (2... Kf5 { [%cal Gf5g6] } 3. h8=Q Kg6) (2... Ke6 3. h8=Q Qf7#) 3. h8=Q+ Kg6 { [%csl Gg6] } *


