The win is slightly different than the other one:

... } { [%csl Gf7,Rg6] }
1... Ke7! (1... Qe7+ { also works, maybe even easier :-) } 2. Kg8 Ke6 3. h8=N (3. h8=Q Qf7#) 3... Kf6) 2. h8=Q Qg4+ 3. Kh6 Qh4+ 4. Kg7 Qg5+ 5. Kh7 Kf7 { .
And the position should look familiar :-) } { [%csl Gf7,Rh7] } *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: Bishop's pawn: how to defend"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Bishop's pawn: how to defend"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/0PoYKu8Z"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/5P2/3K4/8/8/1k6/8/q7 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "18:46:02"]

{ This position is ideal for the defending side. Not only the strong king is far, but we also have time to move the defending king to the right side of the pawn (towards the corner of the board).

... }
1. Ke7! Qe5+ 2. Kd7 { Kf8 draws as well, but in general, we want to make it difficult for the winning side to make progress:
... } 2... Qf6 3. Ke8 Qe6+ 4. Kf8 Kc4 5. Kg7! { .
The right side of the pawn!
... } 5... Qe7 6. Kg8 Qg5+ 7. Kh8 Qf6+ 8. Kg8 Qg6+ 9. Kh8! { .
Similar to the rook's pawn stalemate trick, this resource avoids the strong king to get any closer.
Taking the pawn is a draw, but black cannot bring the king either because we're threatening to promote.
It's a draw. } *


