{ As we can imagine, with the defending king on the wrong side, the strong king can be a bit further away to win. The key squares are g6 and d7 in this case, and the strong king must be 2 steps away from one of them (g6 here).

... } { [%csl Gg6,Gd7] }
1... Qa7+ { [%csl Gg6] } 2. Ke8 { [%csl Gg6] } 2... Qb8+ { [%csl Gg6] } 3. Ke7 { [%csl Gg6] } 3... Qe5+ { [%csl Gg6] } 4. Kd7 { [%csl Gg6] } 4... Qf6 { [%csl Gg6] } 5. Ke8 { [%csl Gg6] } 5... Qe6+ { [%csl Gg6] } 6. Kf8 { [%csl Gg6] } 6... Kg5 { [%csl Gg6] } 7. Kg7 Qe7! { [%csl Gg6] } (7... Qd7 { don't fall for this } 8. Kh8! { it's still winning but we have to maneuver again with the queen since the Kg6 trick does not work here, do you see why? } 8... Kg6 { [%csl Rd7] } (8... Qe7 9. Kg7) 9. f8=Q (9. f8=N+ { [%cal Rf8g6,Rf8d7] }) 9... Qh7#) 8. Kg8 { [%csl Gg6] } (8. Kh8 Kg6) 8... Kg6 { .
And as we know, Black wins. } { [%csl Gg6] } *


