[ChapterName "Bishop's pawn: winning zone against king on the wrong side (b)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/KhzXarny"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/4KP2/8/1k6/8/8/q7/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "19:04:18"]

{ When the king is two steps away from d7 instead of g6, we must be careful not to allow the enemy king to reach the right side without losing tempi:

... } { [%csl Gd7,Gg6] }
1... Qa3+! { Other checks also win, but accuracy is required after.
It's easier to prevent Kf8 with this check.
... } { [%csl Rf8,Rf6][%cal Ga3f8,Ge7e8] } (1... Qa7+ 2. Kf6 { And now only Qa1+ and !d4+ work, to prevent Kg7. } (2. Kf8 { And now Qg1 is the only move. } 2... Qg1 { [%csl Rg8,Rg7][%cal Gg1g8] })) (1... Qe2+ 2. Kf8 { [%csl Gg2,Gg4][%cal Ge2g2,Ge2g4] }) 2. Ke8 (2. Kf6 Qf8) 2... Qa8+ 3. Ke7 Qe4+ { .
Nice position to remember. We finally allow Kf8 but only when our queen can access g6 or h7:
... } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Re7f8,Ge4h7] } 4. Kf8 Qh7! { .
Instead of bringing the king when the pawn is blocked, we prevent the enemy king to go to the right side, and with our queen on the 7th rank we have the nice "allow-promotion" tricks we already know:
... } 5. Ke8 Kc6! 6. f8=Q Qd7# *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: A common trick"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "A common trick"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/EBdosdl4"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/3K4/8/4Q3/2p5/1k6 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "19:10:50"]

{ In this position, the defending king is on the right side. That means White could win if the king was 1 step away from a key square (b3 and d2). It's not the case.

Therefore it's a draw.

HOWEVER there's a common trick that White can try and will force Black to make a couple of accurate moves that you should know:

... } { [%csl Rb3,Rd2] }
1. Qb3+ Ka1 2. Qe3 { .
We can hardly add an exclamation mark to the move since the position is a draw, but it almost deserves the mark as it's setting up a clever trick:
... } 2... Kb1 3. Qe4 Kb2 4. Qe2 { .
The trick!
There's only one move for black to make a draw here:
... } 4... Ka1! { As a general rule, we go here whenever it works and that's the safest. Actually, we could have gone here one move earlier (after Qe4).
Plesae explore the other alternatives to Ka1 to see how the trick works. } (4... Kb1?? { It looks like a principled move, but it's a blunder! } 5. Kc4! c1=Q+ 6. Kb3! { and White wins } { [%csl Gb3,Gb1,Rc1][%cal Ge2a2] }) (4... Kc3?? { This does not work either. However it's not a natural move that you would think of, unless you're seen it in the next chapter in a position where it's the only move. } 5. Qe5+! { Only move to win, but a logical one, since it forces the king to the wrong side. } 5... Kd2 6. Qd4+ Ke1 7. Qc3+ Kd1 8. Qd3+ Kc1 9. Kc4 { etc }) *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: Same trick on the other side"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "Same trick on the other side"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/Ez3RMM3x"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/4K3/8/1Q6/2pk4/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "19:20:49"]

{ Let's try the trick on the other side. The chances to win are higher because the defense is more difficult:

... }
1. Qb2 { Same as before, we don't go immediately for it, we first move around a bit: } 1... Kd1 2. Qb3 Kd2 3. Qa2 { .
Here comes the trick. Now black has only one move to draw, but it's definitely not an obvious one:
... } 3... Kd3?? { Why Kc3 and not Kd3 when this one keeps the king away better? Well, White will win a tempo thanks to a pin: } (3... Kc3! { .
This is why we study endgames, my friends. If you find this move OTB congratulations, but it's much easier if you know it. Any other move loses.
... } 4. Qa1+ Kd2 $10) (3... Kc1 { [%csl Gc1] } 4. Kd4) (3... Kd1?? { this natural move has the same problem as in the other side of the pawn: } 4. Kd4 c1=Q 5. Kd3 { and White wins }) 4. Qb2! { The only move to prevent Qc1 is to walk into a pin: } 4... Kd2 5. Ke4 { and White wins } *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: An improvement over De la Villa key squares"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "An improvement over De la Villa key squares"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/1xThm0Iq"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5K2/5P2/6q1/8/2k5/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "19:35:35"]

{ According to De la Villa, since we're not 2 squares away from d7 or g6, we should use this free tempo (since the pawn is blocked) to get our king closer.

All the 3 moves that get the king closer to d7 (Kb5, Kc5 and Kd5) win.

But it turns out that e6 (the other square one knight-jump away from the promotion square) is also a valid key square. And we're only 2 steps away from there.

And that means that there's a 4th winning move in this position. One that we can remember from a similar situation: } { [%csl Gd7,Be6][%cal Gc4b5,Gc4c5,Gc4d5,Gg6h7] }
1... Qh7! 2. Ke8 { (self-pinning in the wrong side brings nothing) } { [%csl Rd7,Rg6,Ge6] } 2... Kd5! 3. f8=Q Ke6! { and Black wins } *


[Event "Queen vs pawn: from game: SaveADog vs Sparklehorse"]
[Date "2019.08.19"]
