[ChapterName "from game: SaveADog vs Sparklehorse"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gN0DmxOp/kDzCqRtF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5K2/5P2/6q1/7P/2k5/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.08.19"]
[UTCTime "19:34:58"]

{ This interesting endgame happened a week ago in this game:

https://lichess.org/CbkiIryV/black#111

White has just pushed the h pawn to h5, threatening the queen, hoping that the queen captures the pawn (which is a draw after the defending king immediately access the right side of the pawn).

From our previous chapter, we know that if there was no pawn on h5 there would be 4 winning moves: Kb5, Kc5, Kd5 and Qh7.

Since the queen is attacked, the king moves cannot work. Therefore in this beautiful endgame there's only one beautiful move to win:

... }
1... Qh7! 2. Ke8 Kd5 { .
We would do the same against h6 or Ke7.
... } 3. h6 { .
This one might be the trickiest, waiting to meet Ke6 with underpromoting to a knight.
Kd6 or Qxh6 allowing promotion to a queen cannot work either.
Kc6 intending to meet promotion with Qd7 checkmate, allows Ke7 and we probably need to repeat with Kd5.
What do we do?
We keep maneuvering now that black's king is on the wrong side:
... } 3... Kc6 (3... Qg6 4. Ke7 Qd6+ { there are other moves to win, but this is the simplest } 5. Ke8 Ke6 { Forcing underpromotion and winning in a few moves. } { [%csl Ge6] }) 4. Ke7 Kd5 5. Ke8 *


