[ChapterName "INTRO"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx/7BiMu7NV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.05"]
[UTCTime "19:08:25"]

{ After rook endgames, bishop vs knight are the most frequent endgames.

With many pawns, they're really interesting (and complex), but with just 1 pawn they're either easily solved or difficult to set simple rules for them.

Let's see some common cases to have an idea of those endgames, but concrete calculation is usually required due to the tactical nature of the bishop/knight imbalance. }
 *


[Event "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board): ::::[ Bishop vs Knight + pawn ]::::"]
[Date "2019.05.05"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "::::[ Bishop vs Knight + pawn ]::::"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx/RUvuLBPH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.05"]
[UTCTime "19:26:00"]

{ A bishop is generally a better defender against a pawn.
DRAWING CHANCES are very high here.
But because of the minor pieces imbalance, these endings are rich in tactics and small details might decide the game.

We're going to see a couple of examples and ideas that are good to remember, but concrete calculation will be required in general.

A key factor will be HOW LONG ARE THE DIAGONALS from which the bishop can chase the pawn, as we'll see in the examples. }
 *


[Event "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board): Central pawn"]
[Date "2019.05.05"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Central pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx/fYR2ih77"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "1K6/4B3/8/8/8/2n2p2/5k2/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.05"]
[UTCTime "14:13:21"]

{ In this example, the bishop can draw, but accuracy is required.

Of course, it's an extreme position: the pawn is close to promotion and it counts with the support of king and knight, while the white's king is far from helping.

The bishop wants to control one of the squares where the pawn has to go through.
In this case, only one dark square is left (f2), so we have to control it.
Generally, the bishop must use the longer diagonal.

... } { [%cal Rf2h4,Rf2e1,Gf2g1,Gf2a7] }
1. Bc5+! (1. Bh4+? { This is losing! } 1... Kg2 2. Kc7 Ne4 { [%cal Ge4g3] } 3. Be1 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5d3] } 4. Kd6 Nd3 5. Bh4 Kh3! { Now the diagonal is too short. White loses. } { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3,Rh4] }) 1... Ke2 { [%csl Re3][%cal Rc3d5,Rd5e3,Gb8c7] } 2. Bg1!! { This is a tough move to find, but worth remembering the idea.
We want to bring our king fast (Kc7), but if we do that directly, Black has a tactical way (Nd5-Ne3) to block our bishop. So we want the bishop in the other side of the pawn.
... } (2. Kc7?? Nd5+ 3. Kd6 Ne3 { [%cal Gf3f2,Gf2f1] }) (2. Kc8?? { Since Kc7 allows Nd5 with tempo we could be tempted to do this, but now the king is too slow. } 2... Nd1! { [%csl Re3][%cal Rd1e3] } 3. Bg1 Nf2 (3... Kf1) 4. Kd7 Kf1 5. Bh2 Ng4 6. Bg3 (6. Bd6 Ne3) 6... Kg2 { [%csl Rf2,Rg3] } 7. Bh4 { [%csl Rg3,Rf2] } 7... Kh3! { [%csl Rh4,Rg3,Rf2] } 8. Be1 { [%csl Rf2,Rg3,Rh4] } 8... Ne5+ { [%csl Rg3,Rh4][%cal Re5d3] } 9. Ke6 { [%csl Rh4,Rg3][%cal Re5d3] } 9... Nd3 { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3,Rh4] }) 2... Nd1 { The only winning attempt. Black wants to play Nf2, Kf1, Kf2, Kh3 etc, driving the bishop off. But white's king is just in time:
... } 3. Kc7! Nf2 4. Bh2! { Another very accurate move. We need to be ready to go to the proper diagonal depending where the knight jumps. } (4. Kd6?? Kf1 5. Bh2 Nd3! { [%csl Rf2,Re1][%cal Gf1g2] } 6. Bg3 { [%csl Rf2,Re1][%cal Gf1g2] } 6... Kg2 { [%csl Rf2,Re1,Rg3][%cal Gg2h3] } 7. Bh4 { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3][%cal Gg2h3] } 7... Kh3! { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3,Rh4] }) (4. Kd7?? Kf1 5. Bh2 Ng4! 6. Bg3 (6. Bd6 { [%cal Gd6c5] } 6... Ne3 7. Bg3 Nf5 { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3,Rh4] }) 6... Kg2 { [%csl Rg3,Rf2] } 7. Be1 { [%csl Rg3,Rf2] } 7... Ne5+! { [%csl Rg3,Rf2][%cal Re5d3] } 8. Ke6 { [%csl Rg3,Rf2][%cal Re5d3] } 8... Nd3 { [%csl Rf2,Re1,Rg3][%cal Gg2h3] } 9. Bh4 { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3][%cal Gg2h3] } 9... Kh3 { [%csl Rh4,Rg3,Rf2,Re1] }) 4... Kf1 (4... Ng4 { doesn't win either but we need to be careful: } 5. Bg1! { if the knight goes to g4 we go back to the long diagonal }) (4... Nh3 5. Bg3! { With the knight on h3 we move to the short diagonal. The knight is badly placed and an extra tempo is required for White to dominate the short diagonal, so we're just in time: } 5... Nf4 6. Kd6 Nh5 7. Bh4 Ng7 { [%cal Gg7f5] } 8. Ke5!) 5. Be5! (5. Kc6?? Ng4 6. Bd6 Ke2 7. Bc5 (7. Bg3 Ne3 { [%csl Re1,Rf2,Rg3,Rh4][%cal Ge3f5] }) 7... Ne3) 5... Ng4 6. Bd4 Ke2 7. Bg1! { draw
Of course, other positions have other subtleties, but ideas are similar.
Important conclusions:
1) When the bishop has 2 diagonals consisting of 5 squares, we don't need king support to draw
2) When shorter diagonal consists of 4 squares, the bishop can be driven off. It's not easy though, so the defending king only loses if he is too far away.
3) If the shorter diagonal consists of less than 4 squares, there are a lot of winning chances. } *


[Event "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board): Rook's pawn"]
[Date "2019.05.05"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Rook's pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx/66pt6dAD"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/B6n/7p/6k1/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.05"]
[UTCTime "17:42:37"]

{ Rook's pawns create more problems for the defense. The shorter diagonal is very short and even disappears when the pawn reaches the 7th rank.

This case arises quite often and contains an unexpected drawing resource we must know.

Black threatens to put king on g1 and knight on g2.

... } { [%cal Gg2g1,Gh4g2] }
1. Bd7! { The pawn must be on the 7th rank for the drawing resource to work!
... } (1. Bc6+?? Kg1 2. Bd5 Ng2+ { [%cal Gh3h2,Gh2h1] }) 1... h2 2. Bc6+ Kg1 { .
How do we stop now Ng2 followed by promotion?
... } { [%cal Gh4g2] } (2... Nf3+ 3. Ke2) 3. Bh1!! { .
Amazing but saving resource!
... } 3... Kxh1 (3... Ng2+ 4. Ke2 Nf4+ 5. Ke1 $10) (3... Nf5 4. Bf3) 4. Kf2! { important: go to same colour as the knight } { [%csl Gf2,Gh4] } (4. Kf1?? Nf5 5. Kf2 Ng3 { [%csl Rf1] }) 4... Nf3 5. Kf1 Nd2+ 6. Kf2 Ne4+ 7. Kf1 $10 { .
An important trick/resource to remember.
But of course, it only works when the king is close enough. } *


