[Date "2019.05.05"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Rook's pawn (defending king is far)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx/zTnl0GyJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/5B2/8/1n6/8/p1k1K3/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.05"]
[UTCTime "17:48:26"]

{ This position is from the game Stein - Dorfman, USSR, 1970

The difference with the previous chapter is that now the defending king is a bit further away. }
1... Nd3 { [%cal Gd3b2] } 2. Ba1 Nb2 { .
Unlike the previous chapter, Black's king can avoid getting trapped in the corner now.
... } 3. Ke1 (3. Ke3 Na4! 4. Kd4 (4. Ke2 Kc1) 4... Kb1 5. Kd3 Nc5+! 6. Kc3 Kxa1 7. Kc2 Nb3 { [%csl Rc1] }) 3... Na4! (3... Kb1?? { was played in the game and ended in a draw with the resource we already know }) 4. Ke2 Kc1 5. Ke1 (5. Kd3 Kb1 6. Kd2 Nb2) (5. Ke3 Kb1 6. Kd3 Nc5+!) 5... Nc5! { [%cal Gc5b3] } 6. Ke2 (6. Bg7 Nd3+ 7. Ke2 Nb2) 6... Kb1! { .
The key: white king cannot go to the ideal square (d2).
... } 7. Kd1 (7. Bg7 Na4!) 7... Nd3 8. Kd2 Nb2! { .
Zugzwang!
White would like to pass the turn to make a draw.
... } 9. Kc3 Kxa1 { [%csl Rc1][%cal Rc3c1] } 10. Kc2 Nd3 { [%csl Rc1] } *


[Event "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board): Nakamura vs Kasparov (St Louis, 2017)"]
[Date "2019.05.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Nakamura vs Kasparov (St Louis, 2017)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/a4DRdtUx/jCcFuM4W"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/3k4/8/P3K2p/7P/5bN1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.06"]
[UTCTime "12:18:23"]

{ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iw3rsUIC3RU&start=9925

This endgame was a draw all the time, but some tricks were there so Garry had to be careful.

... }
1. Kf3 Bg3 2. Kg4 Kc5 3. Nxh4 Bf2 4. Nf5 Kb4 5. Ng3 Kxa4 { .
We reach our bishop vs knight endgame.
As we know, the bishop is a great defender in such a scenario. Despite the Black king being far, the pawn has to traverse 3 dark squares, so the knight has to do a lot of maneuvres and the Black king will have time to help.
Because we have a rook pawn we know the king MUST help in the defence.
... } 6. h4 Kb5 7. h5 Be3 8. Ne4 Kc6 9. Ng5 Kd7 10. h6 Ke7 11. h7 Bd4 12. Kf5 Ba1 13. Kg6 { .
This should be an easy draw now. We've seen positions worst than this (white king on g8). With Black's king controlling f7, White's king cannot access g8.
Kasparov will continue defending this way by moving the king, when required, along the squares e7, e8 and f8, not to lose control of f7.
... } { [%csl Rf7,Rg7][%cal Ga1g7] } 13... Bb2 14. Nf7 Ba1 15. Nh6 Bh8 (15... Bb2 16. Ng8+ { commentators were worried about this "trick", but it's not winning } 16... Ke6! { [%csl Rf6] } (16... Kf8?? 17. Nf6 { [%cal Gh7h8] })) 16. Ng4 Ba1 17. Ne3 Bh8 18. Nd5+ Ke6 { .
Since Kasparov rejected Kf8 here, he probably understood that the easiest defending setup is to keep moving the king between e7 and e6, stopping both the incursion Kf7 and the blockade Nf6.
Of course, this is not an immediate trivial way to draw, because the knight can try to maneuvre to block on g7 instead when the bishop is out, or to f7 to push the bishop out. But as we've seen in the last moves, the knight is so slow to make these ideas dangerous.
... } (18... Kf8 { Kasparov almost played this move, which is not losing, but he didn't like it } 19. Nf6 { Now only one move draws: } 19... Ke7! (19... Bg7 20. Nd7+)) 19. Nf4+ Ke7 20. Nh3 Ke6 21. Ng5+ Ke7 (21... Kd7?? { Let's explore this obvious blunder to refresh our mind on how to win this position: } 22. Kf7 Ba1 23. Ne4 { [%cal Ge4f6] } 23... Bh8 24. Nf6+ Kd8 25. Nh5 Kd7 26. Kf8! Kd8 27. Nf4! { remember, we set up the fork on g6 and then we go Kg8 } 27... Kd7 28. Kg8! { and the fork on g6 prevents the "drawing" move Ke7 } { [%csl Re7] } 28... Ke8 29. Nh5 Ke7 30. Ng7 Kf6 31. Kxh8 Kf7 32. Ne6 { [%csl Rf8] }) 22. Nf7 Ba1 23. h8=Q Bxh8 *


[Event "Knight vs Bishop (wiht 1 pawn on the board): ::::[ Knight vs Bishop + pawn ]::::"]
