[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/4K3/3P1n2/3k4/8/8/2B5/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.05"]
[UTCTime "20:11:12"]

{ When the pawn is less advanced, zugzwang is impossible if the defending king is in front of the pawn.

In other cases, winning chances exist when the knight position is unstable.

This example position features both a defending king not in front of the pawn and an unstable knight. White wins, but complex tactics are involved:

... }
1. Bb3+! (1. Be4+?? Ke5!! $10) 1... Kc5 (1... Ke5 2. Be6! { zugzwang }) 2. Ba2 (2. Ke6?? Nh7!! 3. Ke7 Nf8!! $10 4. Bc2 Kc6 5. Bb1 (5. Ba4+ Kc5 6. Be8 Kd5 7. Bf7+ Kc6 8. Bh5 Kc5!! $10 (8... Kd5?? 9. Bf3+! Ke5 10. Be4!! { zugzwang })) 5... Kd5!! (5... Kc5?? 6. Be4! { zugzwang }) 6. Bd3 Kc6 $10) 2... Kc6 (2... Ng4 3. Bb1 Nf6 4. Be4 Ng8+ 5. Kd7 Nf6+ 6. Ke6!) 3. Ke6!! Nh7 (3... Ne4 4. Bd5+) (3... Kc5 4. Bb1 (4. Bd5 Nxd5 (4... Ne8 5. d7) (4... Nh7 5. Ke7 Nf6 6. Be4 Ng8+ 7. Ke6 Nf6 8. Bg2 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc5d6] } 8... Nh7 9. Bf3 Nf6 10. Be4) 5. d7) 4... Kc6 5. Bc2 Kc5 6. Be4) 4. Bd5+ Kc5 5. Ke7 Nf6 (5... Nf8 6. Be4!!) 6. Bf3 Ng8+ 7. Ke6 Nf6 8. Be4!! $18 { zugzwang
It's hard to take any general conclusion.
No theoretical rule can be established and accurate calculation is required.
However searching for zugzwang positions (as the one we see now) is very useful to guide the calculation process. } *


