{ As usual, everything changes with Rook's pawns.
The edge of the board is very dangerous for the knight.

In this case, the drawing method consists of entering with the knight the circuit shown in blue. If we can enter that circuit of 4 squares, then it's a draw.

It's easy to remember because the circuit is a square in which one corner is the square in front of the pawn.

... } { [%csl Be3,Bf1,Bh2,Bg4][%cal Be3g4,Bg4e3,Be3f1,Bf1e3,Bf1h2,Bh2f1,Bh2g4,Bg4h2] }
1. Ng4+! { .
Once in the circuit, whenever our knight is attacked we follow the direction in the circuit where it goes to a safe square.
... } { [%csl Bg4,Be3,Bf1,Bh2] } 1... Kg3 { [%csl Bf1,Be3,Bg4,Bh2][%cal Rg4h2,Gg4e3] } 2. Ne3 { .
If Black pushes the pawn, there's a fork on f1.
... } { [%csl Bh2,Bg4,Be3,Bf1] } 2... Kf3 { [%csl Bf1,Be3,Bg4,Bh2][%cal Ge3f1,Re3g4] } 3. Nf1 { [%csl Bf1,Be3,Bg4,Bh2] } 3... Kf2 { [%csl Bf1,Be3,Bg4,Bh2][%cal Rf1e3,Gf1h2] } 4. Nh2 { draw } { [%csl Bh2,Bf1,Be3,Bg4] } *


