{ Now that we know the circuit, there's no way we get this wrong.
But anyway let's see what happens if the knight goes to the wrong square (if our opponent does it, it's useful to know how to win!):

... } { [%csl Bg4,Be3,Bf1,Bh2] }
1. Nf3+?? { [%csl Rf3,Bg4,Be3,Bf1,Bh2][%cal Re5f3] } 1... Kg2 { .
The knight cannot keep h2 controlled nor can it threaten a fork.
Therefore we check (what else?):
... } 2. Nh4+ (2. Ne1+ Kg3 { [%csl Rf3][%cal Rg3f3,Gh3h2,Gh2h1] }) 2... Kf2 { No way to stop the pawn. } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Rf2f3,Gh3h2,Gh2h1] } *


