{ [%cal Gc3d4,Gc3c2,Gc3d3] }
1... Kd4 { .
Black anticipates the barrier and wins an important tempo. Now Ng3 would be losing, but we have a different barrier:
... } (1... Kd3 { we should use the "normal" barrier: } 2. Ng3! { [%csl Re4,Re3,Re2,Rd2][%cal Gc7d6,Gd6e5,Ge5f4] }) (1... Kc2 { we should use the "normal" barrier: } 2. Ng3! { [%csl Rd2,Re2,Re3,Re4][%cal Gc7d6,Gd6e5,Ge5f4] }) 2. Nf2! { .
the knight creates a perfect barrier just in time } { [%csl Re4,Rd3,Be3,Be5] } (2. Ng3?? { the "normal" barrier fails, because Black's king is too close now: } { [%csl Re4,Re3,Re2,Rd2,Gd4] } 2... Ke5! 3. Kc6 Kf4 4. Nh1 Kf3 { [%cal Rc6d5,Rd5e4,Re4f3] } 5. Kd5 Kg2 6. Ke4 Kxh1 { [%cal Gh1g1] } 7. Kf3 Kg1) 2... Kc3 { [%csl Rd3,Re3,Re4,Re5] } 3. Kd6 { [%csl Rd3,Re3,Re4,Re5] } 3... Kd2 { [%csl Rd3,Re3,Re4,Re5] } 4. Ke5 { [%csl Rd3,Re3,Re4,Re5] } 4... Ke2 { .
Again, the barrier is no longer important, but sacrificing the knight on h1 is:
... } { [%csl Rd3,Re3,Re4,Re5] } 5. Nh1! Kf3 6. Kd4 Kg2 7. Ke3 Kxh1 8. Kf2 $10 *


