{ If the black pawn is blocked in any square above the line (including the squares in the line itself), then White wins regardless of the position of the kings!

If the pawn is pushed beyond that line, sometimes it will be a win and sometimes it won't, depending on the kings' position.

In practice, knowing this is not very useful, as accuracy is really hard. } { [%cal Ga4b6,Gb6d4,Gd4e4,Ge4g6,Gg6h4,Gh4g6,Gg6e4,Ge4d4,Gd4b6,Gb6a4] }
 *


[Event "2 knights vs pawn: The checkmate technique"]
[Date "1955"]
[White "A. Chéron"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "2 knights vs pawn"]
[ChapterName "The checkmate technique"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/eYXrigQn/yYbc5a2Z"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/2N5/6p1/k1K3N1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The pawn has been pushed beyond Troitsky's line, but Black's king is trapped in a corner near the pawn (if the king was trapped on a8 instead this would be a draw), so White can win.

As we will see, precise technique is required here because Black's pawn is way too close to promote: } { [%csl Rb1,Rb2,Rb3,Ra3] }
1. Kc3! { Since Black's pawn is only 2 moves away from promoting we have to choose very carefully where to bring the g2 knight. It turns out it can reach c2 in 2 moves, so let's clear that square for it. } { [%csl Rb2,Rb3,Ra3] } 1... Kb1 { Trying to escape via c1 } { [%csl Rc2,Rb2][%cal Rb1c1] } 2. Kd2! { [%csl Rc1,Rc2,Rb2] } 2... Ka1 { [%csl Rb2] } (2... Ka2 3. Kc2) 3. Kc1! { Using opposition we manage to push the king back to a1 on the next move: } { [%csl Rb1,Rb2] } 3... Ka2 { [%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rb1] } 4. Kc2! { This is the same as the starting position, but it's Black to move (so we triangulated). Being therefore pushed to a1, we manage to keep Black's king trapped on the first rank instead of the a-file, which is going to be convenient for the checkmate pattern. } { [%csl Rb1,Rb2,Rb3,Ra3] } 4... Ka1 { [%csl Rb1,Rb2] } 5. Kb3! { [%csl Rb2,Ra2] } 5... Kb1 { Now the next task is to reach this same position but with the knight on d3 instead of c4, in order to keep the king trapped on a1-b1.
This involves more maneuvering: } { [%csl Ra2,Rb2,Rc2] } 6. Nb2! { Esta jugada puede parecer poco intuitiva, pero decíamos que queríamos el caballo en d3. Ce5 no gana porque es importante controlar d1 para la siguiente jugada. } { [%csl Rb2,Ra2,Rc2] } 6... Kc1 { [%csl Rc2,Rb2,Rd1] } 7. Kc3! { Note that a king and 1 knight are able to trap the opponent's king if coordinated precisely. } { [%csl Rb2,Rc2,Rd2,Rd1] } 7... Kb1 { [%csl Rc2,Rb2] } 8. Nd3 { [%csl Rb2,Rc2,Rc1] } 8... Ka1!? { the most challenging, as Black tries to regain the opposition } { [%csl Rb2] } (8... Ka2 { maybe more intuitive, but less challenging actually } 9. Kb4!) 9. Kb4! { better than Kb3 so we can regain the opposition on the next move } { [%csl Rb2] } 9... Ka2 { [%csl Ra3,Rb3,Rb2] } 10. Ka4! { [%csl Rb3,Ra3,Rb2] } 10... Ka1 { [%csl Rb2] } 11. Ka3! { [%csl Rb2,Ra2] } 11... Kb1 { [%csl Ra2,Rb2,Rc1] } 12. Kb3! { There we go!
Now we're finally ready to bring the other knight and deliver checkmate :-) } { [%csl Rc1,Rc2,Rb2,Ra2] } 12... Ka1 { [%csl Ra2,Rb2] } 13. Ne3 { [%csl Rb2,Ra2] } (13. Nge1 { would work the same way }) 13... g2 { [%csl Ra2,Rb2] } 14. Nc2+ { [%csl Ra2,Rb2,Ra1] } 14... Kb1 { [%csl Rc1,Rc2,Rb2,Ra2,Ra1] } 15. Na3+ { [%csl Rc1,Rc2,Rb2,Rb1,Ra2] } 15... Ka1 { And if there was no pawn this would be a draw, because the knight on d3 needs 2 tempi to get to c2, which would lead to a stalemate if there was no pawn. } { [%csl Rb1,Rb2,Ra2] } 16. Ne1 { [%csl Rb1,Rb2,Ra2] } (16. Nb4 { also working, obviously }) 16... g1=Q { [%csl Ra2,Rb2,Rb1] } 17. Nec2# { This was an instructive but extreme example.
In practice, if the pawn is blocked farther away from promoting, you'll find it much easier to maneuver your knights to deliver checkmate, as you have more tempi available for the 2nd knight.
The first part (trapping the king) is generally the difficult task. } *


