{ This game shows how in practice being accurate is really difficult with both sides.

White's technique is perfect and despite being a drawn endgame he managed to win.

I included the whole game for reference, but please move forward to move 56 for Black to start seeing the endgame. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4 b4 9. a5 d6 10. d3 Be6 11. Nbd2 Qc8 12. h3 Rb8 13. Nc4 h6 14. Be3 Rd8 15. Qe2 Bf8 16. Nfd2 g6 17. Ba4 Qb7 18. Qf3 Nh7 19. Qg3 Bg7 20. f4 exf4 21. Bxf4 Nf6 22. Be3 Nd7 23. Qf2 Nc5 24. Bxc6 Qxc6 25. Bd4 Bxd4 26. Qxd4 b3 27. c3 Nd7 28. Qe3 d5 29. exd5 Bxd5 30. Qxh6 Re8 31. Ne3 Ne5 32. c4 Bxg2 33. Nxg2 Nxd3 34. Re3 Qc5 35. Kh1 Nf2+ 36. Kh2 Qd6+ 37. Kg1 Rxe3 38. Qxe3 Nxh3+ 39. Kh1 Kg7 40. Re1 Rh8 41. Qe5+ Qxe5 42. Rxe5 Ng5+ 43. Kg1 Rd8 44. Rd5 Rxd5 45. cxd5 Kf6 46. Nxb3 Ne4 47. Ne3 Ke5 48. Kg2 f5 49. Nc1 f4 50. Nc2 Kxd5 51. Nb4+ Kc4 52. Nxa6 Kb5 53. Nxc7+ Kxa5 54. Nd3 Nd2 55. Ne6 Kb5 56. Nexf4 Nc4 { Note that taking the free pawn on g6 is an immediate draw. } 57. Ne6! { This is a theoretical draw, but we can still put an exclamation mark to the move that challenges the opponent the most right? :-)
The knight is going to block the pawn on g5 if allowed, but most importantly it steps away from the path of the pawn. Since the pawn wants to be pushed as much as possible it would be terrible to allow it with tempo on the knight on f4. } (57. Nxg6? Nxb2 $10) 57... Nxb2! { Very logical and it "forces" the draw (at least theoretically, but there's still work to do).
It also wins a tempo on the d3 knight so it secures the g5 push. } 58. Nxb2 g5! { It's pushed beyond Troitsky's line and the king is not in trouble, so it should be a draw.
But again, that knowledge in practice is not super-useful as it all depends on showing good technique. } 59. Nd4+! { There was no way to block the pawn on g5 so this knight is going to g3 to keep the pawn blocked on g4. } 59... Kc5 60. Nf5! g4 61. Ng3! Kd4 { Now comes the most difficult part for the strong side: push the opponent's king into an edge/corner only using the king and one knight.
We can learn a lot on how White does this in the game.
Note that sometimes the knight on g3 also helps by covering some squares such as e4 or f5. } 62. Kf2 { [%csl Re4,Re3,Rd3,Rc4] } 62... Kc3 { [%csl Rd3,Rc4] } 63. Nd1+ { [%csl Rc3,Rb2] } 63... Kd3 { [%csl Re2,Re3,Re4,Rc3] } 64. Ke1! { [%csl Re4,Re3,Re2,Rd2,Rc3] } 64... Kc4 { [%csl Rc3] } 65. Kd2 { [%csl Rc3,Rd3] } 65... Kd4 { [%csl Rd3,Rc3,Re3,Re4] } 66. Nc3 { [%csl Re4,Re3,Rd3,Rc3,Rd5] } 66... Kc4 { [%csl Rd5,Rd3,Rc3] } 67. Nce2 { [%csl Rc3,Rd3,Rd4] } 67... Kd5 { [%csl Rd4,Re4] } 68. Kc3 { [%csl Rc4,Rd4,Re4] } 68... Kc5 { [%csl Rd4,Rc4,Rb4] } 69. Nf4 { [%csl Rb4,Rc4,Rd5,Rd4] } 69... Kc6 { [%csl Rd5] } 70. Kc4 { [%csl Rd5,Rc5,Rb5] } 70... Kd6 { [%csl Rd5,Re6,Rc5] } 71. Nd3 { [%csl Re5,Rd5,Rc5] } 71... Kc6 { [%csl Rc5,Rd5,Rb5] } 72. Ne5+ { [%csl Rb5,Rc6,Rc5,Rd5,Rd7] } 72... Kd6 { [%csl Rd7,Rc6,Rc5,Rd5] } 73. Kd4 { [%csl Rd5,Rc5,Rc6,Rd7,Re5] } 73... Ke6 { [%csl Rd7,Rf7,Rf5,Re5,Rd5] } 74. Nc4 { [%csl Rd5,Rd6,Re5,Rf5] } 74... Kf6 { [%csl Rf5,Re5] } 75. Ne3 { [%csl Re5,Rf5] } 75... Ke6 { [%csl Rd5,Re5,Rf5] } 76. Nef5 { [%csl Rf5,Re5,Rd5,Rd6] } 76... Kd7 { [%csl Rd6,Re7] } 77. Kd5 { [%csl Re7,Re6,Rd6,Rc6] } 77... Kc7 { [%csl Rc6,Rd6] } 78. Nd4 { [%csl Rd6,Rc6] } 78... Kd7?! { It doesn't lose, but Sevian chooses the wrong plan.
It's hard to assess whether the king can receive checkmate on a8, but in any case it would have been the best corner to target (farthest from the pawn).
Black is being resilient. But in this move and the next ones, he misses the opportunity to run towards a8. } { [%csl Rc6,Rd6,Re6] } 79. Ne6 { [%csl Re6,Rd6,Rc6,Rc7] } 79... Ke7?! { [%csl Re6,Rd6] } 80. Nc5 { [%csl Rd7,Rd6,Re6] } 80... Kf7?! { [%csl Re6] } 81. Kd6 { [%csl Re6,Re7] } 81... Kf6?? { Objectively this was the only mistake of Sevian (Ke8 was a draw).
It was tempting to come to f6 to threaten Kg5, but this is actually what leads to the king to be trapped on h8. } { [%csl Rf5,Re5,Re6,Re7][%cal Rf6g5] } 82. Nce4+! { Stopping Kg5 right on time! } { [%csl Rg5,Rf6,Rf5,Re5,Re6,Re7] } 82... Kf7 { [%csl Rf6,Re6,Re7] } 83. Kd7 { [%csl Rf6,Re6,Re7,Re8] } 83... Kf8 { [%csl Re8,Re7] } 84. Nd6 { [%csl Re7,Re8,Rf7] } 84... Kg7 { [%csl Rf7] } 85. Ke6 { [%csl Rf7,Rf6] } 85... Kg6 { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rf5,Rh5] } 86. Nde4! { Again stopping Kg5 right on time. } { [%csl Rh5,Rg5,Rf5,Rf6,Rf7] } 86... Kg7 { [%csl Rf7,Rf6] } 87. Ke7 { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rf8] } 87... Kg8 { [%csl Rf8,Rf7] } 88. Kf6 { [%csl Rf7,Rg7] } 88... Kh7 { [%csl Rg7,Rg6] } (88... Kf8 { [%csl Rg7,Rf7,Re7] } 89. Nd6! { [%csl Re8,Re7,Rf7,Rg7] }) 89. Nf5!! { White calculated the checkmate. With the pawn 3 tempi away from promotion, White has enough now to deliver checkmate. } { [%csl Rg7,Rg6,Rh6] } 89... Kg8!? { Sevian breaks the rule of always pushing the pawn when possible, probably because he saw the checkmate after g3 and Kf7.
So he tries Kg8 that stops Kf7 and attempts an escape via f8. Good try! } { [%csl Rg7,Rf7] } (89... g3 { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rg7] } 90. Kf7! { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rg7,Rg8] } 90... g2 { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rg7,Rg8] } 91. Ng5+ { [%csl Rh6,Rh7,Rg6,Rg7,Rg8] } 91... Kh8 { [%csl Rh7,Rg7,Rg8] } 92. Nh4 { [%csl Rh7,Rg7,Rg8] } 92... g1=Q { [%csl Rh7,Rg7,Rg8] } 93. Ng6#) 90. Ke7! { White again has the checkmate calculated and doesn't need to block the pawn anymore.
Now Sevian has no other option but to push the pawn and see White finish the job: } { [%csl Rf7,Rf8,Rg7] } 90... g3 { [%csl Rg7,Rf7,Rf8] } (90... Kh7 { this would be absurd now because Black would have just lost a tempo } { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rg7,Rg8] } 91. Kf7! { mate in 3 } { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rg7,Rg8] }) 91. Nf6+ { [%csl Rh7,Rg7,Rf7,Rf8] } 91... Kh8 { [%csl Rg7,Rh7] } 92. Kf8! { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Keeping f7 available for the knight to deliver checkmate.
Sevian resignes because it's mate in 2. } { [%csl Gf7,Rg8,Rg7,Rh7][%cal Bf5d6,Bd6f7,Bf5h6,Bh6f7] } 1-0


