{ The black queen and king are a bit trapped. How can we use that? }
1. a5+ { Correct!
Because of the fork on c6, the king is pushed back to b7 and black's pieces start to lack mobility. } 1... Kb7 { How to put black in zugzwang? } 2. Nc6 { Correct!
Black has only one legal move to keep the queen alive. } 2... Qa8 { This is the tricky part of the puzzle. Where is the zugzwang now? } 3. Kg7! { Correct!
Every legal move by black will lose the queen. Bravo! Puzzle solved :-) } *


[Event "Cool Puzzles: Chapter 5"]
[Date "2018.12.14"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Cool Puzzles"]
[ChapterName "Chapter 5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/UItSsgwM/KGmo1IDY"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5N2/p5p1/k7/P3pP2/2K3pP/6P1/4n3/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.14"]
[UTCTime "10:52:42"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ The position seems roughly equal but both sides are trying to promote. Black's knight will take on g3, giving black 2 dangerous passed pawns. Can we strike first? }
1. f6 { Correct!
Immediately creating a passed pawn. } 1... gxf6 { Keep the counterplay going! } 2. h5 { Correct! } 2... Nxg3 3. h6 { Correct! } 3... Nf5 { Is black stopping our pawn in time? Black wants to play Nd6+ and Nf7. Hmmmm... } 4. h7 { Correct! } 4... Nd6+ { Ok. Now black is going to stop our pawn with Nf7. And black has 3 passed pawns prepared to run. What can our king do against that? } 5. Kb4 { Correct!
The king sets up a resource here for the next move. } 5... Nf7 { Black stopped our pawn and is ready to start running theirs. What strong threat can we create to force a winning line? } 6. Ne6 { Correct!
This forces Kb7 to stop the checkmate and then we have a great resource to win. } (6. Nd7 { This is not enough, since after Kb7 we have no more threats and black will eventualy win. }) 6... Kb7 7. Nd8+ { Correct!
We promote first. Puzzle solved :-) } *


[Event "Cool Puzzles: Chapter 6"]
[Date "2018.12.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Cool Puzzles"]
[ChapterName "Chapter 6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/UItSsgwM/RpDEq06f"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "6k1/7p/3P4/7B/7K/4b2N/5p1p/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.18"]
[UTCTime "09:56:57"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ White is a piece up, but look at those black pawns about to promote! How can white save this position? }
1. d7 { Yes! Counterplay! } 1... Bb6 2. Nxf2 { Yes! Stopping promotion for a move and distracting the bishop from defending d8. } 2... Bxf2+ 3. Kg5 { Yes! Did you see the stalemate trick we're after? :-) } (3. Kg4 { This blocks our own bishop. If black plays Bb6 now, black will promote and we won't, since we don't have Bf3. }) (3. Kh3 { Allowing promotion with check? Not good! }) 3... Bh4+ { Black didn't promote because with our king on g5 we would promote with check and a forced checkmate would follow. Now black wants us to take the bishop to promote with check. What do we do? } 4. Kh6 { Bravo! Now when black promotes to a queen we do d8=Q+ and Bxd8 is stalemate! } 4... h1=B { Wait! Black promotes to bishop! What do we do? } 5. Bf3 { Awesome! Black is forced to take it because otherwise Bxh1 is an immediate draw. } 5... Bxf3 6. d8=Q+ { Congratulations! Puzzle solved :-) } (6. d8=R+ { This might be drawing or not, since after Kf7 the position is complicated, with a slight advantage for black due to the bishop pair vs the rook. No need to do this. }) *


