{ Welcome!

First time here?

- To study, just follow the chapters in order
- To practice, start with TEST in chapter 9

:-)

. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 { .
In this study, I will recommend playing Bc5 instead and I will intentionally call that "the BEST way", thinking of people that usually get Fried-Livered: from all the ways to avoid it, this is the one closest to their repertoire.
But of course, there's no BEST way from a theoretical point of view :-)
. } 4. Ng5 { .
The Fried Liver Attack happens from this position, after a series of decisions by both players. In this study, we will cover the different ways to prevent it and how to play it if you don't.
If you reach this position (which you could have avoided already), there's no choice but to play d5.
. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7] } 4... d5 5. exd5 { .
The Fried Liver Attack happens only if we take the pawn on d5. That pawn is actually a good shelter for us since it prevents the bishop from attacking f7. Therefore, keeping the pawn alive is the safer approach.
A number of moves have been tried here, but the main ones would be Na5, b5 and Nd4.
. } { [%cal Rf6d5] } 5... Nxd5 { .
THIS IS WHAT YOU SHOULDN'T DO
. } 6. Nxf7 { .
Funnily enough, Nxf7 is not the best move for white (d4 is), but it's dangerous for black in practical play anyway.
Starting with chapter 11, we're going to cover how to play the Fried Liver with black, in case you reach this dangerous position. } *


