1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { .
This is one of the best moments to avoid the Fried Liver while still playing a regular Italian game.
Nf6 is the main move, but Bc5 is almost as main as that one, and when the Fried Liver is not played they tend to transpose (they lead to the same position).
. } { [%cal Rg8f6] } 3... Bc5 { .
By developing the bishop first, white has no option to put the knight on g5, since our queen protects the square.
If white tries to fried-liver us in the next move we'll be ready to castle, for example:
. } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gf8c5] } (3... Nf6 { Your usual move to keep dangerously heading towards the Fried Liver. } { [%csl Rf6] }) 4. O-O Nf6 5. Ng5 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7] } 5... O-O { No problem!
.
-----[[ One last note ]]-------------------------------
The move 3 ... Bc5 allows white to play the Evans Gambit, a weapon you would not face with 3 ... Nf6.
Since it's important to be aware of this, I included a recipe against the Evans Gambit from chapter 13. } *


