[Event "How to survive the Fried Liver Attack: Move 5: last call"]
[Date "2019.01.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C59"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Two Knights Defense, Polerio Defense, Suhle Defense"]
[StudyName "How to survive the Fried Liver Attack"]
[ChapterName "Move 5: last call"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ehCEPts4/h3CsHgsh"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.10"]
[UTCTime "12:24:05"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 { .
This is the last call to avoid the Fried Liver. If you take on d5 now you allow it.
So DON'T TAKE ON d5.
Let's follow the main line instead:
. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rf6d5] } 5... Na5! { .
Let's understand this move.
Black intentionally allows white to retain the extra pawn on d5 because that pawn is a good shelter for black since it stops the bishop from attacking f7 (as opposed to taking it with the knight that would open the bishop's attack against f7 again).
Of course, we had to save the attacked knight on c6, and with this move, we attack the bishop and try to break white's active pieces (knight and bishop) coordination. We'll attack the knight in the future with h6 to force it to a worse square.
For example, if we follow the main line:
. } (5... b5 { Ulvestad Variation
It's not as well known as Na5 so it might be a surprise weapon, but it's tricky. Black also gets good compensation for the pawn: } 6. Bxb5 Qxd5 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. O-O Bb7 9. f3 Bc5+ 10. Kh1 h6 11. Nh3 O-O-O!) (5... Nd4 { Fritz Variation
Another tricky one } 6. c3 b5 7. cxd4 bxc4 8. dxe5 Nxd5 9. d4 Bb4+ 10. Kf1 { only move } (10. Bd2?? { for some reason, this blunder is the main move in the database XD } 10... Qxg5 11. Bxb4 Qxg2 { black is winning }) 10... Bf5 { Black has a great position. }) 6. Bb5+ { White tries to keep the extra pawn } 6... c6! { We allow white to trade pawns and retain the extra pawn, but in return we get a great lead in development because we're attacking white's developed pieces. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6b5] } 7. dxc6 bxc6 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6b5] } 8. Be2 h6 { [%csl Rg5][%cal Gh6g5] } 9. Nf3 e4 { .
I would suggest remembering the mainline only to this point since there are plenty of options from this position.
However, let's show a few more moves in the mainline so you can understand how black's lead in development gives an easy play for the pawn:
. } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Ge4f3] } 10. Ne5 Bd6 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gd6e5] } 11. d4 exd3 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gd6e5] } 12. Nxd3 O-O 13. O-O Qc7 { .
Black's lead in development gives full compensation for the pawn.
. } { [%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1,Ge6,Gf5,Gg4,Ga6,Gb7,Gc4][%cal Gc8a6,Gc8g4,Gc8f5,Gc8e6,Gc8b7,Gf8e8,Ga8b8,Ga8d8,Ga5c4,Gc4e5] } *


