[ChapterName "Summary on avoiding it"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ehCEPts4/mIuE7z6u"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "00:31:51"]

{ You have several opportunities to avoid the Fried Liver at different moments:

. }
1. e4 e5 { .
There are many alternative openings to 1 ... e5
See chapter 3 for an overview of the main ones.
. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Re7e5] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { .
There are a couple of moves that you can play instead of Nc6 (see chapter 4).
. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rb8c6] } 3. Bc4 Nf6 { .
If you play Bc5 instead of Nf6 you will totally avoid the Fried Liver while still very likely transpose to your usual position from this opening.
Therefore, this is my main recommendation.
. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Rg8f6] } 4. Ng5 d5 { no alternative here } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd7d5] } 5. exd5 { .
Several options now to avoid the Fried Liver. The main line would be Na5 (see chapter 7). } 5... Na5 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gc6a5] } (5... b5 { (see chapter 7) }) (5... Nd4 { (see chapter 7) }) (5... Nxd5 { Nooooooo :-( } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rf6d5] }) *


