{ This section is Work In Progress. I'll add more chapters in the future :-)

For now let's see a quick overview of it:

. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 { .
Remember, 3 ... Bc5 instead is my recommendation (chapter 5).
. } 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 { .
Remember, you could still avoid the Fried Liver with a number of moves discussed in chapter 7.
. } 6. Nxf7 { .
Ok, let's take it from here. How do we play now?
Obviously, we have to take the knight now:
. } { [%csl Rh8,Rd8,Gf7][%cal Rf7d8,Rf7h8] } (6. d4! { This is even better than the Fried Liver.
You better pray white does not know this if you're trying to go for the Fried Liver. }) 6... Kxf7 7. Qf3+ { .
This is a fork. There's only one move that saves the piece so... scary as it is, it's the only move again:
. } { [%csl Rf7,Rd5][%cal Rf3f7,Rf3d5] } 7... Ke6 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5] } 8. Nc3 { .
Our knight is pinned so white keeps adding attackers to it.
There are 2 ways to defend it now: Ne7 or Nb4.
They both have the same evaluation more or less, but in the practice I found Ne7 to be slightly safer so I will recommend that for now: } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Rc3d5,Rc4d5,Rf3d5] } 8... Ne7 { Compared to the Nb4 line, white can castle and play slowly because the compensation is more or less permanent (we need a lot of moves to bring our king to safety).
But if you ask me, having a king on e6 I like it when white's best plan is to play slowly :-)
The logical follow-up plan for black is to defend the extra knight with c6 and then walk the king towards c7. } { [%cal Gc7c6,Be6d6,Bd6c7] } (8... Nb4 { this is tempting because it threatens a fork on c2, but the knight was better defending than attacking and white does not really mind to give the rook to kill us: } 9. a3 Nxc2+ 10. Kd1 Nxa1 11. Nxd5 { Yes, we took the rook but... look at our king now. } { [%cal Rc4e6,Rh1e1,Rd2d4,Rd5b6,Rd5c7,Rd5f6,Rd5f4] } 11... Kd6 { White is going to keep attacking very strongly from here. } { [%cal Gh1e1,Gd2d4] }) *


[Event "How to survive the Fried Liver Attack: ::::[ THE EVANS GAMBIT ]:::::"]
[Date "2019.01.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C51"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Evans Gambit, Anderssen Variation, Cordel Line"]
[StudyName "How to survive the Fried Liver Attack"]
[ChapterName "::::[ THE EVANS GAMBIT ]:::::"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ehCEPts4/wnPimkNH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.10"]
[UTCTime "13:46:42"]

{ I cannot recommend 3 ... Bc5 without talking about the Evans Gambit.

The Evans Gambit is the only scary thing that we allow with Bc5 and we don't allow with Nf6.

Therefore we can call this option the drawback of Bc5.

. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 { .
This is the Evans Gambit.
It's not as dangerous as the Fried Liver Attack, but it's a good try for white to get a strong initiative.
It's out of the scope of this study to go for a deep understanding of the Evans Gambit, so I'll just try to give a simple forcing recipe:
. } 4... Bxb4 { .
The pawn must be taken (with the bishop better).
In the words of Paco Vallejo: "black must accept the gambit, and then play very humble even returning the pawn if necessary".
. } 5. c3 { [%cal Gd2d4,Gd1b3] } 5... Be7 { This is the most solid move, and my recommendation. } (5... Bc5 { This is playable, but asking from trouble.
I don't recommend it if you're new to this opening. } 6. d4 { White has a lot of initiative and different attacking ideas. Very dangerous! }) (5... Bd6 { Another suspicious move I wouldn't recommend for newbies.
The pawn on d7 never gets to d6, so this is very dangerous. } 6. d4 Nf6 { [%csl Rd7][%cal Ge8g8] } 7. Ng5 (7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rd6] }) 7... O-O 8. f4) (5... Ba5 { This is another solid approach for black. } { [%cal Gd7d6,Gg8f6] } 6. d4 d6 (6... exd4 7. O-O) 7. Qb3 Qd7 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gd7f7] } 8. O-O Bb6 { [%cal Gc6a5] } 9. dxe5 Na5 10. Qb4 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 { [%csl Gc8,Gb6] }) 6. d4 { We need to know how to respond to this d4 idea and to Qb3.
I'm going to add specific chapters with just those lines, as a quick summary, but here let's explore both: } (6. Qb3 Nh6 7. d4 Na5 8. Qa4 Nxc4 9. Qxc4 { Black has:
- pawn up
- bishop pair
White has:
- pawn center
- black knight on h6
. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Rh6,Ge7,Gc8] } 9... Ng4 { Although the main move is exd4, I would recommend this as it's easier to play for black. } 10. dxe5 d6 11. exd6 Qxd6 { [%csl Gc8,Ge7,Rc3,Ra2] }) 6... Na5 { My forcing recommendation.
We give the pawn back to have a good position. } (6... exd4?! { This is the main move but it leads to great complications. You should only play it if you know what you're doing ;-) } 7. Qb3 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] }) 7. Be2 (7. Nxe5 Nxc4 8. Nxc4 d5) 7... d6 8. dxe5 dxe5 { If we trade queens, we have a better position because of white's pawn structure.
Therefore white usually avoids the queen trade: } { [%csl Rc3,Ra2][%cal Gd8d1,Gd1d8] } 9. Qa4+ c6 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gd8a5] } 10. Nxe5 Nf6 { We had to return the pawn, but we survived the opening and we're going to castle at the same time as white does.
Black's pawn structure is better for the price of a knight on the rim (a5), which cannot be attacked by a pawn so it's not so bad. The position is roughly equal (if any, easier for black due to the pawn structure). } *


