[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1n1p1p/2p1p1p1/3p2b1/3PP3/2NQ3P/PPP2P2/1K1R1BR1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.04"]
[UTCTime "16:09:29"]

{ This game was revealing for me. At this moment I spent ~30 min calculating due to the bad position I have. By pure calculation, I concluded the best move was h4. It was one of the few times in my life I found a good complicated move. However today I would spend 2 min to decide to play h4, because it feels obvious that the h file must remain open to have counterplay.

To me, this is a good example to explain the difference between pure calculation (what engines do) and strategical thinking (what humans do). We shouldn't look for perfection, but understanding. Sometimes we'll calculate well, but strategical ideas definitely make our lifes easier. }
1. Be2 (1. h4! { Giving up a second pawn is the best option! } 1... Bxh4 2. f4 f5 3. e5 { [%cal Gg1h1] } 3... Rf7 { [%csl Gh7,Gg6,Gf5][%cal Gf7h7] } 4. Qh3 { [%cal Gg1h1] } 4... Be7 5. Ne2 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gc2c3] } 5... c5 6. c3 b5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Nd4 { [%csl Rb5,Re6][%cal Gd4b5,Gf1b5] } 8... Bxd4 9. Rxd4 { [%cal Gd1d4] } 9... Rb8 10. Rb4 a5 11. Rxb5 Rxb5 12. Bxb5 Qb6 { [%cal Rb6b5,Rb6g1] } 13. Qf1 Nc5 14. a4 { [%cal Gb1a2] } 14... Ne4 { [%csl Rd2] } 15. Rg2 Qe3 { [%cal Ge4d2] } 16. Kc2 Rc7 17. Re2 Qc5 18. Qh3 { [%cal Rc5g1,Re4f2] } 18... d4 19. Rxe4 fxe4 20. Qxe6+ Kf8 21. Qf6+ Kg8 (21... Rf7 22. Qh8+ Ke7 23. Qe8#) 22. Qd8+ Kg7 23. Qf6+ Kg8) (1. e5 { [%csl Gh3] } 1... Bh4 { [%csl Rh3][%cal Gc6c5] }) 1... Bh4 { [%cal Rb7b5,Ra7a5,Ra5a4,Rb5b4] } *


[Event "Strategical Thinking: ChesspatzerWAL - pepellou"]
