[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Strategical Thinking"]
[ChapterName "ChesspatzerWAL - pepellou"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/t1utdDCh/0Fxxhi3B"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/1b2k3/2p1pp1p/p1P3p1/1pBBPbP1/1P3P1P/P3K3/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This was a blitz game full of tactical mistakes from both sides, but strategical thinking makes life easier. }
1. Be3 { Engine approved, totally equal. But from a practical point of view, it's risky business: white trades his best bishop for black's worst one.
Therefore, I criticize this move, even though it's objectively still equal (and even though black was tactically lost after this). Specially in blitz it's better to make our life easier, and our opponent's life tougher. 9 times out of 10, it will work out well. } 1... Bxe3 2. Kxe3 e5 { According to the remaining bishops, only black's weakness is going to be the c6 pawn, so the king must be careful with defending it. Then the bishop on b7 can make threats forever to white's pawns, probably in coordination with some pawn break. } { [%csl Rc6] } 3. Kd3 Bc8 4. Bg8 Kf8 5. Bh7 Ba6+ 6. Ke3 Bf1 7. Bf5 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rf5d7] } 7... Ke7 { Remember, the c6 pawn shouldn't be lost. } 8. Kf2 Bxh3? { It turns out that this move is a tactical mistake because black has the powerful move Bc8! with the threat of Ba6 and Kg2.
From a "perfection" point of view, Black's plan is wrong because it's not supported by the tactics. From a "practical" point of view though, if not for a tactical shot the endgame is very pleasant for black, given white's pawns.
That gives us the other side of the coin: when you're on the worse end of a strategical unbalance, you should be looking for tactics to bail out! } (8... Bd3) 9. Kg1 (9. Bc8! h5 10. Kg3! Bf1 (10... hxg4 11. Ba6 { [%cal Rf3g4] }) 11. gxh5) 9... Kd8 10. Kf2 Kc7 11. Be6 h5 12. Kg3 hxg4 13. fxg4 Bf1 14. Kf2 Bd3 15. Ke3 Bb1 16. Bc4 Bxa2 17. Kf2 a4 18. Bd3 Bxb3 19. Bb1 a3 0-1


