{ Stage 1 does not require theoretical study.

There's no concrete maneuver to push the king towards a side, nor there's a right side of the board. Just keep walking with your king and keep bringing your 2 pieces to help cornering the opponent's king.

Let's see for example a really bad starting position. Don't memorize these moves, they're just an example of what to do: } { [%csl Rc3,Rc4,Rd5] }
1. Kb2 { Walking with the king every time we can is generally good. } { [%csl Rc3,Rc4,Rd5] } 1... Kd3 { [%csl Rc3,Rc4,Rd2,Rc2] } 2. Nc3 { Our king couldn't really advance towards the opponent, so we start bringing pieces and controlling squares. We shouldn't leave our pieces behind, specially the knight since it's the slowest piece. } { [%csl Re2,Re4,Rc4,Rc2,Rc3] } 2... Kd4 { [%csl Rc4,Rc3,Re4,Rd5] } 3. Kc2 { [%csl Re4,Rc4,Rd3,Rc3] } 3... Ke3 { [%csl Re4,Rd3,Rd2,Re2] } 4. Nd5+ { [%csl Re3,Rd3,Rd2] } 4... Kd4 { [%csl Rd5,Rc4,Rc3,Re3,Rd3] } 5. Bb3 { [%csl Re3,Rd3,Rc3,Rc4,Rd5] } 5... Ke4 { [%csl Re3,Rd3,Rd5,Rf4] } 6. Kc3 { [%csl Re3,Rd3,Rd4,Rd5,Rf4] } 6... Ke5 { [%csl Rd5,Rd4,Rf6,Rf4] } 7. Kd3 { [%csl Rf4,Rf6,Re4,Rd4,Rd5] } 7... Kf5 { [%csl Rf4,Rf6,Re4] } 8. Kd4 { [%csl Rf4,Re4,Re5,Rf6] } 8... Ke6 { [%csl Rf6,Re7,Rd5,Re5] } 9. Ne3+ { [%csl Rf5,Re5,Rd5,Re6,Rf7] } 9... Kf6 { [%csl Rf5,Re5,Re6,Rf7] } 10. Bd5 { [%csl Rf7,Re6,Re5,Rf5] } 10... Kg7 { [%csl Rf7,Rg8] } 11. Ke5 { [%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rg8] } 11... Kg6 { [%csl Rf7,Rf6,Rf5] } 12. Be6 { [%csl Rf5,Rf6,Rf7] } 12... Kg7 { [%csl Rf7,Rg8,Rf6] } 13. Kf5 { [%csl Rg6,Rf6,Rf7,Rg8] } 13... Kh6 { [%csl Rg6,Rg5] } 14. Ng4+ { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rg5] } 14... Kg7 { [%csl Rh6,Rg6,Rf6,Rf7,Rg8] } 15. Ne5 { [%csl Rg6,Rf7,Rg8,Rf6] } 15... Kh6 { [%csl Rg6,Rg5] } 16. Kf6 { [%csl Rg5,Rg6,Rg7] } 16... Kh7 { [%csl Rg8,Rg7,Rg6] } 17. Ng6 { [%csl Rh8,Rg8,Rg7,Rg6] } 17... Kh6 { The king in the side of the board and close to a "bad corner" (h8). Stage 2 will consist in pushing it to the "right corner", i.e. or the color of our bishop (h1).
Note we spent 17 moves from an extremely bad position. In general stage 1 takes less than 20 moves if you're not too clumsy.
Stages 2 and 3 are mechanical and together take 18 moves in the worst case. } { [%csl Rg6,Rg7,Rg5] } *


[Event "Checkmate with Bishop and Knight: Stage 2: push king to the right corner"]
[Date "2021.01.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmate with Bishop and Knight"]
[ChapterName "Stage 2: push king to the right corner"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/izrJ2Ugh/elFLvYjh"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5k2/5N2/5K2/5B2/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.19"]
[UTCTime "17:50:08"]

{ We rotated the final position of stage 1. You should be used to understanding that there's no right side of the board.

In this example, we want to push the king to a8.

We'll use the bishop to cut the king when necessary, while the knight will draw a W shape as shown. The king will just walk in straight line defending the knight. } { [%csl Rh8,Ga8][%cal Gf7e5,Ge5d7,Gd7c5,Gc5b7,Bf6e6,Be6d6,Bd6c6,Bc6b6,Rf8h8] }
1. Bh7! { As we said, the bishop will cut the king to push it to the other side. We'll do this whenever the king is trying to escape back via a light square. } { [%csl Gh7,Rg8,Re7,Rf7,Rg7][%cal Gf5h7,Gf6e7,Gf6f7,Gf6g7] } 1... Ke8 2. Ne5 { Starting the knight maneuver. When the knight reaches the next point (d7), it will cut the escape via f8.
Note the harmony of bishop and knight, controlling squares of both colors. } { [%csl Ge5,Rf8][%cal Gf7e5,Be5d7] } 2... Kd8!? { This is the critical test. Our king was a bit slow so the opponent will escape from the side of the board. What follows is important to remember or we won't win: } { [%cal Bf6b6,Ye5d7,Yd7c5,Yc5b7,Rd8c7] } (2... Kf8 { Returning to f8 only speeds up our maneuver: } 3. Nd7+ { [%csl Gd7,Rg8,Rf8][%cal Ge5d7] } 3... Ke8 { [%csl Rf8,Rg8,Yd7][%cal Gd7f8,Gh7g8] } 4. Ke6 { [%csl Ge6,Rf8,Rg8][%cal Gf6e6,Be6d7,Gh7g8,Gd7f8] } 4... Kd8 { [%csl Rf8,Rg8][%cal Gd7f8,Gh7g8] } 5. Kd6 { [%csl Rf8,Rg8][%cal Ge6d6,Gh7g8,Gd7f8] } 5... Ke8 { [%csl Rf8,Rg8][%cal Gd7f8,Gh7g8] } 6. Bg6+ { And the king is easily pushed. } { [%csl Re8,Rf8][%cal Gg6e8,Gd7f8] }) 3. Ke6! { Time to run with the king!
Note that the king and the knight are going to do exactly the moves we drew at the beginning of stage 2, so it's not hard to remember.
We're one move away from opposing the kings again, so black must try to escape the side now: } 3... Kc7 { [%cal Rc7b6] } 4. Nd7! { Easy to remember: the king could not go to the next square (d6), so we move the knight. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Ge5d7,Gf7e5,Bd7c5,Bc5b7] } 4... Kc6 { The king is escaping, but our knight ideally controls every dark square around it and we're going to close the cage with the bishop: } { [%csl Rd5,Rd6,Rd7,Rc5,Rb6][%cal Ge6d5,Ge6d6,Ge6d7,Gd7c5,Gd7b6,Bh7d3,Bd3a6] } 5. Bd3! { You don't need to remember the bishop's moves because they're easy to discover on the board. We're always cutting the opponent's king with our bishop. } { [%csl Rb5,Ra6,Rc5,Rb6,Rd7,Rd6,Rd5][%cal Gd3a6,Gd7c5,Gd7b6,Ge6d7,Ge6d6,Ge6d5] } 5... Kc7 6. Bb5 { We keep cutting the king.
If the king doesn't return to the side of the board now, we'll keep caging it easily (Kd6, Kc6 etc) so let's see the critical case: } { [%csl Rc6,Ra6,Rb6,Rd6,Rd7][%cal Gb5c6,Gb5a6,Gd7b6,Ge6d6,Ge6d7] } (6. Be4 { Also works in this case, but I find Bb5 easier to remember since it works against both 5...Kc7 and 5...Kb7. } { [%csl Rb7,Rc6,Rb6,Rd6,Rd7][%cal Ge4b7,Gd7b6,Ge6d6,Ge6d7] }) 6... Kd8!? { The king comes back to the side of the board but threatening to travel back to the wrong corner h8. } { [%cal Rd8h8] } 7. Kd6! { No problem!
We can keep doing our intended moves with king and knight because we only need to control f7 at the right moment with the bishop. } { [%csl Rf8,Re7][%cal Gd7f8,Gd6e7] } 7... Ke8 { [%cal Re8f7] } 8. Bc4! { [%csl Rf7,Rf8,Re7,Rd7,Rc7][%cal Gd7f8,Gc4f7,Gd6e7,Gd6d7,Gd6c7] } 8... Kd8 9. Bf7! { [%csl Re7,Rd7,Re8,Rc7][%cal Gd6e7,Gd6d7,Gf7e8,Gd6c7] } 9... Kc8 10. Nc5! { Rule: we keep drawing the W whenever we can (as we did on move 2). I.e. the knight goes first, then the king.
Now that the corner is close, the king cannot try to escape the side so their best attempt is to return to d8: } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gf7e5,Ge5d7,Gd7c5,Bc5b7] } 10... Kd8 11. Nb7+! { Finishing the W with tempo and pushing the king easily from now on: } { [%csl Gb7,Rd8,Re8,Rc7,Rd7,Re7][%cal Gb7d8,Gf7e8,Bf7e5,Be5d7,Bd7c5,Bc5b7,Gd6c7,Gd6d7,Gd6e7] } 11... Kc8 12. Kc6! { [%csl Rb7,Rc7,Rd7,Rd8][%cal Gc6b7,Gc6c7,Gc6d7,Gb7d8] } 12... Kb8 13. Kb6! { [%csl Rc7,Ra7,Rb7,Rd8][%cal Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7,Gb7d8] } 13... Kc8 14. Be6+! { Now the king is caged in 2 squares (a8 and b8).
Time to move on to stage 3. } { [%csl Rd7,Rc8,Rd8,Rc7,Rb7,Ra7][%cal Ge6c8,Gb7d8,Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7] } *


[Event "Checkmate with Bishop and Knight: Stage 3: checkmate"]
[Date "2021.01.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmate with Bishop and Knight"]
[ChapterName "Stage 3: checkmate"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/izrJ2Ugh/qm8HyK1q"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "1k6/1N6/1K2B3/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.19"]
[UTCTime "17:50:08"]

{ The king is caged in 2 squares (a8 and b8).

To checkmate we need to control b8 with the knight and a8 with the bishop, but we need to do it with checks and in that order for it to be checkmate.

The knight must go to a6, since on c6 or d7 it would block diagonals that the bishop needs.

Therefore we bring the knight to a6: } { [%csl Rc8,Rc7,Rb7,Ra7][%cal Ge6c8,Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7] }
1. Nc5! { [%csl Rc8,Rc7,Rb7,Ra7] } 1... Ka8 2. Bh3! { Remember: the knight must go to a6 with check!
Any waiting move of the bishop would win now (not just Bh3, but also Bd7, Bf5 or Bg4). } { [%csl Ra7,Rb7,Rc7,Rc8] } (2. Na6?? $10 { Nooooo. Stalemate! }) 2... Kb8 { And now we do the 2 checks that we mentioned: } 3. Na6+! { [%csl Rb8,Rc8,Rc7,Rb7,Ra7][%cal Ga6b8,Gh3c8,Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7] } 3... Ka8 4. Bg2# { Checkmate! } *


