1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. Nc3 { Quaade Gambit or Quaade Attack: Recently recommended by Scottish grandmaster John Shaw as a less explored alternative to 4.h4 (he considers 4.Bc4 inferior) } (4. h4 { Paris Attack } 4... g4 5. Ne5 { Kieseritzky Gambit: It was popularized by Lionel Kieseritzky in the 1840s and used successfully by Wilhelm Steinitz. Boris Spassky used it to beat Bobby Fischer in a famous game at Mar del Plata in 1960.[17] This motivated Fischer to develop his own defense to the King's Gambit (see Fischer Defense). } (5. Ng5 { Allgaier Gambit: } 5... h6 6. Nxf7 { This knight sacrifice is considered dubious by modern theory. })) (4. Bc4 g4 (4... Bg7 5. d4 (5. h4 h6 6. d4 d6 { Philidor Gambit }) 5... d6 6. O-O h6 { Hanstein Gambit }) 5. O-O (5. d4 { Ghulam Kassim Gambit, considered inferior to the Muzio Gambit }) (5. Nc3 { McDonnell Gambit, considered inferior to the Muzio Gambit }) (5. Bxf7+ { Lolli Gambit, also inferior, leaves White with insufficient compensation for the piece after: } 5... Kxf7 6. Ne5+ Ke8 7. Qxg4 Nf6 8. Qxf4 d6) (5. Ne5 { Salvio Gambit, is considered better for Black due to the insecurity of White's king } 5... Qh4+ 6. Kf1 { And black has 3 good options here: } 6... Nh6 (6... f3) (6... Nc6)) 5... gxf3 6. Qxf3 { Muzio Gambit: White has gambited a knight but has three pieces bearing down on f7.[20] Such wild play is rare in modern chess, but Black must exercise care in consolidating his position. } 6... Qf6 7. e5 Qxe5 8. Bxf7+ { Double Muzio: Perhaps the sharpest continuation, leaving White two pieces down in eight moves, but with a position that some masters consider to be equal. }) 4... Bg7 (4... g4 5. Ne5 Qh4+ 6. g3 fxg3 7. Qxg4 Qxg4 (7... g2+? 8. Qxh4 gxh1=Q 9. Qh5! { White is close to winning. Black's best defence is considered to be: } 9... Nh6 10. d4 d6 11. Bxh6 dxe5 12. Qxe5+ Be6 13. Qxh8 Nd7 14. Bxf8 O-O-O { and White will emerge a clear pawn ahead }) 8. Nxg4 d5 $10) (4... d6 { Transposes to Fischer's Defense }) (4... h6 { Becker's Defense }) (4... Nc6 { Recommended by Konstantin Sakaev }) *


