1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 d5 { Also called the Abbazia Defense, has much the same idea as the Falkbeer Counter-Gambit, and can in fact be reached by transposition, e.g. 2.f4 d5 3.exd5 exf4. Black concentrates on gaining piece play and fighting for the initiative rather than keeping the extra pawn. It has been recommended by several publications as an easy way to equalize, although White keeps a slight advantage due to his extra central pawn and piece activity. } 4. Qe2 (4. exd5 Qxd5 { Scandinavian Variation of the KGA } (4... Bd6 5. d4 Nf6 6. c4 O-O 7. Be2 Re8 8. O-O) (4... Nf6 5. c4 (5. d4 Nxd5 6. c4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Ne3 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qb3 Bxd2+ 10. Nbxd2 O-O 11. Bd3 Nc6 12. Kf2) (5. Bc4 Nxd5 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 O-O (7... Ne3 8. Bxe3 fxe3 9. Ne5 (9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Ne5+ Kg8 11. Qh5 { [%csl Rf7] } 11... Be6 12. Nf7 { [%csl Rh8] } 12... Qxd4 13. Nh6+ gxh6 14. Qe8+ Kg7 15. Qxe7+ Kg6 16. Qxe6+ Kh5 17. Rf5+ Kh4 18. g3+ Kg4 19. Rf4+) 9... O-O) 8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Bxf4) 5... c6 6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. d4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be2 Ne4 10. Qd3 Bf5) 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Be2 Bd6 7. O-O Ne7 8. d4 O-O { [%csl Gf4] } 9. Bd3) (4. e5 g5 (4... Bg4 5. d4) 5. Nxg5 (5. d4 g4 6. Bxf4 gxf3 7. Qxf3 Be6 8. Bd3) 5... Qxg5 6. d4 Qh4+) 4... dxe4 5. Qxe4+ Qe7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qxe7+ Bxe7 8. d4 { [%csl Rf4][%cal Gc1f4] } 8... Bd6 *


