{ When the king and the pawn didn't surpass the 5th rank, we can use this simple method. } { [%cal Gg3g6] }
1... Rg6! { Now the rook will control the 3rd rank until White decides to push the pawn. } { [%cal Gg6a6,Gg6h6] } 2. e6 { This is the only real attempt for White to advance with the king.
Once this pawn advances, we should immediately go back with the rook to deliver checks from behind. } (2. Rb7 Rh6 { If White does not push the pawn, we keep the rook on the 3rd rank so the king cannot advance. }) 2... Rg1! 3. Kd6 Rd1+ 4. Ke5 Re1+ 5. Kf6 Rf1+ { Note that if the pawn hadn't been pushed, the king would be able to use it as a shelter from these checks. That's why we keep the rook on the 3rd rank until the pawn advances. } *


