[ChapterName "Kling and Horwitz"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Fz9GhZVU/GEbIib4v"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "4k3/7R/8/3KPr2/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.12.10"]
[UTCTime "21:52:37"]

{ When we cannot use Philidor against a central or bishop's pawn, we have this technique. The main idea is to keep the rook behind the pawn:

... }
1... Rf1! { Rf2, Rf3 and Rf4 also work with the same idea, but as a general rule we want to put the rook as far as possible from the opponent's king. } (1... Rg5?? 2. Kd6! (2. Ke6? Rg6+ { allows 3rd rank defence }) 2... Rg6+ (2... Rg1 { [%cal Gd6e6] } 3. Rh8+ Kf7 4. e6+) 3. e6 Rg8 4. Ra7) 2. Kd6 { The most challenging move, as it gives black many alternatives, but only one draws. } (2. Ke6 { could be annoying, but less practical since Black's answer is forced: } { [%cal Ge8f8,Re8d8] } 2... Kd8? (2... Kf8! 3. Ra7 Re1! { Transposing to the main line } { [%cal Gf1e1] }) 3. Rh8+ Kc7 4. Ke7 Rf2 5. e6 Rf1 6. Ke8 Rf2 7. e7 Rf1 8. Rf8 { [%cal Gf8f7] }) 2... Re1! { .
It's the only move, and it's difficult to find if you don't know K&H. The rook needs to stand behind the pawn to prevent its advance.
... } (2... Rd1+?? { See next chapter }) 3. Ke6 (3. Rh8+ Kf7 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6,Ge1e6] } 4. Rh7+ Ke8 5. Ke6) 3... Kf8! 4. Rf7+ (4. Rh8+ Kg7) 4... Ke8 (4... Kg8 5. Rf5) 5. Ra7 Kf8 6. Ra8+ Kg7 { .
And here if Black's rook was on any other file, White would win with Ke7. White needs to keep the pawn defended and there's no way to make progress.
... } 7. Kd6 Kf7! { [%csl Re6] } 8. Ra7+ Ke8 { .
No way to make progress, we keep applying the same technique or Philidor if given the chance. } *


