{ Let's follow the same position again: }
1... Rf1 2. Kd6 Rd1+?? { .
Once the king has shelter in front of the pawn, throwing the check is just losing.
... } 3. Ke6 Kf8 { .
How is this winning?
How is this different from the position after 2. Ke6, Kf8?
Well, in that position the rook was on f1, preventing the following maneuver:
... } 4. Rf7+! Ke8 (4... Kg8 5. Rd7 Re1 6. Kf6 { And the pawn advances, although the ending is still difficult to convert: } 6... Rf1+ 7. Ke7 Ra1! { Best defence, since now e6 would be a draw (see chapter XX), we'll see how to win this in chapter XX. }) 5. Ra7! { Important tempo to secure the advance of the pawn. } 5... Kf8 6. Ra8+ Kg7 7. Ke7 { Black is lost because the rook occupied the important a-file. We'll see how that's important to win in chapter XX. } *


[Event "Rook + Pawn vs Rook: Kling and Horwitz (a recoverable mistake)"]
[Date "2020.12.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook + Pawn vs Rook"]
[ChapterName "Kling and Horwitz (a recoverable mistake)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Fz9GhZVU/Y9jxjo5h"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "4k3/7R/8/3KPr2/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.12.10"]
[UTCTime "21:52:37"]

{ We'll see now another common mistake that doesn't lose but makes black's life difficult. You never know when you'll get to that position from a middlegame, so it's important to know it even if you're certain you wouldn't commit the "mistake".

We start as usual:

... }
1... Rf1 2. Kd6 Re1! 3. Ke6 Kd8? { .
For an engine (or for an endgame database), this move is as good as Kf8. But we broke the principle of going to the short side with the king. The endgame is still a draw, but some additional difficulties will be presented, given the wrong placement of the king:
... } 4. Rh8+ (4. Ra7 { a rook waiting move is best answered with a rook waiting move: } 4... Re2!) 4... Kc7 { .
For now K&H is working: White cannot play Ke7 because of our rook attacking the pawn. But White can try several things to exploit our king's position:
... } 5. Kf6 { .
1st attempt, easy to refute:
... } 5... Kd7! { This is purely the K&H technique. } 6. Rh7+ Ke8 7. Ke6 { .
And of course, now we could (and should) play Kf8, but let's go with Kd8 again to see another attempt by White:
... } 7... Kd8? (7... Kf8) 8. Rh8+ Kc7 9. Re8 { .
This is the most challenging attempt. The threat is Kf7 and advancing the pawn.
The game is still a draw but Black needs to be precise.
... } 9... Re2?? { Waiting would lose, but the analysis is complex: } (9... Rh1!! { The only move!
We can defend with checks from the short side. That shouldn't usually work but it does in this case thanks to White's rook's placement. } 10. Kf7 (10. Rf8 Re1) 10... Rh7+ 11. Kg6 (11. Kf6 Rh6+ 12. Kg7 Kd7) 11... Kd7 12. Ra8 Rh1 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gh1e1,Gd7e6] }) (9... Rf1?? 10. Ke7 { [%cal Ge5e6] }) 10. Kf7! Rh2 { too late } (10... Rf2+ 11. Ke7 Rh2 12. Rf8! { and e6 will lead to Lucena }) (10... Kd7 11. e6+ Kd6 12. Rd8+ { [%cal Ge6e7,Ge7e8] }) 11. Rg8! (11. e6?? Rh7+ 12. Kg6 Rh1 13. e7 Kd7 $10) 11... Rh7+ 12. Rg7 Rh8 13. Ke7! { White needs a lot of patience before being able to push the pawn! } (13. e6?? Kd6 14. e7 Kd7 $10) 13... Kc6 14. e6 Kc7 15. Kf6+ Kd8 (15... Kc6 16. Rd7 { will lead to Lucena }) (15... Kd6 16. Rd7+ Kc6 17. Rd1 Rh6+ 18. Kf7 Rh7+ 19. Kg6 Rh2 20. e7 Re2 21. Kf7 Rf2+ 22. Ke8 { Lucena }) 16. Kf7 Kc7 17. Rg1 Rh7+ 18. Kg6 Rh8 19. Rd1 { Lucena } *


