[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: 2 patterns, 1 idea"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "2 patterns, 1 idea"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/6NFNUgDb"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/6k1/5Q2/1k6/1Q3R2/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ In this study, we're going to explore 2 different patterns involving a defended queen checkmating a king.

In general, the king has always 2 escape squares (in red), which are one knight-jump away from the queen. So for the checkmate to exist, we need those squares either to be: blocked by pieces, protected by some of our pieces or not exist (if the king is on the side of the board).

We'll see examples of diagonal checkmate (the one on the right), also called DOVETAIL checkmate, as well as examples of a non-diagonal checkmate (the one on the left), also called SWALLOW's TAIL checkmate. } { [%csl Ra5,Rc5,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Gf5h7,Gf5f8,Gf5h5,Gb3b8,Gb3a3,Gb3c3,Gb3a4,Gb3c4] }
 *


