[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ [%csl Rf7,Rg6] }
 *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: Escape blocked by own pieces"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "Escape blocked by own pieces"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/gjyaLz9G"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "2kN4/4bp2/p5pp/1p6/4q1P1/2KR4/P1P2P1P/3R4 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ This is probably the most common scenario of this checkmate.

Due to the fact that pawns tend to defend each other (or other own pieces) diagonally, it's very common for a king to have escape squares covered this way. In those cases, an exposed king can be vulnerable to this kind of checkmate. }
1... Qb4# { [%csl Rc2,Rd3,Gb4][%cal Be7b4] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: An example with pawns"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "An example with pawns"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/qWkxsdZX"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "3Q4/8/6pk/8/3b1PK1/6P1/8/7q b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ As we said, it's very common for a king to be vulnerable to this pattern when he's close to his own pawn chains: } { [%csl Rg3,Rf4][%cal Bg6h5] }
1... Qh5# { [%csl Rg3,Rf4,Gh5][%cal Bg6h5] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: Escape covered"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "Escape covered"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/BzrNsyx4"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "1r5k/7p/3p2p1/1b1Np3/1N2Q2b/2P3Pq/1P3K2/R3R3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ Because the escape squares are arranged diagonally, it's very common to have a bishop to cover them, although it's not the only way.

This is a typical scenario: } { [%csl Rf1,Re2,Gg3][%cal Bh4g3,Bb5f1] }
1... Qxg3# { [%csl Gg3,Rf1,Re2][%cal Bb5f1,Bh4g3] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: Combining own piece and cover"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "Combining own piece and cover"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/SQcInz0t"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5b2/3q2kp/2R2p2/pr6/6P1/1BP2Q1P/1P3PK1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ This is probably the toughest situation to identify the pattern: one escape square is blocked by an own piece, and the other is covered by another attacker.

The pattern applies the same though: }
1. Qxf6# { [%csl Gf6,Rg8,Rh7][%cal Bb3g8,Bc6f6] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: Non existing escape squares"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "Non existing escape squares"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/4tNoSW7c"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "1r5k/5R2/1p1q3p/4p3/8/P5Q1/1P4PK/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ When a king is in a corner of the board, there are no escape squares, so a queen diagonal check is checkmate: } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Bf7g7] }
1. Qg7# { [%csl Gg7][%cal Bf7g7] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: An example in 2 moves"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "An example in 2 moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/QyguTIrD"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "7Q/8/5pp1/1p2p1k1/p7/P5K1/1qp5/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ We've covered the basic cases, but there are combinations of many moves ending up in this pattern.

This is a simple example in 2 moves: }
1. Qh4+ { [%csl Gh4,Rg6,Rf5][%cal Bg3h4,Rg5f5] } 1... Kf5 { [%csl Rf6,Re5,Gg4][%cal Bg3g4] } 2. Qg4# { [%csl Gg4,Rf6,Re5][%cal Bg3g4] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: Combining other tactics"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "Combining other tactics"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/UF3GtlXi"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r4r2/5Pkp/p2p2p1/3Pp1P1/1p2Q3/1P5R/3q4/5R1K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ Being a checkmate, the DOVETAIL pattern will be the last tactic of a sequence but can be (and will be) preceded by other tactical motifs.

In this example, we notice black's king is in a box. Any diagonal check from our queen could be checkmate. How can we bring our queen to f6 or h6 to deliver checkmate?

We use the tactical theme of ATTRACTION (equivalent to MAGNET in crazyhouse) to attract black's king to a position where we can keep checking with our queen:

... }
1. Rxh7+ { [%csl Rg6,Rf7,Rg8] } 1... Kxh7 { .
Now the pattern becomes more or less obvious: we're going to checkmate on h6. } { [%csl Rf7,Rg8,Gh6][%cal Ge4h4,Gh4h6,Bg5h6] } 2. Qh4+ { [%csl Gh6,Rf7,Rg8][%cal Gh4h6,Bg5h6] } 2... Kg7 { [%csl Rf7,Rg8,Gh6][%cal Gh4h6,Bg5h6] } 3. Qh6# { [%csl Gh6,Rf7,Rg8][%cal Bg5h6] } *


