[FEN "4r2k/2p1q2P/5pp1/p7/2P5/Q2B4/2P2P2/3K4 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ The king is on the side of the board.
If we could put the queen on d2 it would be checkmate because there would be no escape squares. We know that from the previous chapter.

However, we have a different case here. Instead of a frontal check, we do a lateral check (also from the side of the board). This is a very common pattern, in which there's only one escape square (blocked by a pawn in this position).

... } { [%csl Rc2][%cal Be8e1] }
1... Qe1# { [%csl Rc2,Ge1][%cal Be8e1] } *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: An example in 2 moves"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "An example in 2 moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/qBgqqOOn"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "b5k1/1q3pb1/p6p/1p6/5QP1/2P1P2P/1P1R4/4R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ We have a great battery with bishop and queen, but the g2 square is defended by a rook so we cannot do checkmate in 1. We have a checkmate in 2 though:

... }
1... Qh1+ { .
Lateral check from the side of the board, i.e. the king has only one escape:
... } { [%csl Gh1,Re1,Re3][%cal Gh1g1,Rg1f2,Ba8h1] } 2. Kf2 { [%csl Re1,Re3][%cal Ba8g2] } 2... Qg2# { .
And this lateral check is now checkmate because the escape squares are blocked by own pieces. } { [%csl Re3,Re1,Gg2][%cal Ba8g2] } *


