[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "Combining other tactics"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/4Zc2uYUK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "4r3/pp1q4/2pnb1kp/8/5RP1/1PB2Q1P/P4P1K/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ Like any other tactic, you should start considering the forcing moves (in this case Rf6+) and eventually, you'll see the pattern. It's hard to spot right now where are we going to checkmate the king, but if you noticed those red circles you might already have an idea :-)

Anyway, let's go for the line:

... } { [%csl Re6,Re8] }
1. Rf6+ { [%csl Re6,Re8] } 1... Kh7 { .
How do we get to attack the king with our queen. Qd3+ is tempting, but there's a stronger move:
... } { [%csl Re6,Re8] } 2. Rxh6+! { A rook sacrifice that is both an ATTRACTION (the king will be checked on h6) and a CLEARANCE (we clear the h file, necessary to continue checking from h4).
... } { [%csl Re8,Re6] } 2... Kxh6 { [%csl Re6,Re8] } 3. Qf6+ { [%csl Re8,Re6][%cal Rh6h7] } 3... Kh7 { [%csl Re6,Re8] } 4. Qh4+! { .
The king has 2 moves.
Do you see what happens if he goes to g6? (hint: DOVETAIL)
... } { [%csl Re8,Re6][%cal Rh7g6,Rh7g8] } 4... Kg8 { [%csl Re6,Re8] } 5. Qh8+ { [%csl Re8,Re6,Gh8][%cal Bc3h8] } 5... Kf7 { [%csl Re6,Re8] } 6. Qg7# { [%csl Re8,Re6,Gg7][%cal Bc3g7] } *


