{ The patterns of DOVETAIL and SWALLOW's TAIL not only apply to checkmate positions.
Recognizing immediately what the escape squares are for a queen check allow us to quickly calculate some forcing lines in various types of positions.

I wanted to focus on a common pattern that contains these ideas: king hunts where the queen chases the king until a final checkmate. }
 *


[Event "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen: A sample king hunt"]
[Date "2020.06.03"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Checkmates - Patterns with defended queen"]
[ChapterName "A sample king hunt"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ppfi9AbT/ZqRvta6Q"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "6Q1/pB1kq2p/1b3p2/6pP/4P3/8/5PK1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:27:18"]

{ This is a typical king hunt with the queen:

... }
1. Qc8+ { .
Diagonal check, 2 escape squares, one is blocked.
... } { [%csl Gc8,Re7,Rd6][%cal Gg8c8,Bb7c8,Rd7d6] } 1... Kd6 { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gg8c8] } 2. Qc6+ { .
Lateral check, 2 escape squares, one is blocked.
... } { [%csl Gc6,Re7,Re5,Gc8][%cal Gg8c8,Gc8c6,Bb7c6,Rd6e5] } 2... Ke5 { [%csl Gc8,Gc6][%cal Gg8c8,Gc8c6] } 3. Qd5+ { .
Lateral check, 2 escape squares, one is blocked.
... } { [%csl Gd5,Rf6,Rf4,Gc8,Gc6][%cal Gg8c8,Gc8c6,Gc6d5,Be4d5,Re5f4] } 3... Kf4 { [%csl Gc8,Gc6,Gd5][%cal Gg8c8,Gc8c6,Gc6d5] } 4. Qf5# { .
And a final frontal check, 2 escape squares, both covered, so it's checkmate.
With a trained mind, you can see the checkmate from the first position in less than a second, but that's a topic for another lesson :-D } { [%csl Gf5,Re3,Rg3,Gc8,Gc6,Gd5][%cal Be4f5,Gg8c8,Gc8c6,Gc6d5,Gd5f5] } *


