[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2020.03.02"]
[UTCTime "11:18:26"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We'll try to practice our recipe against the Evans Gambit, so please allow it by avoiding the Fried Liver with 3 ... Bc5 :-) }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 { Exactly! The pawn must be taken. } (4... Nxb4 { Playable, but not our recipe. }) 5. c3 Be7 (5... Bd6 { Very dangerous choice. Also, not our recipe :-) }) (5... Bc5 { Very dangerous choice. Also, not our recipe :-) }) (5... Ba5 { That's a good solid option, but not our recipe :-) }) 6. Qb3 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gb3f7] } 6... Nh6 { Correct! With the bishop on c1 still blocked by the pawn on d2, we have time for this! } 7. d4 { How do we prevent Bxh6 followed by Bxf7+? } { [%csl Rh6,Rf7][%cal Rc1h6,Rb3f7] } 7... Na5 { Bravo!
With f7 defended, white has no time to take it, so we're going to take the bishop on c4. } 8. Qa4 Nxc4 9. Qxc4 { We're going to give our pawn back, but our worst piece is that knight on the terrible h6 square. How do we improve that piece to give the pawn back under the best circumstances? } { [%csl Rh6,Ge7,Gc8,Gd4,Ge4,Re5] } 9... Ng4 { Yes!
We improve our knight and avoid Nxe5 (we would trade knights), forcing white to take with the pawn. } (9... exd4 { It's playable. Just not our recipe :-) }) 10. dxe5 { We gave the pawn back in the best way, but our knight has no good squares and it does not want to go back to h6. How do we keep developing so that this kinght has a good square to go to? } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Rg4f6,Rg4e5,Rg4e3,Rg4f2,Rg4h2,Bg4h6] } 10... d6 { Yes!!
We gain the e5 square for the knight. We're also threatening to take a pawn there, so white's move is also forced now. } 11. exd6 Qxd6 { Perfect!!
We have the better structure and the bishop pair. Perfect position for black :-) } { [%cal Gg4e5,Ge8g8] } (11... cxd6 { Although it's playable, we ruin our pawn structure. There's a better move than this. }) (11... Bxd6 { Playable, but the bishop was going great controlling g5. }) *


