[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Doubled pawns"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Doubled pawns"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/ZzhYASag"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/1k6/8/1P6/1P6/1K6/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "15:47:36"]

{ We know that if the pawns were rook pawns it would be a draw (because with rook pawns the number of pawns is not important).

Therefore, the scenario is interesting for any other pawns, like the example position. White wins:

... }
1. Kc3! { .
The standard procedure is to use the less advanced pawn to waste a move to win the opposition later.
... } 1... Kc7 2. Kd4 Kb6 3. Kc4 Kc7 4. Kc5 Kb7 5. b6 { [%csl Ba6,Bb6,Bc6] } 5... Ka6! (5... Kb8 6. Kc6 Kc8 7. b7+ Kb8 8. b5! (8. Kc5 Kc7 9. b8=Q+ Kxb8 10. Kb6) 8... Ka7 9. b8=Q+ Kxb8 10. Kb6 { [%csl Gb6,Rb8,Ba7,Bb7,Bc7] }) 6. b7! Kxb7 7. Kb5 { .
So the procedure always involves giving up the 1st pawn to have a winning endgame with the 2nd. Therefore it's important not to push the 2nd pawn until we have a winning endgame.
IMPORTANT TO REMEMBER:
Doubled pawns always win, except:
1) They are rook pawns
2) The less advanced pawn is on the 5th rank already } { [%csl Ba6,Bb6,Bc6,Rb7,Gb5] } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Isolated pawns"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
