{ It's black to play, but white wins.

Here we see an example of delaying the capture of the pawns until the king can help:

... }
1... Kd5 2. a5! { Preventing Kxd4 } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gb5a5,Gb5d5,Ga7a8,Ga7a5,Gd7d8,Gd7d5,Gc8d8,Gc8a8] } 2... Kc6 3. Kg2 Kb5 { .
Now if black's king takes the 'a' pawn, white's king will arrive in time to a key square of the other pawn.
... } { [%csl Bc6,Bd6,Be6] } 4. Kf3 { [%csl Bc6,Bd6,Be6] } 4... Kxa5 { [%csl Bc6,Bd6,Be6] } 5. Ke4 { [%csl Be6,Bc6,Bd6] } 5... Kb6 { [%csl Bd6,Bc6,Be6] } 6. Kd5 { [%csl Bc6,Bd6,Be6] } 6... Kc7 { [%csl Bc6,Bd6,Ge6] } 7. Ke6 { winning } *


