[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Blocked pawns - key squares"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Blocked pawns - key squares"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/IjkWChj7"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "k7/8/1p6/1P6/8/8/7K/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "16:05:53"]

{ When we have blocked pawns, we should always think of key squares.

KEY SQUARES ARE: 3 SQUARES ON EACH SIDE OF THE PAWN

For the b6 pawn, the key squares are c6, d6 and e6 (a6 is not really reachable). That means that if White's king arrives to one of them, it will be able to take the pawn.

Conversely, Black's king wants to reach c5, d5 or e5 to win White's pawn.

Having the key squares in mind, it's easy to determine who's winning and also finding the right moves (usually by using the opposition).

... } { [%csl Bc6,Bd6,Be6,Ba6,Ra5,Rc5,Rd5,Re5] }
1. Kg3! { [%csl Ba6,Bc6,Bd6,Be6,Re5,Rd5,Rc5,Ra5] } 1... Kb7 { [%csl Be6,Bd6,Bc6,Ba6,Ra5,Rc5,Rd5,Re5] } 2. Kf4 { [%csl Ba6,Bc6,Bd6,Be6,Re5,Rd5,Rc5,Ra5] } 2... Kc7 { [%csl Ba6,Bc6,Bd6,Be6,Ra5,Rc5,Rd5,Re5] } 3. Ke5 { [%csl Ba6,Bc6,Bd6,Be6,Re5,Rd5,Rc5,Ra5] } 3... Kd7 { [%csl Re5,Rd5,Rc5,Ra5,Ba6,Bc6,Bd6,Be6] } 4. Kd5! { Winning the opposition. Now we'll have access to one of the key squares.
... } { [%csl Ra5,Rc5,Re5,Ba6,Bc6,Bd6,Be6,Gd5,Rd7] } 4... Kc7 { [%csl Ge6,Ba6,Bc6,Bd6][%cal Gd5e6] } 5. Ke6 { .
Once we reach a key square, taking the pawn is very easy:
... } { [%csl Ge6,Bd6,Bc6,Ba6] } 5... Kc8 6. Kd6 Kb7 7. Kd7 Kb8 8. Kc6 Ka7 9. Kc7 Ka8 10. Kxb6 { .
Note that when we capture the pawn, it doesn't matter that we lose the opposition, because white's pawn is on the 5th rank so we're already in a key square. It's important to notice that this does not happen in other ranks. } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Blocked pawns - reserving squares"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Blocked pawns - reserving squares"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/V4ua0JpU"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/2K5/4p3/4P3/6k1/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "16:13:27"]

{ When both kings can access the key squares of their enemy pawns, we usually have a mutual zugzwang situation.

The first king to attack the pawn MUST reserve (is possible) the important square that attacks and defends at the same time (d6 for white's king, f5 for black's king). If you enter that square too early you lose.

... } { [%csl Rb5,Rc5,Rd5,Rg5,Rh5,Bb6,Bc6,Bf6,Bg6,Bh6,Gd6,Gf5] }
1. Kd7! { .
Now unfortunately for Black, the only way to defend the pawn is entering the f5 square:
... } { [%csl Bd6,Bc6,Bb6,Bf6,Bg6,Bh6][%cal Gd7e6,Rg4f5] } (1. Kd6?? Kf5 { And White is in zugzwang so Black wins. }) 1... Kf5 2. Kd6! { Zugzwang. White wins.
Silman calls this the Trebuchet - according to MICKEK1977 :-). } { [%csl Bd6,Rf5] } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Blocked pawns - an example"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Blocked pawns - an example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/r0A0kIN5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/7k/3p2p1/3P4/6KP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "16:17:37"]

{ Black to play and win.

In this example, we'll see how the rules of blocked pawns can help us in dealing with more complex situations with more pawns.

If Black wants to win with the blocked pawn, the king needs to reach e3, f3 or g3. This can be achieved easily by getting rid of the non-blocked pawns:

... } { [%csl Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Be3,Bf3,Bg3] }
1... Kh4! { [%csl Ba3,Bb3,Bc3,Bf3,Be3,Bg3][%cal Gh4h3] } 2. Kf2 { [%csl Bg3,Bf3,Be3,Bc3,Bb3,Ba3] } 2... Kh3 { [%csl Bg3,Bf3,Be3,Bc3,Bb3,Ba3] } 3. Kg1 { [%csl Bg3,Bf3,Be3,Bc3,Bb3,Ba3] } 3... g3 { [%csl Be3,Bf3,Bg3,Bc3,Bb3,Ba3] } 4. hxg3 { [%csl Bg3,Bf3,Be3,Bc3,Bb3,Ba3] } (4. Kh1 Kg4 (4... Kh4 5. Kg2 gxh2 6. Kxh2 { [%csl Gh2,Rh4] }) 5. Kg2 gxh2 6. Kxh2 Kf3) 4... Kxg3 { .
With an easy win, as we know. } { [%csl Gg3] } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Blocked pawns - before 5th rank"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Blocked pawns - before 5th rank"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/NaOW2vJq"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/5p2/3k4/5P2/8/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "16:23:10"]

{ Reaching the key squares allows to take the pawn, but that does not guarantee victory. We've seen in chapter 6 how with a pawn in 5th rank it is a victory (since key squares are in front of the pawn), but with a less advanced pawn that will not be the case.

By having this concept clear in your mind, you would have no trouble in finding the only way to draw this position as white:

... }
1. f4! { And now we only need to be careful to be ready to play Kf2 in response to Kxf4.
... } (1. Kf2?? f4 { and Black will at least reach c3, winning the pawn and the game } { [%csl Be3,Bd3,Bc3] }) 1... Ke4 2. Kg2! { (or Kf1) } 2... Kxf4 3. Kf2 { draw } { [%csl Gf2,Rf4,Be3,Bf3,Bg3] } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Blocked pawns - king routes"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Blocked pawns - king routes"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/WH6VsaeV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/1p6/1P6/8/7K/8/8/1k6 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "16:29:01"]

{ We've just seen that when the pawn is not on the 5th rank yet, the defending side can draw if he achieves the opposition at the right time (when the capture happens). Therefore, the maneuvering of the kings before the capture is key.

In this position, Black needs 5 moves to capture the pawn. White needs 6 moves to get to b4. Since White has the turn we could conclude that it's a draw.

However, not all routes work!

... }
1. Kg3! { .
White's king has 141 different routes from h4 to b4.
The one route that works is the farthest from the one chosen by Black's king (who will try to choose the closest to White's king to try and shoulder it).
... } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gg3f2,Gf2e1,Ge1d2,Gd2c3,Gc3b4] } (1. Kg5 Kc2 2. Kf6 Kd3 3. Ke7 Kc4 4. Kd7 Kb5 5. Kc7 Ka6) (1. Kg4?? { .
let's see how this would lose, Black can shoulder White's king!
... } 1... Kc2 2. Kf3 (2. Kf4 Kd3 3. Ke5 Kc4 4. Ke4 Kc5 5. Kd3 Kxb6) 2... Kd3! { .
Oops!
White has to lose a tempo here.
... } { [%csl Gd3,Rf3] } 3. Kf2 Kc4 4. Ke2 Kb5 5. Kd3 Kxb6 { [%csl Rd3,Gb4] }) 1... Kc2 { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gc3b4,Gd2c3,Ge1d2,Gg3f2,Gf2e1] } 2. Kf2 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gf2e1,Ge1d2,Gd2c3,Gc3b4] } 2... Kd3 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gf2e1,Ge1d2,Gc3b4,Gd2c3] } 3. Ke1 { [%csl Ge1][%cal Ge1d2,Gd2c3,Gc3b4] } 3... Kc4 { [%csl Ge1][%cal Ge1d2,Gd2c3,Gc3b4] } 4. Kd2 { [%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2c3,Gc3b4] } 4... Kb5 { [%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2c3,Gc3b4] } 5. Kc3 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc3b4] } 5... Kxb6 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc3b4] } 6. Kb4 { draw } *


