{ With rook's pawns, it's generally easier for the defending side since trapping the strong king on the rook file is enough to draw.

However, we have a desperate situation here where White can win. But again, not all routes work.

Black needs to reach c7 when White takes the a7 pawn, so White's king needs to shoulder its counterpart:

... } { [%csl Bc7] }
1. Ke6! { [%csl Ge6,Bc7][%cal Ge6d5,Gd5c6,Gc6b7] } (1. Ke7?? { this would lead to a draw: } { [%csl Bc7] } 1... Kc3 { [%csl Bc7] } 2. Kd7 { [%csl Bc7] } 2... Kd4 { [%csl Bc7] } 3. Kc7 { [%csl Bc7] } 3... Kd5 { [%csl Bc7] } 4. Kb7 { [%csl Bc7] } 4... Kd6 { [%csl Bc7] } 5. Kxa7 { [%csl Bc7] } 5... Kc7 $10 { [%csl Gc7] }) 1... Kc3 { [%csl Ge6,Bc7][%cal Ge6d5,Gd5c6,Gc6b7] } 2. Kd5 { Black has to lose a tempo now } { [%csl Gd5,Bc7][%cal Gd5c6,Gc6b7] } 2... Kd3 { [%csl Gd5,Bc7][%cal Gd5c6,Gc6b7] } 3. Kc6 { [%csl Gc6,Bc7][%cal Gc6b7] } 3... Kd4 { [%csl Gc6,Bc7][%cal Gc6b7] } 4. Kb7 { [%csl Gb7,Bc7] } 4... Kd5 { [%csl Bc7] } 5. Kxa7 { [%csl Bc7] } 5... Kc6 { [%csl Bc7,Rc6] } 6. Kb8 { White wins. } { [%csl Bc7,Rc6][%cal Ga6a7,Ga7a8] } *


