[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/5p2/8/4P1k1/8/7K/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "16:49:38"]

{ When pawns are on adjacent files, it's usually very easy to calculate the consequences of the capture or defense of the pawns.

This position is an example of maybe the only trick you need to remember: giving up a lost pawn to change the key squares.

White is going to lose the pawn, but Black already reached the key squares of its pawn. The resource to save the position is:

... } { [%csl Be4,Bf4,Bg4] }
1. e5! { .
Forcing the capture with the pawn will change its key squares and now we'll be in time to defend.
... } { [%csl Be4,Bf4,Bg4] } 1... fxe5 { [%csl Bf3,Be3,Bd3,Re4,Rf4,Rg4][%cal Rg4f3,Rf4e3,Re4d3] } 2. Kg2! { .
And with the opposition, we prevent Black's king to enter those key squares.
Draw. } { [%csl Bf3,Be3,Bd3] } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Passed pawns - dual-purpose kings"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Passed pawns - dual-purpose kings"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/eNSv3YY5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/6p1/7k/8/1K6/8/1P6/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "18:12:34"]

{ Most positions with passed pawns are easy to calculate, they're just a pawn race.

Some extreme positions are however very interesting because kings can maneuver to both support their own pawn and bother the opponent's one. Variations are then far from obvious.

This is such an example. It's a composition by Duras (1905).

... }
1. Kc5! { .
It's the only move that wins, and serves 2 purposes:
1) Keeping the king in the square of the g7 pawn.
2) Shouldering black's king away from white's pawn.
... } (1. Kc4?? Kg6 2. b4 Kf7 3. b5 Ke7 $10) 1... Kg6 { .
Black does not want to block the pawn, but there's no way to win the pawn race because White's king can stop the pawn.
... } (1... g5 2. b4 g4 3. Kd4 $18) 2. b4 Kf7 { [%csl Gc5] } 3. b5 Ke7 { .
If the Black king can stop the pawn it would be a draw, so now the White king, who was serving 2 purposes, can commit himself to stop Black's king:
... } 4. Kc6! Kd8 { even though White's king stepped out of the g7 square, now playing g5 would be stupid, since White's pawn is on the 5th and Black's pawn still on the 2nd, so the pawn race would be clearly lost } 5. Kb7! { .
White's king is fully committed now to promoting the own pawn, since the race is won:
... } 5... g5 6. b6 g4 7. Ka7 (7. Ka6 Kc8 8. Ka7) 7... g3 8. b7 g2 9. b8=Q+ $18 *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Passed pawns - Reti study"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Passed pawns - Reti study"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/nf2iOf0b"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "7K/8/k1P5/7p/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "18:27:04"]

{ We all know this composition. It was made by Reti in 1921.

There's no better example of a dual-purpose king maneuver.
White's king can save the game here by threatening 2 ideas:

1) Helping the own pawn promote
2) Entering the opponent's pawn square

Each of those ideas is not enough to save the game, but it is when we find the king route that threatens both:

... }
1. Kg7! { .
There are 9 routes from h8 to d6, but only one of them allows the king to also come nearer the black's pawn square
... } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7f6,Gf6e5,Ge5d6,Bh4h5,Bh4h1,Bg1h1,Bg1d1,Bg5h5,Bg5d5,Bd4d5,Bd4d1] } 1... h4 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Bh3h4,Bh3h1,Bg1h1,Bg1e1,Be2e1,Be2e4,Bg4h4,Bg4e4,Gg7f6,Gf6e5,Ge5d6] } 2. Kf6 { .
The king keeps getting near the pawn square, but now it also threatens Ke7 to help the pawn promote, so Black is forced to spend the first tempo on defense:
... } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gf6e5,Ge5d6,Bf6e7,Bg4h4,Bg4e4,Be3e4,Be3e1,Bf1e1,Bf1h1,Bh2h1,Bh2h4] } 2... Kb6 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Bh3h4,Bh3h1,Bg1h1,Bg1e1,Be2e1,Be2e4,Bf4e4,Bf4h4,Gf6e5,Ge5d6] } (2... h3 3. Ke7 { and it does not matter that Black promotes because White also does } 3... h2 4. c7) 3. Ke5! { .
Now if Black takes the pawn, White's king enters the square.
But if the 'h' pawn is pushed, White's king supports the pawn and both sides promote.
It's a draw. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Bg4h4,Bg4e4,Be3e4,Be3e1,Bf1e1,Bf1h1,Bh2h1,Bh2h4,Ge5d6] } 3... h3 (3... Kxc6 4. Kf4) 4. Kd6 h2 5. c7 h1=Q 6. c8=Q *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Passed pawns - forcing king to bad square"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Passed pawns - forcing king to bad square"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/InRFtJF1"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/5p2/2k5/K7/8/1P6/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "18:35:54"]

{ Sometimes, the goal of a dual-purpose king maneuver is to draw the enemy king to a certain square.

This example is a from the game Ljubojevic - Browne, Amsterdam 1972

... }
1... Kd5! { The king eludes an eventual check and shoulders the enemy king away from the black's pawn.
Apparently, the White pawn is more advanced in the race, but since Black's king is close to bothering the White's pawn, the White king will need to be in an unfortunate position to try and support its pawn:
... } (1... Kb7 2. Kb5 { [%cal Gb5f5] }) (1... f5 2. Kb4) 2. b4 (2. Kb4 Kd4) 2... f5 3. b5 f4 4. b6 Kc6! { .
Now there's only one move for White to make progress, and it will put the king on a6, where it will receive a check when Black promotes!
... } 5. Ka6 f3 6. b7 f2 7. b8=Q f1=Q+ { And the White queen is lost. } 8. Ka5 Qa1+ 9. Kb4 Qb1+ { [%csl Rb8][%cal Gb1b8] } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Passed pawns - Another example"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Passed pawns - Another example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/7YI9bXuP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/1p6/8/8/6P1/k1K5/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "18:41:37"]

{ We solve this puzzle on chess.com the other day.

The technique is very similar to the previous example, although a tiny bit more sophisticated:

... }
1. Kc3! { .
We want the Black's king to be on a7 when we promote, but we also want our king to not be checked during the pawn race.
So the winning maneuver consists in luring the Black's king up in a way that we escape from checks, and then luring it back to a2 at the right time:
... } (1. g4 b5 2. g5 b4 3. g6 b3+ 4. Kc3 b2 5. g7 b1=Q (5... Ka1 6. g8=Q b1=Q) 6. g8=Q+ Ka1 7. Qa8+ Qa2 8. Qh1+ Qb1) (1. Kd3 b5 2. Kc3 Ka3 3. Kc2 { [%cal Gc2b1] }) 1... Ka3 { otherwise Kb4 clearly wins } 2. Kc4 Ka4 { otherwise Kb5 clearly wins } 3. g4! { .
Accurate! We need to shoulder Black's king until the pawns start racing.
If we go Kd3 immediately, Black's king plays Kb5 and enters our pawn's square.
... } (3. Kd3 { [%cal Bg4g3,Bg4g8,Bf8g8,Bf8b8,Bf3g3,Bf3b3,Bb4b3,Bb4b8] } 3... Kb5) 3... b5+ 4. Kd3! { .
Preventing any further checks in the race. Now Black's king is not in time to reach our pawn's square so they will try to race. It's time to lure Black's king back to a2:
... } 4... b4 (4... Kb4 5. Kd4 (5. g5)) 5. g5 b3 6. g6 (6. Kc3 Ka3 7. g6 b2 8. Kc2 Ka2 9. g7) 6... Ka3 (6... b2 7. Kc2 Ka3 8. Kb1) 7. g7 b2 8. Kc2! Ka2 9. g8=Q+ { winning } *


