[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Rook's pawns and one distant passed pawn"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Rook's pawns and one distant passed pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/QHWzhvDJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/3k3p/3P3P/2K5/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "18:53:57"]

{ The result of this ending is determined by:

1) How advanced the blocked rook's pawns are (5th or 6th means it's a win)
2) How advanced the passed pawn is (as far from promotion as possible is best to win)
3) The position of the kings

In this example, we have the rook pawn blocked on the 5th, which means it's winning. Let's see how:

... }
1. Kd4 Kd7 2. Ke5! { Important to keep the Black's king away from the pawn. } (2. Ke4 Kd6 3. Kf5? { would lead to a draw } 3... Kxd5 4. Kg6 Ke6 5. Kxh6 Kf6) 2... Ke7 3. Kf5 Kd6 4. Kg6 Kxd5 5. Kxh6 Ke6 6. Kg7 { .
IMPORTANT TO REMEMBER
This is winning also with the pawn in any other square on the a, b, c or d files.
Also, with some exceptions, on the e file (we'll see them later).
The technique for White's king after taking the rook's pawn is to move diagonally to shoulder the opponent. Therefore the 'f' file is the drawing zone. } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Rook's pawn not on 5th yet"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Rook's pawn not on 5th yet"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/2WX4jl1G"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/1k5p/7P/1PK5/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "19:05:17"]

{ After Black takes our pawn, the king will try to go to the f file (drawing zone), specifically trying for f7 or f8. Therefore we want Black's king to take as much time as possible to take our pawn:

... }
1. Kd4! { .
Remember the 2nd rule: the passed pawn, we want it as far from promotion as possible.
... } 1... Kb4 2. Ke5 Kxb3 3. Kf5 Kc4 4. Kg5 Kd5 5. Kxh5 Ke6 6. Kg6! Ke7 7. Kg7 $18 *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Bähr Rule"]
[Date "2019.05.18"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Bähr Rule"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/1yk4yHV9"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/1k5p/1P5P/2K5/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "22:02:34"]

{ This position is the same as in the previous example, but with the pawn already on b4, which is good for Black.

Bähr invented this geometrical rule to assess this kind of positions: we draw diagonals from the captured pawns to the drawing zone (the f-file). The line that goes higher wins. In this case, that's the one the Black king will use (green line), therefore this position is a draw.

The diagonals, of course, are the last part of the corresponding king routes (after taking each pawn). If the diagonals collide in f-file in the same square, that favors the winning side.

Let's see how this is a draw, but keeping the diagonals on the board to illustrate:

... } { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Rf5f8,Rf5f1,Gb4f8,Bh5f7] }
1. Kb3 { We've seen it's best for white to force the Black king to separate from the pawn before starting the race. } { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3] } 1... Kb6 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb5b6] } 2. Kc4 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yb5b6] } 2... Kc6 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yb5b6,Yb6c6] } 3. Kd4 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yb5b6,Yb6c6] } 3... Kb5 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5] } 4. Ke4 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5] } 4... Kxb4 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 5. Kf5 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 5... Kc5 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 6. Kg5 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yf5g5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 6... Kd6 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yf5g5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 7. Kxh5 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yf5g5,Yg5h5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 7... Ke7 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yf5g5,Yg5h5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 8. Kg6 { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yf5g5,Yg5h5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } 8... Kf8 { .
It does not matter the maneuvers previous to the captures (yellow routes), because both kings will do the same after the captures: run diagonally upwards to the f-file. Regardless how white maneuvers to start the race, Black will be able to draw. } { [%csl Gb4,Bh5][%cal Gb4f8,Bh5f7,Rf6f8,Rf6f1,Yc3b3,Yb3c4,Yc4d4,Yd4e4,Ye4f5,Yf5g5,Yg5h5,Yb5b6,Yb6c6,Yc6b5,Yb5b4] } *


