{ When the blocked pawn is on the 4th rank, the counterattack works only with certain positions of the kings.

... }
1. Ke1 Kc4 2. Ke2 Kd4 { Passive defense fails, of course: } (2... Kb4 3. Kd3! Kxa4 4. Kc4! { .
In this case, Black is closer to promoting than in the previous example, but the position of the kings will play an important role:
... } 4... Ka3 5. d4 a4 6. d5 Kb2 7. d6 a3 8. d7 a2 9. d8=Q a1=Q 10. Qd2+ Ka3 (10... Kb1 11. Kb3 $18 { .
Finally, if the pawn is less advanced than the 4th, the counterattack is impossible so the Bähr Rule applies normally. }) 11. Qb4+ Ka2 12. Qb3#) 3. d3 Kc5 4. Ke3 Kd5 5. d4 Kd6 6. Ke4 Ke6 7. d5+ Kd6 8. Kd4 { Bähr rule says that white wins } { [%csl Ga5,Rd5][%cal Ga5c7,Rd5c6] } 8... Kd7 9. Kc5 Kc7 10. Kb5 Kd6 11. Kxa5 Kxd5 12. Kb6 { [%cal Ga4a8] } *


