[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5k2/5P1p/4K3/8/8/8/7P/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.18"]
[UTCTime "22:41:30"]

{ A bishop's pawn is too close to the rook's file. The approach to this ending is different than the previous ones.

The key is where the rook's pawns are.
Both sides want to have the rook's pawn on their 2nd rank.

This position is a clear win, because white has the pawn in the 2nd rank, so the chance to choose between moving it 1 square or 2 to start with allows to create the zugzwang for Black:

... }
1. Kf6! { The only way. As the strong side, we don't want to commit the pawn too soon.
... } (1. h4 h5) (1. h3 h6 2. Kf6 h5) 1... h5 2. h3 { (of course we would play h4 against h6) } (2. Ke6 h4 3. h3) (2. Kg6 h4 3. h3) 2... h4 3. Ke6 { Zugzwang. White wins.
REMEMBER:
- This ending is always a win if the strong side has the rook pawn in the 2nd rank } *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Passed bishop pawn on same wing - triangulation"]
[Date "2019.05.19"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "Passed bishop pawn on same wing - triangulation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/nwMUnwRA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "2k5/8/p1P5/P2K4/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.19"]
[UTCTime "10:50:34"]

{ When the strong side has moved the blocked pawn (it's not on the 2nd rank), the ending is still winning if the defending side has moved it too.

This is such a position.
It introduces us to the concept of TRIANGULATION.

Triangulation is the simplest (and most frequent) case of CORRESPONDING SQUARES.

In this position, the squares in blue are corresponding squares. So are the squares in yellow. That means that the kings should fight to enter them when it's the opponent to move (same concept as the opposition). Those squares are mutual zugzwang.

White king can use triangulation to achieve this:

... } { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Yd6,Yd8] }
1. Kd4! { .
We can usually extend the concept of corresponding squares to more squares. In this case, the squares in green are also corresponding, for they allow access to both the yellow and the blue ones.
White will use e5 and d5 to triangulate Black, since Black's king has no row to go backwards.
... } { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Yd6,Yd8,Gc8,Gd5] } 1... Kd8 { .
Black just entered the yellow square, but we don't have access to the yellow square yet... We keep triangulating.
... } { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Yd6,Yd8,Gd5,Gc8] } 2. Kc4 { [%csl Bc5,Yd6,Yd8,Gd5,Gc8,Bc7] } 2... Kc8 { .
Black just entered the green square, now we do the same!
... } { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Yd6,Yd8,Gd5,Gc8] } 3. Kd5! { .
Now we're going to achieve the zugzwang.
... } { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Yd6,Yd8,Gd5,Gc8] } 3... Kc7 { [%csl Bc7,Bc5,Yd6,Yd8,Gc8,Gd5] } (3... Kd8 { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Yd6,Yd8] } 4. Kd6 Kc8 5. c7 Kb7 6. Kd7 Ka7 7. Kc6 Ka8 8. c8=Q+ Ka7 9. Qb7#) 4. Kc5 { .
CONCLUSION:
The ending with 2 blocked rook's pawns and an extra bishop's pawn on the same wing, is always won if the defending pawn has moved. } { [%csl Bc5,Bc7,Gc8,Gd5,Yd6,Yd8] } *


