[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/7p/5k2/8/5K2/8/6PP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.28"]
[UTCTime "09:11:53"]

{ This position favors White and it's worth remembering.

White wins no matter who moves. We'll see now what happens if Black moves (White has the opposition) and in the next chapter what if White moves (when reserve tempi will help).

... }
1... h6 { since waiting is not enough, Black might try this, which is very instructive: } (1... Kg6 2. g4?? (2. Kg4 { .
First step: reach h6 with the king.
... } { [%csl Bh6] } 2... Kf6 (2... Kh6 3. Kf5 Kh5 4. Kf6 Kh6 5. h3 Kh5 6. Kg7 h6 7. Kf6 Kh4 8. Kg6 h5 { [%csl Rg4][%cal Gh3g4] } 9. Kh6 Kg3 10. Kxh5 Kxg2 11. Kg4) 3. Kh5 Kg7 4. g4?? { It's worth to know why this does not win since you never know when you'll be on the defending side :-) } (4. Kg5 { .
Other moves win (like g3, h3 or h4), and De la Villa recommends g3, but I think it's easier to remember this one.
... } 4... Kf7 5. Kh6 Kg8 { .
With the pawn on h2, we win this position regardless of where the g pawn is, because we'll be able to choose h3 or h4 at the right time.
Second step: push the g pawn to g5:
... } 6. g4 { (g3 also wins, of course) } 6... Kh8 7. g5 Kg8 { .
Third step is BIRD's RULE:
When the kings occupy same-coloured squares, pawns should also occupy same-coloured squares and vice versa.
... } { [%csl Gh8] } 8. h3! (8. h4?? Kh8 9. h5 Kg8 10. g6 hxg6 11. hxg6 Kh8 12. g7+ Kg8 $10) 8... Kh8 9. h4 Kg8 10. h5 Kh8 11. g6 hxg6 12. hxg6 Kg8 13. g7) 4... h6! $10 { and the g4 pawn is a problem for White to transfer the king to f4 } 5. Kh4 Kg6 6. Kg3 h5! $10) 2... Kf6) 2. g4! { interesting to note that this position with pawns on g3 and h3 would be a draw, see chapter 30 } 2... Kg6 { Steinitz Rule: we can choose now between h3 and h4 to find the winning one: } 3. h3! Kf6 4. h4 { because we win the opposition, we can reach the critical squares for the h6 pawn: } { [%csl Bg6,Bf6,Be6] } 4... Ke6 { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } (4... h5 5. g5+ Kf7 6. Ke5! { instructive rejection of the opposition for very concrete reasons } (6. Kf5 Kg7 7. g6?? Kh6! { stalemate tricks save Black }) 6... Kg7 7. Kf5 Kf7 8. g6+ Kg7 9. Kg5) 5. Ke4 { [%csl Bg6,Bf6,Be6] } 5... Kf6 { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } 6. Kd5 { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } 6... Ke7 { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } 7. Ke5 { [%csl Bg6,Bf6,Be6] } 7... Kf7 { [%csl Be6,Bf6,Bg6] } 8. Kf5 { [%csl Bg6,Bf6,Be6] } 8... Kg7 { [%csl Ge6,Bf6,Bg6] } 9. Ke6 { [%csl Ge6,Bf6,Bg6] } 9... Kg6 { [%csl Bg6,Bf6,Ge6] } 10. h5+! { [%csl Bg6,Bf6,Ge6] } 10... Kg5 11. Kf7 Kxg4 12. Kg6 Kf4 13. Kxh6 Kf5 14. Kg7 *


