{ This is the same as before, but now we lose the opposition as White. Not a big problem, since we have reserve tempi.

As usual, g4 would be a mistake. Any other pawn move wins. To keep the ideas similar to the previous case, I would use the g pawn (although De la Villa gives h3):

... }
1. g3 Kg6 2. Kg4 Kh6 3. Kf5 Kg7 (3... Kh5 { .
This is tricky now because Black is trying to prevent us to reach h6 in the simplest way. We should know we can go up with the king:
... } 4. Kf6! Kh6 { this is very easy now: } (4... Kg4 { .
Critical position. There's only one move to win:
... } 5. h4! { .
It's not a difficult move to remember though. Our king is already reaching the critical squares of the h6 pawn, so we save our h pawn:
... } 5... Kxg3 (5... Kh5 6. Kg7 h6 7. Kh7 Kg4 8. Kxh6 Kxg3 9. Kg5) 6. h5 Kh4 7. h6 Kh5 8. Kg7 Kg5 9. Kxh7 Kf6 10. Kg8) 5. h3 Kh5 6. Kg7 h6 7. h4 Kg4 8. Kxh6 Kxg3 9. Kg5) 4. Kg5 { we reach h6 and we win as in the previous chapter, by putting pawn on g5 and following Bird's Rule } *


