[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): The floating square"]
[Date "2019.05.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board)"]
[ChapterName "The floating square"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/WjvkBos6"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/6k1/6P1/p2p3P/8/8/2K5/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.30"]
[UTCTime "15:22:44"]

{ In this position, Black's king cannot help their pawns, since it has to keep White's pawns under control. White's pawns, by the way, defend themselves. It's Black to move. Can Black save the position or even win thanks to those 2 passers?

We can apply the rule of the FLOATING SQUARE:

If a square whose 2 vertices are 2 passed pawns on the same rank (the blue square in this example) reaches the back rank, then the pawns promote without help. If not, the pawns do not promote.

Therefore, Black cannot win because the floating square is one rank away from the back rank.

... } { [%cal Bc5d5,Bc5a5,Ba4a5,Ba4a2,Bd3d2,Bd3d5,Bc2d2,Bc2a2] }
1... Kf6 (1... a4 { .
We know that Black cannot win. But is it a draw?
Well, that depends on the separation between the pawns. The rule is:
- separated by 2 files: the pawns are lost
- separated by 3 files: the pawns are not lost but they cannot advance
- separated by 1 file: the pawns can defend each other, but to win they need to provoke zugzwang
In this case, we have 2 files of separation. Therefore White wins:
... } 2. Kb2?? (2. Kc3! { If we're aware of the rule of the FLOATING SQUARE we know we should not allow d4.
... } 2... Kh6 (2... d4+ 3. Kxd4 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ra3a4,Ra3a1,Rb1a1,Rb1d1,Rd2d1,Rd2d4,Rc4d4,Rc4a4] } 3... Kh6 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Gh6h5,Gg6g7] }) (2... a3 3. Kb3 d4 4. Kxa3 d3 { [%cal Rd2d3,Rd2d1,Rd1b1,Rb1b3,Rb3d3] } 5. Kb3) 3. Kb4 d4 4. Kxa4 { and we're in the square of the d pawn } { [%cal Bc4d4,Bc4a4,Ba3a4,Ba3a1,Bb1a1,Bb1d1,Bd2d1,Bd2d4] }) 2... d4 { The FLOATING SQUARE reaches the back rank: Black wins } { [%cal Bc4d4,Bc4a4,Ba3a4,Ba3a1,Bb1a1,Bd2d1,Bd3d4,Bd3d1,Bc1d1,Bb1d1] } 3. Ka3 d3 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ga3a4,Ga3d3] }) 2. Kb3 Kg7 3. Ka4 d4 4. Kb3 Kf6 5. Kc4 a4 6. Kxd4 *


[Event "Pawn endings (more than 1 pawn on the board): Pawns separated by 3 files"]
[Date "2019.05.30"]
