[UTCDate "2019.05.30"]
[UTCTime "15:35:27"]

{ As we said, the king can hold these pawns, because the floating square didn't reach the back rank. But the king won't be able to capture any of the pawns.

... } { [%cal Bd6e6,Bd6a6,Ba5a6,Ba5a2,Bb2a2,Bb2e2,Be3e2,Be3e6] }
1. Kc4! { The king has to stay in these 3 squares (c4, c5 and c6) to control both pawns. If he goes away from them, the floating square can reach the back rank. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gc6] } (1. Kd4?? { Out of the safe squares. How does Black win? Just pushing the floating square: } { [%csl Rc6,Rc5,Rc4] } 1... a5 2. Kc4 e5 { The pawns promote without help now: } { [%cal Bd5e5,Bd5a5,Ba4a5,Ba4a1,Be4e5,Be4e1,Gd1e1,Gd1a1] } 3. Kb5 e4 4. Kc4 a4) 1... Kh8! { Kg8 also works obviously. The key for Black is not to push the pawns. This way it's just a draw. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gc6] } (1... a5?? { Trying to push the floating square does not work. } 2. Kb5 e5 3. Kxa5 { White wins } { [%cal Bd5e5,Bd5a5,Ba4a5,Ba4a1,Bb1a1,Bb1e1,Be3e1,Be3e5] } 3... e4 4. Kb4 e3 5. Kc3 e2 6. Kd2 e1=Q+ 7. Kxe1 Kg8 8. Ke2 Kh7 9. Ke3 Kg8 10. Ke4 Kh7 11. Ke5 Kg8 12. Kf6 Kh7 13. Kf7 Kh8 14. Kxg6 Kg8) (1... Kg8 2. Kc5 Kh7) 2. Kc5! { only move } { [%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gc6] } 2... Kh7 { [%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gc6] } 3. Kc4 { [%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gc6] } 3... Kh8 $10 { [%csl Gc6,Gc5,Gc4] } *


