[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/e7vtCGV5/Q9mTc9Vf"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/1p2kPp1/6P1/4K3/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.05.30"]
[UTCTime "15:47:06"]

{ As we all know a PROTECTED PASSED PAWN is a great asset in an ending. It gives many chances to win.

In this position, White has such a pawn. Therefore Black's king must protect his b pawn without leaving the square of the f5 passed pawn.

... } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Bf6f5,Bf6f8,Be8f8,Be8c8,Bc7c8,Bc7c5,Bd5c5,Bd5f5] }
1... Kd5! { [%cal Be5f5,Bf6f5,Bf6f8,Be8f8,Be8c8,Bc7c8,Bc7c5,Be5c5] } 2. Kd3 { Opposition is useless here, as White's king cannot penetrate.
... } { [%cal Bd5f5,Bd5c5,Bc6c5,Bc6c8,Bd8c8,Bd8f8,Bf7f8,Bf7f5] } 2... Ke5! { [%cal Bf6f5,Be5f5,Be5c5,Bc6c5,Bc6c8,Bd8c8,Bd8f8,Bf6f8] } (2... Kd6?? 3. Kd4 { [%cal Gd4c5,Gd4d5,Gd4e5] } (3. Ke3 { Let's triangulate to see what if is White to move in the initial position: } 3... Ke5 { [%csl Gc6,Gc5,Rf5][%cal Ge5c5,Gc5c6] } 4. Kd3 Kd5 5. Kc3 Kc5 6. Kb3 { [%csl Gd6,Gd5,Rc6] } 6... Kd5 (6... Kc6?? 7. Kb4) 7. Kb4 Kc6 $10) 3... Kc6 4. Ke5 b4 5. Kd4 b3 6. Kc3 Kd5 7. Kxb3 Kc5 8. Kc3 Kd5 9. Kd3 Ke5 10. Kc4) 3. Kc3 { [%cal Bf6f8,Be5c5,Be5f5,Bf6f5,Bc6c8,Be8c8,Be8f8,Bc6c5] } 3... Kd5 { [%cal Be5f5,Be5c5,Bc6c5,Bc6c8,Bd8c8,Bd8f8,Bf7f8,Bf7f5] } 4. Kb4 { [%cal Bd5c5,Bd5f5,Bf6f5,Bf6f8,Be8f8,Be8c8,Bc7c8,Bc7c5] } 4... Kc6! { Just in time, without leaving the square. } { [%cal Bc6c5,Bd5c5,Bd5f5,Bf6f5,Bf6f8,Bc6c8,Bd8c8,Bd8f8] } 5. Ka5 { [%cal Bc7c8,Bc7c5,Bd5c5,Bd5f5,Bf6f5,Bf6f8,Be8f8,Be8c8] } 5... Kc5 { [%cal Bc6c5,Bc6c8,Bd5c5,Bd5f5,Bf6f5,Bf6f8,Be8f8,Be8c8] } 6. f6 { forced, since Ka6 loses } { [%cal Be6f6,Be6d6,Bd7d6,Bd7d8,Be8d8,Be8f8,Bf7f8,Bf7f6] } 6... Kd6 { [%cal Be6d6,Bd7d6,Be8d8,Be8f8,Bf7f8,Bf7f6,Be6f6,Bd7d8] } 7. Kxb5 { [%cal Bd7d6,Bd7d8,Be6d6,Be6f6,Bf7f6,Bf7f8,Be8f8,Be8d8] } 7... Ke6 { [%csl Rf6] } 8. Kc5 Kxf6 9. Kd5 { .
And now White arrived at a key square of the g5 pawn and will eventually capture that pawn. We know, however, from chapter 9, that Black will draw by answering Kxg5 with Kg7 when the time comes.
CONCLUSION:
A king can defend a pawn as long as for that the king can remain inside the square of an enemy pawn. } { [%csl Bf5,Be5,Gd5] } 9... Ke7 10. Ke5 Kf7 11. Kf5 { [%csl Rg7][%cal Gf7f8,Gf7g8] } 11... Kg8 12. Kg6 Kf8 13. Kxg5 Kg7 *


