[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.26"]
[UTCTime "10:35:11"]

{ Endings with same-colour bishops arise with reasonably frequency.

When there are many pawns on the board, the technique is more or less easy (as one of them will be "the bad bishop").

But with just one pawn, we must know an essential defensive method: the rear opposition. It's not intuitive, and even distinguished players have resigned in drawn positions! }
 *


[Event "Bishop + pawn vs Bishop (same-coloured): Driving off the defending bishop"]
[Date "2019.04.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Bishop + pawn vs Bishop (same-coloured)"]
[ChapterName "Driving off the defending bishop"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xCUdoUqD/ardOujyZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "5k2/2K5/3P4/1b5B/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.04.26"]
[UTCTime "10:38:36"]

{ This is an ideal scenario for the strong side: king is near and opponent's king is not.

The winning manoeuvre consists in driving off the enemy bishop from the diagonals that control the pawn:

... } { [%cal Rb5d7] }
1. Bf3 { [%cal Gf3c6] } (1. Bg4 { Trying to trade on d7 also wins, but then the defending bishop can relocate to a different diagonal and offer some extra resistance: } 1... Ba4 2. Bd7 Bd1 3. Bc6 Bg4) 1... Be8 (1... Ke8 2. Bc6+ Bxc6 3. Kxc6 Kd8 4. d7 { [%cal Rd8e7] }) (1... Ba4 2. Bc6 Bxc6 3. Kxc6 Ke8 4. Kc7) 2. Bc6 *


