{ A peculiar way of defending: having the opposition in the rear of the pawn!

Now the driving-off manoeuvre does not work: } { [%csl Rc5] }
1. Bd7 { By the way, this is the only square available for the trade (if we achieve Bc8, black just trades bishops winning the pawn). } (1. Bh5 Bf5 2. Be2 Bh3 3. Ba6 Bg4 4. Bc8 Bxc8 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gc5d6] }) 1... Bf1 { [%csl Rc5] } 2. Bg4 { [%cal Rd6d7] } 2... Bb5 { Importantly the black king controls c6 so there's no Bf3-Bc6 winning manoeuvre.
No way to make progress for White: } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Gg4f3,Gf3c6] } 3. Bd7 (3. Be2 Ba4 { [%csl Rc5] }) 3... Be2 4. Bc6 Bg4 *


