{ Black seems to have achieved the right defensive setup, with the king in opposition in the rear of the pawn.

However an important factor gives White the victory: one of the diagonals is very short.
It's less than 4 squares long <-- rule to remember.

Let's see how White wins:

... } { [%cal Gg2a8,Gg2h1,Rb7c8,Rb7a6] }
1. Bc8 { Trying the driving-off, as usual. } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 1... Be4 2. Bb7 Bf5 (2... Bd3 3. Bf3 Ba6 { [%csl Ga6,Gb7][%cal Ga7b7,Ga7a6] } 4. Bg4! { Zugzwang!
Now we see the importance of the diagonal being short. White controls all the squares in that short diagonal with king and bishop, and Black's bishop cannot lose a tempo while keeping the diagonal. } { [%cal Rb7c8,Rb7a6] } 4... Kb5 5. Be2+) 3. Bf3 Bc8 4. Be2 { zugzwang } { [%csl Ra6,Rb7] } 4... Kb4 5. Kb8 { [%csl Rc8][%cal Ga7b8] } *


