{ [%cal Gc5f8,Gc5a3,Rg7f8,Rg7h6] }
1. Kg8! { wins exactly as in the previous chapter } (1. Ke8? { We're going to see how this does not win, to understand better the defensive method. Of course the winning move was Kg8, going with the king to control the shortest diagonal. } 1... Ke6 { rear opposition (we had time to play Kg6 or Kf5, but at the key moment when White does Be7, we will need the king on e6) } 2. Bf8 Bf4 3. Bb4 Bh6 { [%csl Rf8,Gg7,Gh6][%cal Gb4c3,Gb4d2] } 4. Bd2 { .
Nice attempt, but since White's king only controls 1 square of the short diagonal (instead of 2 like in the previous chapter), we have one extra square for our bishop:
... } (4. Bc3 { [%csl Rf8,Rg7][%cal Ge8f8,Gc3g7] } 4... Kd6 { [%cal Gh6f8] }) 4... Bg7 5. Be3 { .
Are we in zugzwang?
... } { [%csl Rf8,Rh6] } 5... Kd6! { No! Unlike the previous chapter, our bishop is not attacked so our king can move away.
However, it's important to know that Kd6 is the only move, since any other move allow White's king to make it to the other side of the pawn. } 6. Bd2 Ke6! { Again, only move.
... } 7. Bc3 Bh6 { draw }) 1... Kg6 2. Bf8 Bf4 3. Bb4 Bh6 4. Bc3 { [%csl Gg6,Gh6,Rg7][%cal Gc3g7] } *


