{ There are not many studies on this situation.

We're following the game Kurajica - Markland, Hastings 1971/72

... }
1... Kd7?! { Had Black known about the rear opposition method, he would have played Kd5! with an easy draw. } (1... Kd5 { [%cal Rf5f6,Gc3f6] } 2. Kg6 Ke4 { [%cal Gh2g3,Gg3h4,Gh4f6] }) 2. Kg6 Ke8! { There was no time already to go to the rear of the pawn.
It is still a draw, but we're going to witness a new defensive method: the frontal defence. The king wants to reach g8.
... } { [%csl Gg8][%cal Ge8g8] } 3. Bf4 { [%csl Ge8,Rf5][%cal Re8g8] } (3. Bd6 { cutting the king would not help making progress, since Black could just wai: } 3... Bd4) 3... Kf8! { this was the correct way to defend! } (3... Bd4? { .
Black failed to find the defensive method, and resigned after the next move: } 4. Bh6! { [%csl Rf8][%cal Gh6f8] } 4... Bc3 { [%csl Re8] } 5. Bg7 Bb4 6. f6 Bc5 7. f7+ { [%cal Re8e7] } 7... Kd7 8. Kh7 Ke6 9. Kg8 { [%cal Re6f5,Rf5g6] } 9... Kf5 10. Bf8 Be3 { [%cal Ge3h6] } (10... Bd4 11. Bd6) 11. Bb4 Bh6 { [%cal Gg8h7] } 12. Bc3) 4. Bh6+ Kg8! { for clarity purposes, let's see this method in the next chapter } { [%csl Rg8,Gg6] } *


