[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/1V5yy2jW/Mi6mJzlC"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2019.02.05"]
[UTCTime "22:03:08"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 { It's an important alternative and avoids the weight of theory associated with 3...Bf5. It was used by Mikhail Botvinnik in his 1961 match versus Mikhail Tal (though with a negative outcome for Botvinnik – two draws and a loss). The line was christened the "Arkell/Khenkin Variation" in the leading chess magazine New in Chess yearbook 42 in recognition of the work these two grandmasters did and the success they were having with the variation. In comparison to the French Defence, Black lacks the tempo normally spent on ...e6; however, White can only exploit this by the weakening of his own central bind with 4. dxc5 when Black has good chances of regaining the pawn } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Intro: basic ideas"]
[Date "2018.12.27"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Intro: basic ideas"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/VAW6Q107"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR/ w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.27"]
[UTCTime "21:39:47"]

{ Theoreticians tend to think that crazyhouse is a forced win for white, but the game is so complex (more than regular chess itself) that there's no human capable of handling the complex opening theory.

However, in this study I'll try to cover the basic knowledge that I want to build for myself (and still don't have), namely:

- Well known opening traps or blunders
- Typical crazyhouse tactical patterns
- Annotated games

: : : : Related links : : : :
Theoreticians discussion on theory study: --[[ https://lichess.org/forum/team-crazyhouse-chess-theoreoticians/theory-study#2 ]]-- }
 *


