[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: What are the stronger pieces?"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "What are the stronger pieces?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/wq58BLOa"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR/ w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "11:23:56"]

{ A "strong" piece to me is one that can create strong threats (it can threaten checkmate, perform a tactic, etc). They're important to me to identify because I think my brain works considering first the stronger threats/pieces when it comes to tactics.

In ZH, from my noob point of view, the "strength" of the pieces should go in this order in general:

1) Pieces out of the board
2) Pieces that can be captured
3) Pieces in the board

This observation is based on the fact that a piece out of the board has more scope than a piece already in the board since it can be placed anywhere. }
 *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Initiative is key"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Initiative is key"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/5CkfGsJQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r1b2knr/ppp1b1pp/4Pb2/3PPN2/3Q4/8/PPPP1PnP/RNB2K1R/Pqp b - - 39 20"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "11:41:20"]

{ ZH is all about checkmating.

The material helps but only to attack or defend, not to reach a technical endgame. Therefore the initiative is more important than the material.

In this position, white has no checks at all while black has some (@e2, Q@d1, etc) so black's initiative is bigger than white's. The fact that white has no checks available allows black to make a strong "quiet" move: }
20... P@f3! { The stronger pieces are those out of the board, for they can create bigger threats. The threat Q@e1 mate is huge and unstoppable. } { [%csl Gf3,Re2,Re1][%cal Gf3g2,Rf3e2,Rg2e1] } 21. Qe4 Q@d1+ 22. Qe1 Qxe1# { .
:::: credits ::::
Puzzle found at:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/Q8uR0t3U ]]-- } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Checks and captures are strong moves"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Checks and captures are strong moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/uFhSSp7c"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r2qr3/1Bp2p2/pkPp1p2/N1p4p/P2PPbn1/2P2N2/1BnpQPPP/R4K1R/B w - - 78 40"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "11:48:53"]

{ As it happens with regular chess, checks and captures are strong moves that we should consider before considering other options. They usually bring the most forcing lines.

In this example, according to the engine, the best moves are:

B@a7+ mate in 3
dxc5+ mate in 6
Bxa8 mate in 16
Nxd2 +42.7
Nc4+ +32.9

If we keep going I'm sure most of the other good moves are checks or captures.
Let's see the quickest mate now: }
40. B@a7+ { I tend to think that a check with a piece that is out of the board has to be a strong move in general. In this case, it brings a forced line: } { [%csl Ra6][%cal Ra8a6,Ge2a6] } 40... Kxa7 (40... Kxa5 41. Qxa6#) (40... Rxa7 41. Nc4#) 41. Qxa6+ Kb8 42. Qxa8# { .
Maybe we can recognize a pattern in this puzzle, I'm still not sure: placing a piece in the escape square of the opponent's king to force black in this example to undefend a6.
:::: credits ::::
Puzzle found at:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/Q8uR0t3U ]]-- } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: The forcing line"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "The forcing line"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/pox1qsxV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r1bR1bk1/ppp1P2p/4b1pq/3QPp2/2b5/2N4n/PPP2P1P/R3K3/Rnnppp b - - 73 37"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "11:57:52"]

{ I tend to think that the forcing lines are the solution to tactical puzzles 80% of the time in regular chess. And even when they're not they help to understand the forces in play. That's why I always advocate finding the most forcing lines first.

The most forcing line is the one that gives your opponent fewer options. Strong moves like checks or captures tend to lead to the most forcing lines.

I think in ZH this idea also applies, maybe even stronger, since the initiative is more important. I think this example shows it well.

The most forcing moves here are:

@d2+
N@g2+
N@f3+

for they only give white 2 possible answers (Qd2+ also gives 2 answers but you know...)

... }
37... P@d2+! { This is very forcing. Now white has only Kd1 or Qxd2. The first one is obvious mate in 1. } 38. Qxd2 { .
What are the most forcing moves now?
N@f3+
N@g2+
Qxd2+
The queen trade gives white a choice between 2 moves but the knight checks only 1 option (Kd1) so they're more forcing.
One of them (N@f3) leads to mate quicker and we can understand that the knight there helps more, since it hits d2 and removes a future choice for white to recapture the queen with the king. } (38. Kd1 Nxf2#) 38... N@f3+ 39. Kd1 { And now the pattern to checkmate should be obvious, but to be honest it turns out that the next move is also the most forcing move :-) } 39... Qxd2+ 40. Rxd2 Q@e1# { .
:::: credits ::::
Puzzle found at:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/Q8uR0t3U ]]-- } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Removing escape squares (a pattern from standard chess)"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Removing escape squares (a pattern from standard chess)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/BLzbAtB7"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/1p1b1pp1/1qn5/8/p2PQB2/2PB3P/5PP1/5RK1 w Qq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "12:18:41"]

{ This puzzle is a standard chess one to show a typical pattern in some tactics. I wanted to show it because I've seen it applies a lot in ZH tactical puzzles. }
1. Qh7+ { So far obvious, right? } 1... Kf8 { [%cal Gf8e7] } 2. Bd6+! { This is the key move. Black is forced to put a piece on e7 and block the king escape route. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Rd6e7] } 2... Ne7 (2... Re7 3. Qh8#) 3. Qh8# *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Removing escape squares (a ZH puzzle now)"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Removing escape squares (a ZH puzzle now)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/ZnIGUxb0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "1bbk3r/pp2Rp1p/3p4/2p5/2B2Q2/8/PPP2PPP/R3K2R/QPPbnnnnpp w KQ - 58 30"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "12:23:15"]

{ The most forcing moves here are:

Q@e8+, 1 answer
Q@d7+, 1 answer
@c7+, 2 answers

It turns out that Q@e8+ and @c7+ lead to the same mate in 5 so they transpose. Let's start with @c7+ since it's the topic I'm discussing. With this move we remove c7 for the king to ever use it to escape: }
30. P@c7+ Bxc7 { Now both Q@e8+ and Q@d7+ are forcing, but the first one has a couple of advantages over the queen sac on d7.
With Q@e8+:
- we attract the rook to trade it next, keeping a forcing line
- with the rook trade we'll attract the king so that Qxf7 is check and we keep the initiative
With Q@d7+:
- we force the bishop from c8 to d7, giving an additional escape possibility to the king
- the bishop will also defend e8 from d7 } 31. Q@e8+ Rxe8 32. Rxe8+ Kxe8 33. Qxf7+ Kd8 34. R@e8# { .
We've seen several patterns in one puzzle. I wanted to narrow it to the escaping squares thing, but I want to just point out the patterns I saw here that I think are common to other ZH puzzles:
- Removing an escape square
- Trading defenders so that we get to put them over the board with initiative
- Attracting with checks (both defenders to trade and the king to keep the initiative)
:::: credits ::::
Puzzle found at:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/Q8uR0t3U ]]-- } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Knight checks are very forcing"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Knight checks are very forcing"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/aIA0DnFm"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/ppp1ppbp/8/4P3/3np3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBK1B1R/PBNnpq b kq - 21 11"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "12:47:41"]

{ This is a theme also in standard chess. If we consider the different types of checks, there are some more forcing than others.

Let's remember there are 3 ways to answer a check:

1) MOVE the king
2) CAPTURE the piece that checks
3) INTERPOSE a piece

Let's do a rank of different checks strength according to the possible defences:

1) Double check (MOVE)
2) Knight check (MOVE + CAPTURE)
3) Check in square next to king (MOVE + CAPTURE)
4) Other normal checks (MOVE + CAPTURE + INTERPOSE)

This applies to both standard chess and ZH.

Let's see this example. How could we find a check with a knight that cannot be captured? Hmmmm... }
11... Q@e1+!! { Distracting the king to prepare the killing Nc2+ } { [%cal Gd4c2] } 12. Kxe1 Nxc2+ 13. Ke2 Qd3# { .
:::: credits ::::
This puzzle is from the game:
--[[ https://lichess.org/yscaWqik/black ]]-- } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: Exposed king"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Exposed king"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/0lFpNrPe"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "3rkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/1B4N1/4Ppb1/5P2/PPPN2PP/R2K3R/QPbqp b k - 19 10"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "13:23:43"]

{ In standard chess, a king is exposed when there are lines open against it so the opponent can build serious threats.

In ZH having an exposed king is a wider concept in my opinion. It's not just "lines" but also any kind of "squares" around the king, since any piece can land at any square in any moment.

In this position there are a lot of squares (in red) around white's king that can potentially be used to land a piece on them.

The e3 square is especially yummy. If only we had a knight to place there... } { [%csl Re3,Rd3,Rc3,Re2,Rf2] }
10... Rxd2+! { I missed this move in the game, but if you think about it, it should be "obvious" to the ZH player:
- Exposes the king more
- Removes defender
- Keeps initiative (it's a capture and a check)
- Grabs the knight we want for e3 or other square (f2 maybe)
It's also the most forcing move :-) } 11. Kc1 { The best attempt, but unfortunately for white there are still checks in the position. } (11. Kxd2 Q@e3+ 12. Kd1 N@f2#) (11. Ke1 Q@f2#) 11... Rxc2+! 12. Kxc2 (12. Kd1 Q@d2#) (12. Kb1 N@a3+ 13. bxa3 Q@b2#) 12... N@e3+ { Finally! } 13. Kd2 { Against any other king move, Q@c2 is mate. } 13... Q@c2+ 14. Ke1 P@f2# { .
:::: credits ::::
This puzzle is from the game:
--[[ https://lichess.org/CezKTXDl/black ]]-- } *


[Event "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero: :::: STRATEGY ::::"]
[Date "2018.12.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName ":::: STRATEGY ::::"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/OZcWzb8e"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR/ w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.12.29"]
[UTCTime "11:18:07"]

{ Some topics I'd like to explore, as they strike me as fundamentally different from regular chess:

- There are no endgames
- What pieces can be captured matter a lot when it comes to tactics
- A piece out of the board can be more "active" than a piece in the board (it has access to more squares)
- Material is not important; king safety is }
 *


