[Event "Casual Crazyhouse game"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/646wM7pa"]
[Date "2019.01.06"]
[Round "-"]
[White "pepellou"]
[Black "azuaga"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "1981"]
[BlackElo "2007"]
[TimeControl "120+3"]
[Termination "Normal"]
[Variant "Crazyhouse"]
[ECO "C23"]
[Opening "Bishop's Opening: Boi Variation"]
[StudyName "Crazyhouse: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "pepellou - azuaga"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/29NkLdaZ/EYPoehbD"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR/ w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This game was hand and brain, and the-lone-wolf was the brain. Thanks to him I learned a basic opening trap :-)

. }
1. e4 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 1... e5 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 2. Bc4 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 2... Bc5? { Considered already a mistake, because of the forcing line we played: } { [%clk 0:01:59] } (2... Nc6 { this is the way to play, and only after Nf3 you play Bc5 }) 3. Qh5 { Now both Qe7 and Qf6 lead to the forcing line we played in the game. Since the bishop on c5 is lost, it's logical that engine's main moves here are Bxf2+ and d5. } { [%clk 0:01:59] } 3... Qf6 { [%clk 0:01:54] } (3... Bxf2+ 4. Kxf2 { Black does not have enough initiative for the piece, and f7 is still a problem: } 4... P@e6 5. Qxe5 $16) (3... d5 4. Bxd5 Bxf2+ 5. Kxf2 P@e6 $16 { Compared to the immediate Bxf2+ this line wins a tempo, so it's a small improvement. However, black does not have enough compensation again. Now both Bb3 and Nf3 retain the advantage. }) 4. Qxf7+ { [%clk 0:01:56] } 4... Qxf7 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 5. Bxf7+ { [%clk 0:01:56] } 5... Kxf7 { [%clk 0:01:59] } 6. Q@d5+ { [%clk 0:01:44] } 6... B@e6 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 7. Qxc5 { The opening trap is done and according to the engine, this position is +7. } { [%clk 0:01:45] } 7... Q@g4 { [%clk 0:01:41] } 8. B@f3 { [%clk 0:01:37] } 8... Qg5 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 9. Qxc7 { [%clk 0:01:24] } 9... Na6 { [%clk 0:01:34] } 10. Qc3 { [%clk 0:01:18] } (10. Qd6 { My intuition led me against this move, which is the engine's choice, but sometimes you need to see what your opponent has out of the board. Had he had anything (pawn, bishop, knight, rook) it's true that this queen could be "tempoed". But it's not the case, and black will never play Qe7 here, so the queen is awesome on d6. }) 10... b6 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 11. P@f5 { @d5 was also interesting, I chose this to disconnect the queen at g5 from the defence of the e5 pawn. } { [%clk 0:00:52] } 11... Bxf5 { [%clk 0:01:11] } 12. exf5 { [%clk 0:00:48] } 12... P@c6 { [%clk 0:01:03] } 13. Qxe5 { [%clk 0:00:46] } 13... Bb7 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 14. Nh3 { [%clk 0:00:30] } (14. P@e6+ { First engine's choice and also my idea, but the-lone-wolf said "knight" :-) } 14... Kf8 15. B@d6+ Ne7 16. exd7 Nc5 17. Bxc5 bxc5 18. N@e6+ Kg8 19. P@f7+ Kxf7 20. Nxg5+ Kg8 21. Q@f7#) 14... Qh4 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 15. P@e6+ { [%clk 0:00:22] } 15... Kf8 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 16. B@d6+ { [%clk 0:00:13] } 16... Ne7 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 17. P@g3 { [%csl Rf7] [%clk 0:00:12] } (17. exd7 { this was mate in 6 }) 17... Qc4 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 18. Nc3 { there are already forced mates, but both the-lone-wolf and me were focused on winning or trading that queen to mate on f7 } { [%clk 0:00:11] } 18... Rd8 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 19. Be2 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 19... Qxc3 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 20. bxc3 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 20... N@d5 { [%csl Gf7] [%clk 0:00:05] } 21. Bxe7+ { the-lone-wolf said "bishop" :'-D } { [%clk 0:00:10] } (21. Q@f7#) 21... Nxe7 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 22. exd7 { the-lone-wolf said "pawn" :'-D } { [%clk 0:00:10] } (22. Q@f7#) 22... Rxd7 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 23. P@e6 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 23... B@f6 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 24. Q@f7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { [%clk 0:00:08] } 1-0


