1. e4 Nc6 { Nimzowitsch Defense } 2. d4 (2. Nf3 { Declined Variation } 2... d6 { Williams Variation } (2... Nf6 3. e5 Ng4 { El Columpio Defense } 4. d4 d6 5. h3 Nh6 6. Bb5 { El Columpio Defense/Pin Variation } (6. exd6 { El Columpio Defense/Exchange Variation }) (6. e6 { El Columpio Defense/El Columpio Gambit })) (2... e6 { Franco-Nimzowitsch Variation }) (2... f5 { Lean Variation } 3. exf5 { Lean Variation/Colorado Counter Accepted } (3. e5 d6 4. exd6 (4. Bb5))) (2... e5 { Transposition: C44 King's Knight Opening/Normal Variation. Avoid this move if you don't want a transposition to one of the more regular openings. } 3. Bb5 { Transposition: C60 Ruy Lopez } (3. Bc4 { Transposition: C50 Italian Game }) (3. d4 { Transposition: C44 Scotch Game })) (2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5) (2... g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. h3 Nf6) 3. d4 Nf6) (2. Nc3 g6 { Pirc Connection } (2... e6 { French Connection }) (2... Nf6 3. d4 e5 { Breyer Variation }) (2... e5 { Transposition: C25 Vienna Game/Max Lange Defense })) (2. Bb5 { Pseudo-Spanish Variation }) (2. b4 { Wheeler Gambit } 2... Nxb4 3. d4 d5 4. Ba3 Nc6?! (4... e5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Bxf8 Kxf8 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Qxd5 Qxd5 9. exd5 Nf6 10. c4 Bf5 11. Nd2 $17) 5. Bb5 dxe4 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. f3?!) (2. f4 d5 (2... e5) 3. e5 (3. exd5) 3... Nh6 (3... d4) (3... Bf5) 4. d4 Bf5 5. Be2 (5. Nf3) (5. c3)) 2... d5 { Scandinavian Variation. This is really the only good move here. All the other options are pretty bad for Black, so bad that I won't even cover them in this study. Do not allow White to play d5! It's that simple. } (2... d6?! $14 { Mikenas Variation } 3. d5 (3. Nc3 e5 4. d5 Nce7 5. Bc4 f5 6. f4 fxe4 7. Nxe4 Bf5 $16) 3... Nb8 4. c4 Nf6) (2... f6? $16 { Neo-Mongoloid Defense } 3. Nf3 e6 4. Bd3 g6 5. d5 Ne5 6. Nxe5 fxe5 $16) (2... a6?! $14 { Woodchuck Variation } 3. Nf3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 $16) (2... e6?! $14 3. Nf3 (3. Nc3 f5 4. exf5 Nf6 { Franco-Hiva Gambit 2 }) (3. c3 d5 4. e5 f6 5. Nf3 Nge7 $14) 3... f5 4. exf5 Nf6 { Franco-Hiva Gambit 1 }) (2... e5?! { Kennedy Variation } 3. d5 { Kennedy Variation/Linksspringer Variation } (3. dxe5 Nxe5 (3... Bc5 { Kennedy Variation/Bielefelder Gambit }) (3... f6 { Kennedy Variation/Hammer Gambit }) (3... Qh4 { Kennedy Variation/Herford Gambit }) (3... d6 { Kennedy Variation/de Smet Gambit }) 4. Nf3 { Kennedy Variation/Paulsen Attack } (4. Nc3 { Kennedy Variation/Keres Attack }) (4. f4 Nc6 { Kennedy Variation/Riemann Defense } (4... Ng6 { Kennedy Variation/Main Line })) 4... Nxf3+ 5. Qxf3 Qf6 6. Qg3) 3... Nce7 { Every normal move is good for White now. } (3... Nb8) (3... Nb4) 4. Nf3 Ng6 5. h4 h5 6. Bg5 { [%cal Rf3e5] } 6... Nf6 (6... f6 7. Be3)) 3. Nc3 $10 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation } (3. Be3 $15 { Hornung Gambit. Not good for White, but playable. } 3... dxe4 { Just take the pawn and have a good game. } 4. d5 { This gives White an interesting initiative in the center and a good lead in development. Still, it's questionable if this is compensation enough. The engine doesn't like it, but what does that mean in a Blitz game? } 4... Ne5 5. Nc3 (5. Qd4 { [%cal Rd4e4,Rd4e5] } 5... Ng4 6. Bc4 (6. Qxe4? N8f6 7. Qa4+ Bd7 8. Bb5 Nxe3 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. fxe3 Nxd5 { [%cal Gd5e3] } 12. Ke2)) (5. Bb5+) 5... Nf6 6. Bd4 Ng6) (3. exd5 Nb4 { Scandinavian Variation/Aachen Gambit } (3... Qxd5 { Scandinavian Variation/Exchange Variation } 4. Nc3 { Scandinavian Variation/Exchange Variation/Marshall Gambit })) (3. e5 { Scandinavian Variation/Advance Variation. This is the line you'll most likely encounter in Blitz and Rapid games. } 3... Bf5 (3... a6) 4. c3 (4. Nf3 e6 5. c3) 4... f6 5. f4 Nh6 6. Nf3) 3... dxe4 (3... a6 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation/Brandics Gambit }) (3... g6 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation/Erben Gambit }) (3... e5 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation/Heinola-Deppe Gambit }) (3... Nf6 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation/Vehre Variation }) 4. d5 Ne5 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation/Nimzowitsch Gambit } (4... Nb8 5. f3 { Scandinavian Variation/Bogoljubow Variation/Richter Gambit }) *


[Event "Nimzowitsch Defense: Scandinavian/Advance: 2…d5 3.e5"]
[Date "2019.01.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B00"]
[Opening "Nimzowitsch Defense: Scandinavian Variation, Advance Variation"]
[StudyName "Nimzowitsch Defense"]
[ChapterName "Scandinavian/Advance: 2…d5 3.e5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/76ojF0DX/HXTH7Fqp"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.06"]
[UTCTime "19:51:56"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { Scandinavian Variation/Advance Variation. This is the line you'll most likely encounter in Blitz and Rapid games. } 3... Bf5 (3... f6 { This is an unusual very early attempt to open the center. I don't recommend it.
White should always respond to f6 with either f4 or Bb5. You will also see Nf3 or exf6 in Blitz games quite often. } { [%cal Gc6e5,Gf6e5] } 4. f4 { Main move. } (4. Bb5 { Note how open the king is for attacks. } { [%cal Rh5f7] } 4... fxe5 5. dxe5 (5. Qh5+ g6 6. Qxe5 { [%cal Re5h8] } 6... Nf6 7. Bf4 { [%cal Re5c7] } 7... Bf5 { [%cal Gf5c2] } (7... Bd7 { Laine, Jari - Koistinen, Kari, 1/2-1/2, MT-Oesterman (FIN), 2016, https://lichess.org/j44SQAl9 }) 8. c3 Bg7 9. Qxc7 Qxc7 10. Bxc7 O-O $14 { White is only slightly better here, despite being a pawn up. Black's lead in development is almost enough compensation. }) 5... e6 6. Nf3) (4. Nf3) (4. exf6) 4... Bf5 5. c3 { Best move. Rare. } (5. Be2 { Second best move. Very rare. } 5... Nb4 { This is quite aggressive. It forces White to place their knight on the awkward a3 square. } { [%cal Gf5c2,Gb4c2] } 6. Na3 e6 7. c3 { [%cal Rc3b4] } 7... Nc6 { Retreat. } { [%cal Gf8a3] } 8. Nc2 Be4 $14 { [%cal Ge4g2] }) (5. Nf3 { Third-best and mostly played move, online and offline. }) 5... Nh6!? { This knight wants to go to f5, its natural home in this variation. } 6. Nf3 e6 7. Be2 Bg6 $14 8. Nbd2 Be7) 4. c3 e6 (4... a6) (4... f6) 5. Bd3 { Most common move. The light-suare bishop is the "bad bishop" for black; trading it off isn't bad at all. But it should be done while developing pieces! So … } (5. Be2 { Best move according to SF, but rarely played. }) 5... Nge7 { White can now either play aggressive (Bg5) or develop the pieces first (Ne2). } { [%cal Ge7f5] } 6. Ne2 (6. Bg5 { Now the knight doesn't protect the bishop anymore. Black has to react. There are three ways: step out of the pin (Qd7), attack White's good bishp (h6), or exchange the light-squared bishops (Bxd3). } 6... Qd7 { The rather quiet response. White can now either keep it quiet (Ne2 or Be2), or go into active play (Bxe7). } (6... h6 7. Bxf5 { Black doesn't want doubled pawns in the center, so they have to take White's "bad bishop". The consequence is that Black cannot castle short anymore. Or it's a bad idea at least. } 7... hxg5 8. Bg4 Nf5 { Again the key move Nf5. } 9. Nd2 { Now the compact center is a problem for Black's development. e7 is a square for the Queen, the bishop and the knight on c6. But only one of them can go there. The engine wants Qe7 and castle long, but I prefer the second best move f6 to open the center. } 9... f6 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gf6e5] } 10. Qe2 { [%cal Re2e5,Rd4e5] } (10. b4 { An interesting and very sharp alternative: attack the knight, so it cannot protect e5 anymore. }) 10... fxe5 11. dxe5 { Note that e6 is unprotected now. This is the case in many lines of this variation as soon as the center opens up. Keep an eye on that! } { [%cal Rg4e6] } 11... Qe7 $10) (6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 h6 { This avoids the doubled-pawn problem that we have seen in the 6…h6 line. } 8. Be3 Nf5 { And again Nf5. } 9. Ne2 Nb8 $10 { Looks weird, but makes c5 possible, and that knight can go to d7 later and support f6. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Gb8d7,Gf7f6,Bd7e5,Bd7f6] }) 7. Be2 (7. Ne2 h6 8. Bxe7 { White's pawns are mostly on black squares now, so this is the "bad bishop" that can be traded off. } 8... Nxe7 $10 { Plans for Black: exchange the light-square bishops, play c5 to open the pawn chain and with that the center. } { [%cal Gf5d3,Gc7c5] } (8... Bxe7 { Mrugala, Artur - Dunne, Alex, 1-0, CM.1998.0.00055, 2017, https://lichess.org/VWzGHqNI })) (7. Bxe7 Nxe7 8. Nf3 (8. Na3 { Postl, Rostislav - Sedlácek, Tomás, 1/2-1/2, CZE/Cup/f25 (CZE), 2012, https://lichess.org/4u6cwbZy }) 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nf5 { Now Black has an active knight on f5 (as in the line 7.Be2) }) 7... h6 8. Be3 { Now that White has decided not to trade off the light-squared bishops, Black wants to get a knight to f5. Which means the bishop has to move. } 8... Be4 { Provoke f3, or exchange the bishop for a knight. } 9. f3 Bh7 10. f4 Nf5 $10 { Further plans for Black: g5, long castling, Be7, and an attack on the king side. } { [%cal Gg7g5,Ge8c8,Gf8e7] }) 6... Qd7 (6... Nb8!? { Interesting suggestion by the engine. The idea is to push c5 quickly. }) 7. Na3!? { Engine suggestion. That knight will go to c2 } (7. O-O) 7... f6 { Open the center immediately. } 8. f4 g6 *


