1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Bc5 { This is an offbeat but playable alternative, as played (for example) by former world champion José Raúl Capablanca against Ilya Kan at Moscow 1936. } 3. Bc4 (3. Nf3 d6 (3... Nc6 { transposing to the Three Knights Game } 4. Nxe5! Nxe5 5. d4 Bd6 6. dxe5 Bxe5 7. Bd3 { leads to a large advantage for White }) 4. d4 (4. Na4 Nd7 5. d3 Ngf6 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Nxc5 Nxc5 9. Ne1 Ne6 10. c3 d5 { is about even }) 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Bg5 (6. Be2 d5 7. e5 Ne4 8. O-O Nxc3 { leads to equality }) 6... h6 7. Bh4 O-O 8. Nb3 { and now De Firmian gives: } 8... Bb4 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 g5! 12. Bg3 Nxe4 { when Black's "chances are at least equal" }) (3. f4 d6 { leads to the King's Gambit Declined } { [%cal Gg1f3,Gf1c4] }) 3... Nf6 (3... Nc6) (3... d6) *


[Event "RacingKings: from zero to hero: Intro: basic ideas"]
[Date "2019.01.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Racing Kings"]
[ECO "?"]
