[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/smcFoj9R/VoemEPjQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/krbnNBRK/qrbnNBRQ w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "10:38:29"]

{ Theoreticians tend to think that Racing Kings is a draw with perfect play, but the game is complex enough for a human rich play. Engines tend to confirm this point.

Since the games are usually short, opening theory is really useful and many times we can solve the game to a forced win or draw.

Tactics are tricky to understand at the beginning because the "no check" rule can be slightly antinatural. Most tactical patterns are related to the endgame, i.e., to the fight to stop the other king or advancing the own, rather than to winning material.

: : : : Related links : : : :

Results of high depth analysis of RK by engine:
--[[ https://lichess.org/forum/team-racing-kings-chess-theoreticians/high-depth-analysis-of-popular-rk-openings ]]--

Beginners first steps:
--[[ https://lichess.org/forum/team-racing-kings-chess-theoreticians/the-beginners-first-steps ]]--

A few ideas on strategy:
--[[ https://lichess.org/forum/team-racing-kings-chess-theoreticians/racing-kings-strategy#2 ]]-- }
 *


