[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "10:57:51"]

{ There are mainly 4 ways to open the game for white in the first move:

- Nxc2, the only legal capture
- Kg3, a king push
- Kh3, the other king push
- Bd4, an annoying pin

Without exploring too many lines, let's try to have a quick glance at each one of them.

::::[ Other moves ]:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

There are other moves, such as Nd4 or Nf4 that are playable, but not good, and others, such as Rg4 that are bad. We're going to cover them in further chapters. }
 *


[Event "RacingKings: from zero to hero: 1. Nxc2: intro"]
[Date "2019.01.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Racing Kings"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "RacingKings: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "1. Nxc2: intro"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/smcFoj9R/FPe6JHQW"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/krbnNBRK/qrbnNBRQ w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "11:02:07"]

1. Nxc2 { .
This is a very forcing move since we capture a piece. Black is forced to recapture, either on c2 or on f2.
.
. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Gc2a1] } 1... Nxf2 { .
This would be a logical copy-cat move for black to do. Now both queens are hanging. Let's have a quick look at the normal simplifying line:
. } { [%csl Ra1,Rh1][%cal Rc2a1,Gf2h1] } (1... Rxc2 { This is the only alternative, we would be a piece down otherwise. }) 2. Rxf2 Rxc2 3. Kh3 Kb3 { .
Kings would start running and we would enter a normal RK "middlegame".
Both sides have lost one of their bishops, which will affect how the remaining bishop can help to cut the other king, but in general, with all rooks and queens still on the board, the game remains very open.
.
::::[ more info on this line ]:::::::::::::::::::::::::::
While we don't analyse it more in depth, have a look at chapters 9-14 in:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/7qOrZwG6 ]]-- } *


[Event "RacingKings: from zero to hero: 1. Kg3: intro"]
[Date "2019.01.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Racing Kings"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "RacingKings: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "1. Kg3: intro"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/smcFoj9R/NlSVdAKd"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/krbnNBRK/qrbnNBRQ w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "11:02:14"]

1. Kg3 { .
This king move keeps Nxf1 forbidden while it advances the king. There are many approaches for black and for white from this point, but white is basically saying "I'm going to start running with my king already".
A common idea (but not the only one) is to run to the a1-h8 diagonal. We'll see this idea in this example line:
. } 1... Nxf2 { .
Let's attack the queen, why not?
. } 2. Kf4!? { .
It's not the best move but it shows how powerful it is to have an active king. According to Stockfish black must take the queen to draw, which gives white an extra tempo with the king:
. } 2... Nxh1 3. Ke5! { .
Because of the "no checks allowed" rule, the rook on b2 cannot move. Therefore it's really hard for black to move their heavy pieces to stop the white king.
Let's show one of the "in extremis" drawing lines:
. } { [%csl Rb2,Rb1,Ra1][%cal Ge5f6,Gf6g7,Gg7h8] } 3... Kb3 4. Kf6 Qa7 { [%csl Rf6,Re7,Rf7,Rg7][%cal Ga7g7,Be7g7,Bg7e7] } 5. Rg7 { [%csl Ra7][%cal Gg7a7] } 5... Ka4 { [%csl Ga7][%cal Ga4a7,Rg7a7] } 6. Re7 { [%csl Be7][%cal Gf6f7,Gf6g7,Ra7e7] } 6... Rb8 { [%csl Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8][%cal Bh8e8,Gb8h8,Be8h8] } 7. Nxc2 Nxf1 8. Kf7 Qa8 9. Rg6 Ka5 10. Rb7! { .
Despite the queen advantage, neither side will be able to make progress with their kings, although the game is still open.
.
::::[ more info on this line ]:::::::::::::::::::::::::::
While we don't analyse it more in depth, have a look at chapters 38-45 in:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/7qOrZwG6 ]]-- } *


[Event "RacingKings: from zero to hero: 1. Kh3: intro"]
[Date "2019.01.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Racing Kings"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "RacingKings: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "1. Kh3: intro"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/smcFoj9R/FiaDeLgt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/krbnNBRK/qrbnNBRQ w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "11:02:28"]

1. Kh3 { .
This king push also states "I'm going to run". The difference with Kg3 is that we keep our g rook available to develop, and we prevent Nxf2.
The game can continue with Be4, Kb3 or Ka3, but let's take the chance to show a common mistake:
. } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Rd1f2,Gh3f2] } 1... Nxf1? { .
This was tempting, since it's a capture that now is available, but this leads to a force win for white!
. } 2. Nxc2 { .
Threatens the queen so Rxc2 is forced:
. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Gc2a1] } 2... Rxc2 3. Bd4 { .
Threatens the queen again. The best moves according to SF are sacrificing the queen (Rxe2, Nde3, ...) which shows how bad this is for black. Let's try to save the queen:
. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Gd4a1] } 3... Bb2 4. Kg4! { .
Initiative!
By the time the black queen and rooks try to stop the white king, this will be very advanced and the white rooks already ready to help. A sample line:
. } { [%cal Gg4h5,Gh5h6,Gh6h7] } 4... Rc7 5. Bxb2 Qxb2 6. Kh5 Qb6 7. Rg7 { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gg7c7,Gg1g6,Gh5h6,Gh6h7,Gh7h8] } 7... Ka3 8. Rxc7 Qxc7 9. Kh6 Rb8 10. Rg7 Qc2 { [%cal Rc2h7] } 11. Qc6 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Rc2c6,Gh6c6] } 11... Kb3 { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gb3c2,Rc6c2] } 12. Rf7 { [%cal Gh6g7,Gf7f8] } 12... Nde3 13. Kg7 { .
White wins in 3 moves.
.
::::[ more info on this line ]:::::::::::::::::::::::::::
While we don't analyse it more in depth, have a look at chapters 46-52 in:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/7qOrZwG6 ]]-- } { [%cal Gf7f8] } *


