[Date "2019.01.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Racing Kings"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "RacingKings: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "1. Bd4: intro"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/smcFoj9R/Ezsnnvvc"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/krbnNBRK/qrbnNBRQ w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "11:02:33"]

1. Bd4 { .
This is a really annoying pin. Now the best move for black is the copy-cat Be4.
But let's see what happens if we try the "obvious" Ka3 defending our rook:
. } 1... Ka3? { [%csl Gb2][%cal Rd4b2,Ga3b2] } 2. Nxc1 { [%csl Rd2][%cal Gg2d2] } 2... Rxc1 3. Rxd2 { .
And this is terrible for black:
- piece down
- b2 rook still pinned
- cannot pin back now with Be4
.
::::[ more info on this line ]:::::::::::::::::::::::::::
While we don't analyse it more in depth, have a look at chapters 15-24 in:
--[[ https://lichess.org/study/7qOrZwG6 ]]-- } *


