[Event "RacingKings: from zero to hero: Value of the pieces"]
[Date "2019.01.04"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Racing Kings"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "RacingKings: from zero to hero"]
[ChapterName "Value of the pieces"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/smcFoj9R/HOSdsWCz"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pepellou"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/krbnNBRK/qrbnNBRQ w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.04"]
[UTCTime "10:38:03"]

{ According to --[[ https://lichess.org/forum/team-racing-kings-chess-theoreticians/first-engine-analysis-results ]]-- the value of the pieces for RK should be:

Queen .... 7
Rook ....... 5
Bishop .... 3
Knight ..... 3

It makes sense to say that the queen is the most powerful piece, but the rooks are almost as powerful as the queen.

In standard chess, the rooks achieve their maximum potential in the endgame. In RK they're playing since move 1, so they are highly important pieces.
.
.

::::[ Note on value of the king ]::::::::::::::::::::::

The king in RK has the ability to create initiative by threatening to advance further.

In the aforementioned study, they attribute a one rank advance of the king a value of 4. This kind of "concept" reminds me of the standard chess concept that a pawn in the 7th rank (as long as it survives) is worth a rook (5 pts).

According to --[[ https://lichess.org/forum/team-racing-kings-chess-theoreticians/racing-kings-strategy#2 ]]-- a 2 ranks advantage of one king to the other is likely winning (for equal material). }
 *


